<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> County Stadium To Host Last Opener </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Hall of Famer Warren Spahn, who welcomed Brew  
City to the big leagues in 1953 when he started the Milwaukee 
Braves' first game at County Stadium, will be the first to say 
goodbye to the venerable ballpark. 
</P>
<P>
	With Miller Park more than half completed and literally on the  
horizon, Spahn will throw out the ceremonial first pitch Friday 
before the Brewers face the Chicago Cubs in their last home opener 
at County Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	The forecast, which will be rendered moot next year under a  
retractable roof, calls for temperatures in the 30s with snow 
flurries. 
</P>
<P>
	Not everybody will be happy when the wrecking ball smashes the  
46-year-old stadium that was baseball's masterpiece when it opened, 
luring the Braves from Boston in the game's first franchise 
relocation. 
</P>
<P>
	``They will take a piece of my heart with them when they tear  
down this place,'' home run king Hank Aaron said. 
</P>
<P>
	And he's not alone.  
</P>
<P>
	Author Gregg Hoffmann said that as he began writing and  
researching ``Down in the Valley,'' an upcoming book on County 
Stadium, he came to realize that stadiums ``can take on almost 
human qualities. A spirit develops in it. The facility takes on its 
own personality, based in large part on the people and great events 
within it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Like all of us humans, County Stadium has aged,'' Hoffmann  
said. ``It is in the last stage of its life. But, what a life it 
has had. What wonderful memories it has given all of us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Before bolting to Atlanta following the 1965 season, the Braves  
never had a losing season in Milwaukee, and brought the city a 
World Series trophy in 1957. 
</P>
<P>
	``I threw the first pitch in the first game, and from that time  
on, it was a love affair between the people of Milwaukee and the 
Braves,'' Spahn said during a news conference Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	They drew 2 million fans four straight seasons, but they  
abandoned Wisconsin for the South, and in 1970, Bud Selig led a 
group of investors that purchased the Seattle Pilots out of 
bankruptcy court. 
</P>
<P>
	When the announcement was made that baseball was returning to  
Milwaukee, hundreds of fans arrived at the ballpark and sat in the 
stands, looking longingly across the diamond where dreams would be 
born and dashed once more. 
</P>
<P>
	Milwaukee was major league again.  
</P>
<P>
	The Brewers won the AL pennant in 1982 but lost the World Series  
to St. Louis in seven games. 
</P>
<P>
	The Green Bay Packers split their home games between Lambeau  
Field and County Stadium until 1994, when quarterback Brett Favre 
bid farewell to Milwaukee with a last-second touchdown that lifted 
the Packers over the Falcons. Take that, Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	But Brewers fans have had little to cheer about lately as the  
gap widened between the game's haves and have-nots. They nearly 
lost the team until a last-minute vote in the Wisconsin Legislature 
assured financing for the new stadium in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	There were historic times: Paul Molitor's 39-game hitting  
streak, Robin Yount's 3,000th hit, heck, even Nolan Ryan's 300th 
win and Mark McGwire's and Sammy Sosa's home runs in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	And there were the wild and wacky times, like Tony Phillips  
asking to be taken out of a game so he could meet a heckler behind 
the stands and beat him up, or the 1997 opener, when thousands of 
giveaway baseballs ended up on the field thanks to inebriated fans 
who nearly forced the Brewers to forfeit. 
</P>
<P>
	There weren't many pennant races, but the Brewers had the  
sausage races and a number of food-related promotions 
</P>
<P>
	There were sea gulls that interrupted games, floods that turned  
County Stadium into swimming pools. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, there were the zany characters. Probably the most notable  
was Johnny Logan, a shortstop for the Braves who used to start the 
fights that Eddie Mathews finished. Logan also was known for 
keeping the clubhouse loose, both during his playing days and 
afterward in his frequent visits. 
</P>
<P>
	One time, after someone said a newspaper's reporting of 0 hits  
for the game was a typographical error, Logan retorted: ``The hell 
it was. It was a clean base hit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``There are a ton of memories here,'' said Aaron, who began his  
storied career in Milwaukee. ``I'm really going to miss this 
place.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
