<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	House Nears Approval on 2000 Budget  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congress today moved to the brink of approving  
a $1.74 trillion budget for fiscal 2000 that Republicans hope will 
sharpen their image as tax cutters and as a party that has moved 
beyond President Clinton's impeachment. The Senate neared final 
approval of the blueprint this afternoon, a day after the House 
passed it by a near party-line 220-208 vote. The measure maps a 
10-year tax cut of at least $778 billion. Passage today would mark 
only the second time Congress has completed the measure on time 
since setting the April 15 deadline in 1987. 

</P>
<P>
	Cohen: Prospect of Casualties High  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Signaling that the NATO air campaign in  
Yugoslavia could stretch into summer, the Clinton administration 
said today the prospect for American casualties is ``very real and 
high,'' and U.S. officials expressed regret for an accidental NATO 
attack on a refugee convoy. ``We do try to reduce the risks to 
innocent human beings,'' Defense Secretary William Cohen told the 
Senate Armed Services Committee. Cohen and Gen. Henry H. Shelton, 
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, said using ground troops is 
not under consideration. ``The reason that we have gone forward as 
we have with an air campaign is that there was not a consensus in 
the NATO alliance to do anything but this,'' Cohen said. 

</P>
<P>
	6 Hurt in Mormon Library Shooting  
</P>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- A gunman opened fire at the Mormon  
church's Family History Library today, wounding at least five 
people before he was shot by police. Police Sgt. Ken Hanson said 
the gunman fired a small-caliber handgun, and the wounded included 
a police officer. Two people in critical condition were transported 
to LDS Hospital. The library is directly across the street from 
Temple Square, site of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day 
Saints' Salt Lake Temple and Tabernacle. 

</P>
<P>
	Bush Campaign Collects $7.6 Million  
</P>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Republican Gov. George W. Bush reported  
today that he has collected $7.6 million during the first 28 days 
of his presidential exploratory campaign, without holding a 
fund-raising event. Bush spent $854,000, leaving $6.75 million in 
the bank, according to his report to the Federal Election 
Commission. ``I am humbled by the tremendous support from people 
across the country,'' Bush said. 

</P>
<P>
	Man Arrested for Fake News Report  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- An employee of California-based PairGain  
Technologies Inc. was arrested today on federal charges of 
fabricating a Bloomberg news service report and posting it on the 
Internet, driving up the company's stock. The FBI arrested Gary 
Dale Hoke, 25, at his Raleigh, N.C., home on charges of securities 
fraud for allegedly disseminating false information about the 
company, whose stock is publicly traded, the U.S. attorney's office 
in Los Angeles said. Hoke was arraigned in North Carolina and 
released on $50,000 bond. Securities fraud is punishable by 10 
years in prison and a $1 million fine. 

</P>
<P>
	Chinese Cops Seal Grave Site  
</P>
<P>
	COMMUNIST YOUTH CITY, China (AP) -- Chinese police kept close  
watch on dissidents and a sensitive grave site today to prevent 
public commemorations of the 10th anniversary of the start of 
Tiananmen Square democracy protests. For two hours this morning, 
police closed off the grave site in southern China of former 
Communist Party leader Hu Yaobang, who was ousted as party chief 
for being too liberal. His death April 15, 1989, started the 
protests that brought over a million people to Beijing's Tiananmen 
Square and ended seven weeks later with the military assault that 
killed hundreds. 

</P>
<P>
	Netanyahu Backs New Settlements  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has promised  
Jewish settlers he won't dismantle 30 new settlements being 
established in the West Bank, Israeli army radio said today. The 
promise is reportedly in exchange for support in the May 17 
elections. In a statement issued in response, Netanyahu did not 
refer to whether he was trading votes for settlements. However, he 
said Israel and the United States have differed over settlement 
policy and that he placed Israeli interests ahead of friendship 
with the United States. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Down 18, Nasdaq Down 48  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 2 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were  
down 18.87 points at 10,392.79. On the NYSE, advancers led 
decliners 1,624-1,291. The Nasdaq was down 48.52 at 2,458.76 

</P>
<P>
	Gretzky Promises Decision by Sunday  
</P>
<P>
	RYE, N.Y. (AP) -- If Wayne Gretzky does decide to retire,  
tonight's game in Ottawa will be his last in his native land. The 
game against the Senators will be broadcast nationally in Canada 
and as many as 200 journalists are expected. Gretzky, 38, promises 
he won't keep everyone hanging. He said he'll decide by Sunday 
whether to end his 20-year NHL career. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
