<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Deutsche Telekom To Sell More Stock </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BONN, Germany (AP) -- German telecommunications company Deutsche  
Telekom said today it plans to make another share offering by the 
end of June, its second under a privatization begun in late 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement, coupled with its report that its earnings were  
unchanged in the first quarter, sent Telekom's shares down 3.7 
percent in early trading in Frankfurt. 
</P>
<P>
	Company chairman Ron Sommer said the share offering would boost  
the company's capital by up to 10 percent although he did not 
disclose how many shares would be issued. 
</P>
<P>
	The money would be used to make Telekom more competitive.  
</P>
<P>
	Telekom earned 1.04 billion marks, or $575 million, in the first  
quarter, uinchanged from a year ago. It cited increased competition 
after full liberalization of Germany's telecommunications market on 
Jan. 1, 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The German government, which had owned all of Telekom, sold  
about a 25 percent stake in the company in the November 1996 
initial public offering. The sale brought Telekom about 20 billion 
marks, or $11 billion. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
