<DOCNO> APW19990415.0008 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 16:54:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gators' Players Agent Investigated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- University of Florida police are  
investigating a sports agent who represents three high-profile 
Gators in this year's NFL draft, a sports publication said. 
</P>
<P>
	Street and Smith's Sports Business Journal reported that campus  
police have included William ``Tank'' Black in their investigation 
of on-campus agent activity. 
</P>
<P>
	Black represents linebackers Jevon Kearse and Mike Peterson and  
defensive lineman Reggie McGrew. All are expected to be selected in 
this weekend's draft, with Kearse going early in the first round. 
</P>
<P>
	The Charlotte, N.C.-based publication said campus police are  
investigating whether Black violated Florida's strict agent laws in 
recruiting and signing several players over the past two years. 
</P>
<P>
	In March, university police charged Michael Joseph McDonald with  
one count of unlicensed athletic agent activity. They accused him 
of funneling money to former Florida players Tim Beauchamp and Dock 
Pollard. Both players were dismissed from the team in December. 
</P>
<P>
	Police spokeswoman Stacy Badics said Thursday the investigation  
was ongoing and the department would not release names of anyone 
involved. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sports Business Journal, in its April 12 issue, reported  
that investigator Darren Baxley confirmed Black was part of the 
investigation. The publication said police have interviewed 
students, other agents and school officials concerning Black. 
</P>
<P>
	Black told the The Orlando Sentinel he welcomed the probe.  
</P>
<P>
	``There's nothing there,'' he said. ``I'm sure they're just  
doing their job and checking'' into the allegations. 
</P>
<P>
	``As far as I'm aware, it's the same investigation that's been  
going on for two months,'' Florida athletic director Jeremy Foley 
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
