<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Rise in Early Trading / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Buying by institutional investors boosted the  
dollar against the yen early Friday. Japanese share prices opened 
higher. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 119.06 yen in early trading, up 0.26 yen from  
late Thursday in Tokyo and above its level of 118.83 yen in New 
York. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nikkei Stock Average rose 27.23 points, or 0.16 percent, to  
16,754.31 in the first 30 minutes of trading. On Thursday, the 
average closed down 37.60 points, or 0.22 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	On the foreign exchange market, the U.S. currency was slightly  
higher as Japanese institutional investors actively bought dollars, 
analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	The ongoing warfare in Kosovo, as well as whispers of political  
uncertainty in Russia, also supported the dollar, often seen as a 
safe haven in times of international unrest. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, Tokyo share prices opened higher, boosted  
by heavy buying at foreign brokerage houses, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	A gain in U.S. stock prices may also have helped.  
</P>
<P>
	In New York, the Dow rose 51.06 points -- or 0.5 percent -- to  
close at 10,462.72, topping Wednesday's record of 10,411.66. 
</P>
<P>
	A big early gainer in Tokyo was Honda Motor. Its share prices  
soared after the Nihon Keizai business daily reported Friday that 
the Japanese automaker will build a new plant in the U.S. or Canada 
by 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
exchange's first section was up 2.44 points, or 0.18 percent, to 
1,340.37. The TOPIX closed down 5.42 points, or 0.40 percent, the 
day before. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 127.44 yen, below  
its level of 128.27 yen late Thursday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the 10-year Japanese government bond slipped to  
1.570 percent from its close of 1.575 percent Thursday, pushing its 
price up to 102.01 yen from 101.97 yen. 

</P>
</TEXT>
