<DOCNO> APW19990415.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 23:11:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Montoya Off to Solid Start in CART </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONG BEACH, Calif. (AP) -- Juan Montoya, who came to Champ Car  
racing this year with a big reputation, is still champing at the 
bit after his first two CART races. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, the Colombian driver, who won last year's European  
Formula 3000 championship, has finished a respectable 10th and 13th 
in CART FedEx Series events. 
</P>
<P>
	But Montoya, who replaced two-time series champion Alex Zanardi  
-- driving in Formula One this season -- was also the center of a 
controversial incident last weekend in Motegi, Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	The 23-year-old racer caused a crash that took both his  
Reynard-Honda and Michael Andretti's Swift-Ford into the wall 
during a practice session for last Sunday's race. Tempers flared 
briefly as Andretti, the winningest active driver in the series, 
chastised the youngster for an arrogant attitude and team owners 
Carl Haas and Chip Ganassi momentarily faced off. 
</P>
<P>
	The owners had a conciliatory drink later that day, and the  
drivers stayed away from each other on and off the track the rest 
of the weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was last week,'' Ganassi said. ``It happened and it's  
over. Juan is learning new things every day and we're all just 
thinking about the future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After the first two oval events of his Champ Car career, Montoya  
will try his hand at a temporary street circuit in Sunday's Toyota 
Grand Prix of Long Beach. 
</P>
<P>
	``Being a rookie, I'm still realistic about my chances,''  
Montoya said. ``At the same time, I know I have the ability. 
</P>
<P>
	``Although I'm not confident in my ability on ovals, I'm very  
confident on road courses, and I'm anxious for the chance to show 
it. It's tough for me not to get excited about the possibility of 
winning at Long Beach and continuing our streak here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He was referring to the fact Target-Chip Ganassi Racing drivers  
have won the last three Long Beach races, with current teammate 
Jimmy Vasser taking the 1996 event and Zanardi the last two. 
</P>
<P>
	Actually, part of the Long Beach course will be new to everyone,  
not just the rookies. 
</P>
<P>
	With constant changes in the downtown area because of new  
buildings going up, the temporary street circuit has gone through 
multiple changes in the 25 years since the event was first run. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest changes have lengthened the course from 1.57 miles  
last April to its current 1.85-mile configuration that includes 
four new turns around the Long Beach Aquarium and a longer front 
straightaway. 
</P>
<P>
	Vasser said, ``Nobody gets a chance to test on a temporary  
circuit like Long Beach, so we're all in the same boat. We'll all 
see it for the first time Friday morning when practice starts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brian Herta, the pole-winner and race runner-up last year, said,  
``The first order of business Friday will be to test the new part 
of the circuit and see if the setup from last year is still valid. 
Computer simulations can indicate a lot of the information we need 
to gather, but computers can't show you the bumps and the slippery 
patches on the track.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Montoya is counting on computers to help him get off to a good  
start. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just hope the course is similar to the Long Beach Grand Prix  
on the Microsoft CART World Series video game I used to play,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ganassi is not worried about his first-year driver.  
</P>
<P>
	``Any rookie would be nervous in his situation,'' Ganassi said.  
``But Juan has handled it extremely well. Jimmy has talked to him 
about the race and what to expect, so I think we have two drivers 
capable of winning the race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Vasser, seventh in the season standings after finishes of fourth  
and 12th, trails leader Greg Moore by 21 points. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not a very superstitious person, but I have noticed that  
the driver who has won at Long Beach the past three years has gone 
on to win the championship,'' Vasser said. ``I don't think there's 
a direct correlation but, just in case, I'm making every effort to 
win this race.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
