<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> How Many Strikes Does Straw Get? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Even if he didn't set out looking for trouble, trouble never had  
to look very far to find Darryl Strawberry. And when he realized 
just how low he had sunk one more time, Strawberry begged the cops 
to help him save his job. 
</P>
<P>
	That's the maddening thing about guys like him. The rules are so  
simple in the games that they learn to play so well. Between the 
lines, it's always been three strikes and you're out -- no mercy, no 
appeal. It's only when they step outside, into the real world, that 
they want to be treated differently. 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry has gone from wrecking machine to wreck, from  
sympathetic figure to pathetic one and back again so many times 
that it's become difficult to keep count. But according to police, 
soon after his arrest on charges of cocaine possession and 
soliciting a prostitute, Strawberry kept pleading with them to bend 
the rules. 
</P>
<P>
	In the spare, cold language of the report accompanying  
Strawberry's arrest, Tampa Police Sgt. Marc J. Hamlin wrote, ``He 
asked several times, if there was anything that we could do to 
change this situation, because this was going to ruin his career.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Charges of violence against several companions, failure to pay  
child support, charges of federal income-tax evasion, bouts with 
alcoholism and substance abuse, even the colon cancer that was 
diagnosed last October -- somehow none of them, or even all of them 
combined, could sidetrack Strawberry's career. 
</P>
<P>
	And it wasn't just talent that saved him, either. It certainly  
played a part in convincing ballclubs to take a chance on him more 
than once. But there was something noble about Strawberry, too, 
something that went beyond bravado and talent, that made his 
teammates and managers and most of all, Yankee boss George 
Steinbrenner, protective of him to a fault. 
</P>
<P>
	It might have been the way he refused, at age 37, to quit trying  
to make his way back to the big leagues. In the New York clubhouse, 
where the last few episodes of Strawberry's comeback battle played 
out like some kind of cautionary tale, the news was devastating. In 
2 1/2 years there, he had become a leader. 
</P>
<P>
	One of his youngest admirers, shortstop Derek Jeter, likened  
Strawberry to ``a big brother.'' One of his oldest friends, pitcher 
David Cone said, ``I'm the least objective person about Darryl. I 
love the guy. It's just an awful situation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Manager Joe Torre wouldn't talk about it. Don Zimmer, who's  
filling in while Torre recovers from his own fight with cancer, 
said, ``I hope it's a mistake,'' even though he knew better. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet, no one should have been surprised. And that's another  
maddening thing about guys like Strawberry. 
</P>
<P>
	The most charming ones usually make good liars. They get so  
good, so practiced at both sinning and covering up that they get to 
the point where even they can't tell the difference. The thing that 
disappointed his teammates the most was that Strawberry seemed so 
close to joining them in New York. They must be asking themselves 
instead how he climbed so close to the edge without even one of 
them having a clue. 
</P>
<P>
	The only question that matters now, of course, is what will  
Steinbrenner do? He made it clear he was running out of patience in 
February when Strawberry failed to show up for an autograph session 
and then was forced to publicly apologize. 
</P>
<P>
	The Boss was attending a funeral Thursday in Cleveland and has  
yet to comment on what's next. Because Strawberry is not on the 
Yankees' 40-man roster, it's not clear whether disciplinary action 
will be handed out by the major or minor leagues. Still, the only 
opinion that counts at the moment is George's. 
</P>
<P>
	After all he's done for Strawberry, nobody could blame  
Steinbrenner if he simply walked away. 
</P>
<P>
	That must have been the player's greatest fear while he sat in  
the police station late Wednesday night, the reason he made that 
desperate plea over and over to the police. 
</P>
<P>
	He knows he may have run out of chances and the courage to make  
it back one more time himself. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Litke is a sports columnist for The Associated Press. Write  
to him at: jlitke(at)ap.org. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
