<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Vajpayee Struggles To Retain Power </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- India's prime minister insisted Thursday  
that he has enough support to stay in power even after his biggest 
ally deserted him and vowed to topple his government. 
</P>
<P>
	Just two days before his government is to face a confidence vote  
in Parliament that could lead to his ouster, Prime Minister Atal 
Bihari Vajpayee appeared self-assured as he strode to his chair 
Thursday, accepting greetings from opposition members. 
</P>
<P>
	``What kind of government will come in my place, and who will  
lead it?'' he told lawmakers, reminding those who are wavering 
about the potential political chaos that could ensue from his 
government's downfall. 
</P>
<P>
	Sharad Pawar, speaker of the main opposition Congress Party,  
responded by blaming the government for India's deteriorating 
economy, the increasing attacks on the Christians and the 
stepped-up arms race with Pakistan. 
</P>
<P>
	Just minutes before, Pakistan tested its second nuclear-capable  
missile in two days, in response to a similar missile test by India 
on Sunday. Both countries conducted underground nuclear explosions 
last May, taking their armed rivalry to a new level. 
</P>
<P>
	The crisis in the ruling coalition was triggered by Jayaram  
Jayalalitha, leader of a group known by its Tamil acronym AIADMK, 
withdrew her 18 lawmakers Wednesday from the ruling coalition. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our entire attention and energies are devoted to ensuring the  
fall of this government,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, Jayalalitha met with Congress Party head Sonia  
Gandhi to discuss new power-sharing arrangements. Jayalalitha said 
Congress had not decided what course of action it would take. 
</P>
<P>
	Gandhi's group has only 140 lawmakers and is wary of seeking  
support from socialists who have attacked Gandhi's policies or her 
Italian ancestry or who are otherwise reluctant to support her. 
</P>
<P>
	Gandhi has held no office of power and emerged as a power center  
by virtue of being a member of the Gandhi dynasty. Three of India's 
prime ministers belonged to the Gandhi family: Jawaharlal Nehru, 
his daughter Indira Gandhi and grandson Rajiv Gandhi. She is 
Rajiv's widow. 
</P>
<P>
	To remain in power, Vajpayee needs a simple majority of  
lawmakers who are present in the legislature and who vote. His 
Bharatiya Janata Party is banking on disarray among opposition 
groups, each with its own plan and regional compulsion. 
</P>
<P>
	If no group is able to form a government, new elections will be  
called, four years ahead of schedule. India's last two elections 
gave no single party a clear majority to come to power on its own. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
