<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Investment Bank DLJ Profits Drop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- After most of Wall Street's investment banks  
reported surprisingly strong profits, Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette 
Inc. disappointed investors Thursday with a 9 percent drop in 
profits and flat revenues for the first quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette posted net income of $122 million,  
or 84 cents a share, beating analysts' average estimates, but below 
the $134 million, or $1 a share, earned in the first quarter of 
1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem: a decline in the market for new high-risk bonds.  
That hurt DLJ, the No. 1 underwriter of high-yield bonds. During 
the quarter, underwriting revenues sank 16 percent to $257 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors reacted quickly to the news, sending DLJ's shares down  
$7.93 3/4, or nearly 9 percent, to $85.06 1/4 on the New York Stock 
Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Total revenues of $1.5 billion were basically unchanged from the  
first quarter last year. Excluding interest expenses, revenues were 
$1.1 billion, up slightly from the year-ago period. 
</P>
<P>
	DLJ did benefit from the surging stock market. Commissions from  
trading stocks and bonds rose more than 40 percent during the first 
quarter to a record $281 million, while trading revenues increased 
46 percent to $174 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York-based investment bank, which has been expanding  
both in the United States and overseas, saw its income from fees 
rise 12 percent to $287 million in the period. 
</P>
<P>
	Net interest income declined 37 percent to $121 million.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990415.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 10:05:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Girl's Conviction in Death Reversed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- An appeals court today reversed the  
conviction of a girl who prosecutors say killed a toddler when she 
was 11, ruling that her statements to police may have been obtained 
illegally. 
</P>
<P>
	Lacresha Murray, now 14, was originally charged with capital  
murder making her the youngest person in Texas to face such a 
charge. After two trials, she was eventually convicted of injury to 
a child and sentenced to 25 years for the beating death of 
2-year-old Jayla Belton. 
</P>
<P>
	The 3rd District Court of Appeals however remanded the case back  
to juvenile court. 
</P>
<P>
	Her lawyers had argued that Lacresha was unlawfully tried twice  
for the same crime and that a statement she gave police was the 
result of an illegal interrogation. 
</P>
<P>
	The court agreed that the interrogation may have been illegal.  
</P>
<P>
	``When we consider the totality of the of the circumstances  
surrounding appellant's interview, it is clear that appellant's 
statements, in whatever form, were obtained in violation of the ... 
Family Code,'' the court said. 
</P>
<P>
	``At a minimum, we cannot say that appellant's statements were  
not the product of fright and despair.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors in the case did not immediately return phone calls  
for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Keith Hampton, the teen's attorney, said the next move is up to  
the prosecutor, who may seek a rehearing before the appellate 
court, take it to the Supreme Court or retry the case. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am going to assume that they're going to retry her a third  
time,'' he said. Lacresha will remain at a Texas Youth Commission 
facility in Corsicana unless prosecutors drop the charges, Hampton 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jayla died on May 24, 1996, of massive internal injuries after  
spending the day in the home Lacresha shared with her grandparents 
and five brothers and sisters. The family often baby-sat for Jayla 
and other children. 
</P>
<P>
	After being placed in a children's shelter, Lacresha was  
questioned by two police detectives. She denied killing Jayla but 
admitted she may have dropped and kicked the toddler. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said the girl was read her rights and agreed to talk to  
them. Lacresha's lawyers say police coerced her testimony. They 
also said police never should have interrogated an 11-year-old 
without notifying her parents or taking her before a judge. 
</P>
<P>
	The jury in her first trial found Lacresha guilty of criminally  
negligent homicide and injury to a child, sentencing her to 20 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	But a second trial was ordered because District Judge John Dietz  
later decided that justice had not been served. The second jury 
found Lacresha guilty of injury to a child and sentenced her to 25 
years, which she is serving at a Texas Youth Commission facility in 
Corsicana. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the people championing the girl's case has been columnist  
Bob Herbert of The New York Times, who has written several columns 
arguing that the supposed facts of the case don't add up. Herbert 
suggested that another relative might have beaten the child. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was no legitimate evidence against her, just a  
`confession' that even prosecutors have acknowledged would not have 
accounted for the injuries that killed Jayla,'' Herbert wrote in 
November. 
</P>
<P>
	Other critics say District Attorney Ronnie Earle sought a  
conviction to help his re-election campaign or was biased against 
Lacresha because she is black. Earle is white. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
