<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Strong storms pushed across the Gulf Coast early today, bringing  
damaging winds and rain to Mississippi and Arkansas. Rain and 
thunderstorms dominated the Midwest and much of the East. 
</P>
<P>
	Heavy rain fell in Kansas and Missouri early today, and wind  
gusts up to 50 mph were common across the Plains. 
</P>
<P>
	By tonight, light snow was possible in parts of Nebraska and  
South Dakota. Up to 6 inches of snow were possible in Wyoming, 
Colorado and New Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	Mostly clear and mild conditions were expected across the West.  
</P>
<P>
	Rain was forecast over the Great Lakes and Northeast by tonight,  
with thunderstorms stretching into the Southeast and Gulf Coast, 
which was pummeled with high winds late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Only scattered rain was forecast for parts of Georgia and  
Florida, which have struggled with dry conditions and fires in 
recent weeks. A blaze in Georgia's Okefenokee National Wildlife 
Refuge has grown to 1,700 acres. 
</P>
<P>
	Highs today were forecast to reach the 30s and 40s in the  
northern Plains and Rockies; the 50s and 60s over the Great Lakes, 
Northeast and New England; and the 70s and 80s in the Southeast and 
West. 
</P>
<P>
	The highest temperature reported in the continental United  
States on Wednesday was 99 degrees at McAllen, Texas. The low was 
12 at Yellowstone National Park, Wyo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
