<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Evidence of New Solar System Found </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- For the first time, there is clear evidence  
that a solar system other than our own exists, researchers said 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Three huge planets are spinning around the star Upsilon  
Andromedae 44 light years from Earth in our Milky Way galaxy, San 
Francisco State University researchers said at a news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Their presence indicates that many of the Milky Way's 200  
billion stars are likely to have planetary systems. 
</P>
<P>
	``It implies that planets can form more easily than we ever  
imagined, and that our Milky Way is teeming with planetary 
systems,'' said Debra Fischer, one of the researchers. 
</P>
<P>
	The researchers began their search for planets 12 years ago.  
They and their colleagues are responsible for finding 14 of the 20 
planets known to exist outside the Earth's solar system. 
</P>
<P>
	However, those planets were single bodies surrounding a star.  
This is the first time multiple planets around a star have been 
found. 
</P>
<P>
	The innermost of the three planets, spotted in 1996, has at  
least 75 percent of the mass of Jupiter and is very close to its 
sun, orbiting once every 4.6 days. Jupiter is the largest planet in 
the solar system, 318 times the size of Earth. 
</P>
<P>
	The middle planet is twice Jupiter's mass and orbits the star  
every 242 days from a location about as far as Venus from the sun. 
The outer planet has the mass of four Jupiters and orbits its star 
every 3 1/2 to 4 years. It is more than twice as far from its star as 
Earth is from the sun. 
</P>
<P>
	Earthlike planets are unlikely to be found in such systems, the  
scientists said, because the forces generated by huge Jupiterlike 
planets moving in elliptical rather than circular orbits would kick 
smaller planets out into oblivion. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now we have a multiple system, maybe a Rosetta stone to help  
us understand a lot of these weird planets we're finding,'' said R. 
Paul Butler by telephone from the Anglo-Australian Observatory in 
Epping, Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rosetta stone is an ancient inscription in three languages  
that allowed scientists to decipher Egyptian hieroglyphics. 
</P>
<P>
	Upsilon Andromedae is easily visible with the naked eye,  
although it is currently behind the sun and will not be seen until 
June. 
</P>
<P>
	The planets were discovered using a method that measures their  
gravitational pull on their star, not by direct observation. 
Planets' gravity tugs on their stars, causing them to wobble 
slightly. By examining the star's ultraviolet light transmissions, 
astronomers can calculate back-and-forth shifts in the ultraviolet 
wavelengths. A larger wobble indicates the orbiting planet is 
large. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am mystified at how such a system of Jupiterlike planets  
might have been created,'' said Geoffrey Marcy, professor of 
physics and astronomy at San Francisco State. 
</P>
<P>
	``This will shake up the theory of planet formation.''  
</P>
<P>
	Alex Wolszczan, an astronomy professor at Penn State University,  
called the discovery an important step toward understanding the 
cosmos. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has been anticipated and awaited by the scientific  
community. It's nice to see it's finally happened,'' he said. 
``What I get right away from this particular discovery is that it 
emphasizes even more how different those systems are from our 
own.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990415.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 05:25:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brighter Days for Johnson &AMP; Johnson </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- For Johnson &AMP; Johnson investors, it's no more  
tears. 
</P>
<P>
	After a year of setbacks and months of stagnant share prices,  
stock in the health care conglomerate has risen 25 percent since 
December amid a suddenly brighter outlook. 
</P>
<P>
	Two upcoming products have helped buoy that sentiment. J&AMP;J hopes  
to soon get U.S. approval for Benecol, a margarine that lowers 
cholesterol, and Aciphex, a new ulcer and heartburn drug. 
</P>
<P>
	Wall Street analysts are also betting the company known best as  
the maker of Tylenol, Band-Aids and Johnson's Baby Shampoo, is due 
for a change in fortunes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not a whole lot is left that could go wrong,'' said Scott  
Wilken, an analyst with Warburg Dillon Read. 
</P>
<P>
	Historically, J&AMP;J's diversity of health care products has made  
it one of Wall Street's most stellar performers and a leader among 
the 30 stocks in the Dow Jones industrial average. 
</P>
<P>
	But the year just past has been painful, punctuated in December  
when the company announced it was eliminating 4,100 jobs, or 4 
percent of its workforce, and taking an $800 million restructuring 
charge in hopes of improving productivity. 
</P>
<P>
	``1998 was one of the more difficult years that Johnson &AMP;  
Johnson has encountered in a long time,'' Ralph Larsen, J&AMP;J's 
chairman and chief executive officer, told shareholders in the 
annual report released this month. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the disappointments:  
</P>
<P>
	--Two of J&AMP;J's promising drugs, one for stroke and one for  
diabetes, failed late in the research process. 
</P>
<P>
	--The Food and Drug Administration delayed approval of Benecol  
due to a dispute with the company over the level of testing needed 
to ensure its safety. 
</P>
<P>
	-- J&AMP;J lost a costly battle with the biotech company Amgen over  
the rights to an experimental anemia drug designed to help cancer 
patients withstand chemotherapy. 
</P>
<P>
	--Sales of J&AMP;J 's coronary stent-- a tiny metal scaffolding that  
props open cholesterol-clogged arteries -- tumbled after competitors 
introduced newer versions. Just, four years ago, J&AMP;J had virtually 
owned the stent market. 
</P>
<P>
	Though J&AMP;J is still most known for consumer goods such as  
Tylenol, consumer products today only comprise about 29 percent of 
sales and less than 10 percent of profits. Prescription drugs last 
year made up 36 percent of sales and 69 percent of profits. 
</P>
<P>
	Some analysts believe J&AMP;J might be better off concentrating  
solely on drugs to better compete with rivals like Merck &AMP;Co. and 
Pfizer. But J&AMP;J officials say their strength remains a diverse 
product line, which also includes contact lens, surgical products 
and other medical devices. 
</P>
<P>
	And J&AMP;J has decided to stay the course.  
</P>
<P>
	``Life is not a series of mountain tops to mountain tops,'' said  
Robert Darretta, J&AMP;J vice president of finance. ``Every 
organization has periods above and below average rate of growth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1998, the company's earnings grew by 11 percent not including  
the special charge. That disappointed investors used historical 
growth rates around 15 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Analyst Charlene Lu of Prudential Securities said she became  
more bullish to J&AMP;J after hearing Larsen acknowledge that the 
company had made mistakes and outlined a plan to fix J&AMP;J 
weaknesses. 
</P>
<P>
	J&AMP;J is adding 800 pharmaceutical sales representatives in  
anticipation of its two new drugs, Lu said. The company also plans 
to buy products from other companies or acquire firms with 
potentially profitable drugs. Further, the company told analysts 
that it will kill drugs earlier in their pipelines if they lack 
promise to avoid embarrassments like last year, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We see management stepping up to the plate,'' Lu said.  
</P>
<P>
	Shares of J&AMP;J have risen from $76 to $98 since December. On  
Wednesday shares fell $3.93 3/4 to $94.68 3/4 on the New York Stock 
Exchange amid widespread profit taking of drug company stocks on 
Wall Street. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990415.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 06:18:30 </DATE_TIME>
