<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court May Hear Immigration Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Gov. Gray Davis has asked a federal  
appeals court to mediate a dispute over a controversial ballot 
measure that seeks to cut off schooling to illegal immigrants. 
</P>
<P>
	Approved by 59 percent of voters in 1994, Proposition 187 has  
not been implemented. A federal court found the measure 
unconstitutional last year, but then-Gov. Pete Wilson appealed that 
decision. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis, a Democrat who opposes Prop 187, could have thwarted the  
initiative by refusing to pursue Wilson's appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, Davis asked the U.S. 9th Circuit Court of Appeal's  
mediation panel to resolve the proposition. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm a governor, not a judge. I have taken an oath to enforce  
all the laws of our state and our nation, regardless of my personal 
views on those laws,'' Davis said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The initiative would exclude illegal immigrants from public  
schools and eliminate non-emergency health and welfare services for 
which they remain eligible. It also would require public agencies 
and employees to report suspected illegal immigrants. 
</P>
<P>
	The question of whether to continue the appeal has developed  
into the most significant political quandary of the early months of 
Davis' administration. 
</P>
<P>
	He was faced with the dilemma of pursing the appeal and angering  
Hispanics and other opponents to the proposition, or letting the 
appeal drop and anger those who voted in favor of the measure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990415.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 07:54:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ford Earnings Jump 20 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Ford Motor Co. said today that strong sales in  
North America helped it post a 20 percent increase in operating 
earnings during the first quarter, beating Wall Street's 
expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	The world's No. 2 automaker reported operating earnings of $1.81  
billion, or $1.46 a share, in the first three months of the year 
compared with $1.51 billion, or $1.22 a share, in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford's results were higher than Wall Street analysts'  
expectations. The average estimate of 10 analysts recently surveyed 
by First Call Corp. was for operating earnings of $1.39 a share. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford stock was up 2 percent, or by $1.25, at $64 a share this  
morning on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	The operating earnings exclude onetime gains that boosted the  
net income figures in both the latest period and in the first 
quarter a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales totaled $38 billion, compared with $36.6 billion a year  
ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Ford team is energized and focused, and we were determined  
to make a fast start in 1999,'' said Jacques Nasser, president and 
CEO. 
</P>
<P>
	``The best news for our consumers and shareholders is that the  
transformation of Ford is really just getting started.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ford said it was the 12th straight quarter that operating  
earnings had improved. Analyst John Casesa of Schroder &AMP; Co. said 
Ford benefitted from an excellent product mix in North America, 
with a wide array of popular light trucks and increased retail 
sales over less-profitable fleet sales. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they could run the whole company like they run North  
America, you wouldn't be able to stop these guys,'' Casesa said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford reported a one-time, after-tax gain of $165 million from  
the sale of its share in the AutoEuropa joint venture in Portugal 
with Germany's Volkswagen AG. In last year's first quarter, Ford 
had a one-time, noncash gain of $15.9 billion from the spinoff of 
The Associates, in addition to $177 million in earnings from the 
former financial subsidiary. 
</P>
<P>
	With the one-time factors included, Ford's earnings totaled  
$1.98 billion, or $1.60 a share in the first quarter, compared with 
$17.65 billion, or $14.23 a share a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford's car business earned $1.49 billion, up 20 percent from a  
year ago, with surging sales in North America making up for a 
break-even quarter in Europe and losses in South America. Worldwide 
sales were $32 billion, up 10 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In North America, Ford said it earned $1.59 billion, up 57  
percent from a year ago. Ford said its high-profit truck sales were 
up 20 percent in the quarter, and car sales were up 10 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Without the AutoEuropa gain, Ford said it would have broke even  
in Europe for the quarter, compared with earnings of $230 million a 
year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford's losses in South America grew substantially, rising to  
$165 million from $45 million a year ago. The company says it does 
not expect to earn a profit there this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The losses were about twice what Casesa was estimating; he  
called the result ``disastrous.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Visteon, Ford's parts subsidiary, said it earned $208 million in  
the first quarter, up 10 percent from $189 million a year ago. 
Revenue for the quarter was $4.8 billion, up 9 percent from $4.4 
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford Credit said it earned $300 million, up 8 percent from $278  
million last quarter. Hertz said it earned $49 million, up 14 
percent from a year ago. Ford's share of the company's earnings was 
$40 million. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990415.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 16:23:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that moved substantially or traded  
heavily Thursday on the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq Stock 
Market. 

</P>
<P>
                               *NYSE    	

</P>
<P>
 *Schwab Corp. fell 14 1/4 to 124.    	
</P>
<P>
	The company reported strong first-quarter earnings, but its  
stock fell as investors took profits in previously high-flying 
online brokerage shares. 

</P>
<P>
 *Friedman Billings Ramsey Group Inc. rose 4 5/8 to 14 7/16.    	
</P>
<P>
	The company sees its new online investment bank and brokerage  
arm, fbr.com, becoming its signature service over the next 10 
years. 

</P>
<P>
 *Storage Technology fell 7 1/16 to 19.  
</P>
<P>
 *EMC fell 9 3/16 to 115 7/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Louisville, Colo.-based Storage Tech said it wouldn't meet Wall  
Street's first-quarter earnings expectations. Spokesman David Reid 
said it couldn't make enough of its 9840 tape drives and that 
customers haven't accepted its virtual storage manager products as 
quickly as management had hoped. The announcement pulled down 
competitor EMC's shares as well. 

</P>
<P>
 *Motorola fell 2 15/16 to 80 3/16.    	
</P>
<P>
	Standard &AMP; Poor's Corp. placed the company's debt on a list for  
possible downgrade on Wednesday, saying that while Motorola had 
made progress in its program to cut costs and improve profits, 
``economic conditions remain challenging in several'' of its 
markets. Salomon Smith Barney and Hambricht &AMP; Quist both upgraded 
Motorola's stock, but Brown Brothers Harriman and Josephthal both 
downgraded it. 

</P>
<P>
 *Mattel rose 2 5/16 to 28 1/4.    	
</P>
<P>
	The El Segundo, Calif.-based toymaker plans to cut 10 percent of  
its workforce and close some plants as part of an ongoing effort to 
revive slumping sales and profits. The company also reported a 
smaller-than-expected first-quarter loss of 7 cents per share, for 
the quarter ended March 31, compared to a net profit of $12.7 
million for the same period last year. 

</P>
<P>
                              *NASDAQ   	

</P>
<P>
 *Altera Corp. rose 9 5/16 to 76 5/8.    	
</P>
<P>
	The San Jose, Calif., computer chipmaker's first-quarter net  
earnings rose to 48 cents a share from 40 cents, amid double-digit 
gains in North America, Japan and Asia. Volpe Brown and Alex. Brown 
both upgraded the stock. 

</P>
<P>
 *Gibson Greetings Inc. fell 3 11/16 to 6 3/8.    	
</P>
<P>
	The greeting-card maker said it expects to report a loss between  
22 cents and 25 cents a diluted share for the first quarter, with 
analysts' projected earnings of 36 cents. Gibson said it expects 
quarterly sales to be about $82 million, down from $101.7 million a 
year ago. 

</P>
<P>
 *Walker Interactive fell 1 to 3.    	
</P>
<P>
	The company said it expects to report a loss of between 7 cents  
and 9 cents a share, compared with a net gain of 7 cents a year 
ago. Walker said that because of uncertainty surrounding Year 2000 
issues in the software industry, it foresees slower- than-expected 
growth for 1999. In addition, the company cited an unanticipated 
delay in signing a $2.6 million software license agreement. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
