<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that are moving substantially or trading  
heavily today on the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq Stock 
Market. 

</P>
<P>
                               *NYSE    	

</P>
<P>
 *Schwab Corp. fell 14 1/4 to 124.    	
</P>
<P>
	The company reported strong first-quarter earnings, but its  
stock fell as investors took profits in previously high-flying 
online brokerage shares. 

</P>
<P>
 *Friedman Billings Ramsey Group Inc. rose 4 5/8 to 14 7/16.    	
</P>
<P>
	The company sees its new online investment bank and brokerage  
arm, fbr.com, becoming its signature service over the next 10 
years. 

</P>
<P>
 *Storage Technology fell 7 1/16 to 19.  
</P>
<P>
 *EMC fell 9 3/16 to 155 7/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Louisville, Colo.-based Storage Tech said it wouldn't meet Wall  
Street's first-quarter earnings expectations. Spokesman David Reid 
said it couldn't make enough of its 9840 tape drives and that 
customers haven't accepted its virtual storage manager products as 
quickly as management had hoped. The announcement pulled down 
competitor EMC's shares as well. 

</P>
<P>
 *Motorola fell 2 15/16 to 80 3/16.    	
</P>
<P>
	Standard &AMP; Poor's Corp. placed the company's debt on a list for  
possible downgrade on Wednesday, saying that while Motorola had 
made progress in its program to cut costs and improve profits, 
``economic conditions remain challenging in several'' of its 
markets. Salomon Smith Barney and Hambricht &AMP; Quist both upgraded 
Motorola's stock, but Brown Brothers Harriman and Josephthal both 
downgraded it. 

</P>
<P>
                              *NASDAQ   	

</P>
<P>
 *Altera Corp. rose 9 5/16 to 76 5/8.    	
</P>
<P>
	The San Jose, Calif., computer chipmaker's first-quarter net  
earnings rose to 48 cents a share from 40 cents, amid double-digit 
gains in North America, Japan and Asia. Volpe Brown and Alex. Brown 
both upgraded the stock. 

</P>
<P>
 *Winland Electronics Inc. rose 5/8 to 2 15/16.    	
</P>
<P>
	First-quarter earnings rose to 15 cents a share from 6 cents a  
year ago at the Mankato, Minn., firm, which manufactures custom 
electronic control products and systems. 

</P>
<P>
 *Gibson Greetings Inc. fell 3 11/16 to 6 3/8.    	
</P>
<P>
	The greeting-card maker said it expects to report a loss between  
22 cents and 25 cents a diluted share for the first quarter, with 
analysts' projected earnings of 36 cents. Gibson said it expects 
quarterly sales to be about $82 million, down from $101.7 million a 
year ago. 

</P>
<P>
 *Walker Interactive fell 1 to 3.    	
</P>
<P>
	The company said it expects to report a loss of between 7 cents  
and 9 cents a share, compared with a net gain of 7 cents a year 
ago. Walker said that because of uncertainty surrounding Year 2000 
issues in the software industry, it foresees slower- than-expected 
growth for 1999. In addition, the company cited an unanticipated 
delay in signing a $2.6 million software license agreement. 


</P>
