<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 00:24:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Panel Lashes IOC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Though he wasn't there, Juan Antonio Samaranch  
no doubt got the message loud and clear: Members of the U.S. 
Congress aren't impressed with the pace of reform on the 
international Olympic scene, and they are prepared to do something 
about it. 
</P>
<P>
	International Olympic Committee members Anita DeFrantz and James  
Easton, standing in for IOC president Samaranch, were grilled for 
45 minutes Wednesday at a hearing of the Senate Commerce Committee, 
which criticized a ``culture of corruption'' that has left the 
rings tarnished and the games defamed. 
</P>
<P>
	``There were expressed doubts about our intentions,'' DeFrantz  
said with understatement when asked how she would describe the 
hearing to Samaranch. ``When you're out to do a task, you like to 
have encouragement. Maybe we should use these doubts as 
encouragement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chairman Sen. John McCain pulled no punches as he examined the  
worst corruption case in the 105-year-old modern Olympic movement 
and said he would consider a second hearing. He also said he would 
immediately introduce a bill to place the IOC under the Federal 
Corrupt Practices Act, which forbids bribery of foreign officials. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, the White House said it hoped to have an answer  
soon on a USOC request to make the IOC a public body under 
international anti-corruption statutes. 
</P>
<P>
	``This issue is about the integrity of an institution and the  
public trust,'' McCain said. 
</P>
<P>
	Two committee members called for Samaranch to resign, and McCain  
seemed perturbed that the IOC president declined an invitation to 
attend. 
</P>
<P>
	In the end, however, the Arizona Republican appeared ready to  
take the go-slow approach advocated by former Senate Majority 
Leader George Mitchell, who suggested Congress give the IOC until 
the end of the year to adopt reforms before enacting any 
tax-exemption-related legislation that could hurt the international 
body financially. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think they have to be given the chance to make the  
recommended changes on their own,'' said Mitchell, chairman of an 
oversight panel that made several recommendations for IOC reform. 
</P>
<P>
	But DeFrantz, an IOC vice president hand-picked to testify by  
Samaranch, and Easton categorically endorsed just one of the 
Mitchell report's four main recommendations, on term limits for IOC 
members who now are essentially elected for life. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's very interesting,'' McCain said with a raised eyebrow  
during the hearing. He later said he was ``very concerned about 
their lack of enthusiasm for the Mitchell commission 
recommendations,'' and that the IOC should carry the ``burden of 
proof'' if it fails to adopt them. 
</P>
<P>
	Several senators said the IOC was dragging its feet on reforms.  
While he has created a 24-member task force to restructure the IOC, 
Samaranch has announced six members so far, they noted. 
</P>
<P>
	Another member of the Mitchell's committee, Ken Duberstein,  
noted that the U.S. Olympic Committee has already adopted the 
suggested reforms. 
</P>
<P>
	``The USOC is following doctor's orders,'' Duberstein said.  
``The IOC prefers to get a second opinion to its liking. They want 
to take two aspirin and call the doctor in the morning -- sometime 
in the year 2000.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McCain spent large amounts of time trying to pin down the IOC  
members on financial matters, asking DeFrantz three times how much 
money the Olympic committee spent on direct support of athletes. 
DeFrantz finally said she did not know. 
</P>
<P>
	Similarly, McCain repeatedly asked how much the Lausanne,  
Switzerland-based IOC made each year. DeFrantz said the committee's 
budget was $40 million but did not know annual income figures, and 
finally had to ask for time to produce a written report, again 
being chastised by the chairman. 
</P>
<P>
	News that the IOC kept the minutes of its general assemblies  
secret for 10 years, and those of executive board sessions locked 
up for 20 years, brought expressions of disbelief from McCain. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sixty percent of the IOC's income is from American  
corporations and donations and the American people deserve to know 
what happens in those meetings,'' he told DeFrantz. 
</P>
<P>
	While McCain's attacks on the IOC and Samaranch weren't exactly  
subtle, other Senators were even more blunt. Democrats Ernest 
Hollings of South Carolina and Richard Bryan of Nevada said the IOC 
president should resign. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe this problem starts at the very top,'' Bryan said.  
Any reforms the IOC enacts, he said, ``would lack credibility 
unless he (Samaranch) takes the honorable action to step down.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990415.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 10:11:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Dow Up 35.24; Nasdaq Down 37.32 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *PM-Wall Street Noon,0370    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Prices were mixed on Wall Street today, with  
blue chips in record high territory for the fourth day in a row but 
technology and consumer stocks dropping once again. 
</P>
<P>
	At noon on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was up  
35.24 at 10,446.90, after rising 16.65 Wednesday to its third 
consecutive closing high of 10,411.66. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 10.52 today to  
1,317.92, and the Nasdaq composite index, which has a high number 
of technology stocks, was off 37.32 at 2,469.96. 
</P>
<P>
	Wednesday's gain in the Dow came at the expense of technology  
and consumer stocks, which investors sold mercilessly to make room 
for cyclical issues, manufacturing and basic-materials stocks that 
are especially sensitive to changes in the economic outlook. That 
trend was continuing this morning. 
</P>
<P>
	Industrial stocks ``are rallying like crazy,'' said Charles  
White, portfolio manager at Avatar Associates. ``It feels like 
people who have been definitely underweighted in these sectors are 
coming in and buying. We're seeing some of these vast mutual fund 
complexes known for buying value stocks stepping up here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The fresh blow to technology stocks was a warning from Storage  
Technology, a maker of computer storage equipment, that it wouldn't 
meet analysts' first-quarter earnings expectations. Storage Tech 
shares were down 8 1/16 at 18, and they pulled ECM, another 
computer storage company, down 11 7/8 to 113 3/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Pharmaceutical stocks were lower amid investors' rush out of  
consumer shares. Dow member Merck was down 2 9/16 at 75 15/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Strong earnings reports helped some stocks but not others.  
</P>
<P>
	Dow component Boeing's earnings far exceeded expectations,  
sending its shares up 4 at 42. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Ford Motor and General Motors posted first-quarter profits  
that surpassed analyst estimates. Ford down 1/2 62 1/4, but GM was down 
2 3/16 at 87 5/8. 
</P>
<P>
	But Delta Air Lines was down 4 at 67 1/4, even after the company's  
earnings came in above expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 3-to-2 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume totaled 504.95 million 
shares, up substantially from Wednesday's pace of 386.13 million. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990415.0037 </DOCNO>
