<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Artwork on Paris Bridge Causes Jam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- A monumental sculpture show portraying Custer's  
Last Stand and other artworks on a footbridge over the Seine River 
is causing a human traffic jam in Paris. 
</P>
<P>
	Security officials said Thursday they're regulating the flow of  
people walking across the Pont des Arts, which links the Left Bank 
to the Louvre, so visitors can get close to the larger-than-life 
portrayals of American Indians and African tribesmen. 
</P>
<P>
	About 5,000 visitors, from foreign tourists to French school  
groups, cross the bridge daily. But weekends draw twice that many 
people, creating gridlock around the works. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokeswoman for Paris city hall denied recent media reports  
that the two-lane crush of people could undermine bridge security. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bridge in wood and steel was conceived to handle many more  
tons than the weight of a few hundred people,'' said the 
spokeswoman on condition of customary anonymity. ``Neither the 
bridge nor the visitors are in any danger.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 68 works depicting the African Massai, Peuls and Nouba  
tribes, as well as the American Indians who triumphed over George 
Custer and his men at the 1876 battle at Little Big Horn, are by 
Ousmane Sow, a 63-year-old Senegalese artist trained as a physical 
therapist. 
</P>
<P>
	The realistic pieces in subtle earth tones, on display until May  
20, are made of wire, plaster, rubber and paper fiber coated with a 
special veneer to protect them from the elements. 
</P>
<P>
	There's a triumphant Indian brandishing a soldier's scalp,  
hand-to-hand combat, falling horses with nostrils flaring and Chief 
Sitting Bull at prayer. 
</P>
<P>
	``I love the fact that this sculpture is part of the environment  
and accessible to everyone,'' said Gerald Ganann, of Minneapolis, 
Minn. 
</P>
<P>
	``The western pieces are very moving to people like me, who've  
been out to the Dakotas and seen the actual sites of the historical 
events'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
