<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Delta Pilots Battle Over Bedding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Delta pilots derisively call it ``the coffin.''  
</P>
<P>
	The snug new bunkbed unit aboard the airline's long-haul flights  
has crew members complaining of too little elbow room and too much 
noise. 
</P>
<P>
	Delta insists the onboard bedding is among the best in the  
industry, but the pilots' union says the bunks put passengers at 
risk by making it tough for the crew to catch needed rest. 
</P>
<P>
	The debate touched passengers on a Delta flight from Atlanta to  
Tokyo when the pilot cut short the 14-hour flight and landed in 
Portland, Ore. 
</P>
<P>
	Capt. Roscoe McMillan, a 30-year veteran, said the four-man crew  
was unable to rest in the bunks, jeopardizing the safety of the 
flight. 
</P>
<P>
	``He felt it would compromise his level of comfort and what he  
wanted as an acceptable safety margin,'' said Capt. Andy Deane, a 
spokesman for the Air Line Pilots Association, Delta's pilots' 
union. 
</P>
<P>
	The incident involving McMillan was the latest salvo in a  
long-running battle between pilots and Delta, which had shrunk the 
sleeping space on some planes to make more room for higher-paying 
business class passengers. 
</P>
<P>
	The union has filed a grievance with the company, asking for  
bunks that allow for more space and quiet. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's small. It lacks adequate privacy considerations and it's  
in a noisy area where the activities of the cabin and the cockpit 
make it difficult if not impossible to get sleep,'' Deane said. 
``Simply being horizontal is not enough.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Delta says the bunks are safe and approved by the Federal  
Aviation Administration. The airline has questioned McMillan and 
his three-member crew, and the pilots' union fears he could be 
fired if the airline decides he acted out of rebellion rather than 
safety concerns. 
</P>
<P>
	The aborted flight April 7 was disclosed in a report in The Wall  
Street Journal Thursday. It angered passengers, who were forced to 
wait for another flight to Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	``The pilots said they had tried to use the sleep module and  
were unable to get to sleep because of outside noise. The captain, 
because of that, made his decision,'' Delta spokesman Bill Berry 
said Thursday. ``He felt that his crew could not be sufficiently 
rested to complete the flight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Passengers were told before the plane landed that ``crew rest  
issues'' had caused the captain to turn back, Berry said. 
</P>
<P>
	Berry wouldn't say if Delta is considering sanctioning the  
pilot, who is just 11 months from retirement. 
</P>
<P>
	Deane said he fears the airline suspects ``this was an act  
perhaps of premeditation or he was doing this as a gesture of 
defiance over the rest facility. That is not true.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McMillan declined to comment when contacted at home Thursday.  
</P>
<P>
	The FAA requires airlines to provide onboard sleeping quarters  
for pilots on flights of 12 hours or more. A crew of four -- two 
pilots, two co-pilots -- take turns at the controls. 
</P>
<P>
	The only Delta flights exceeding 12 hours are nonstop from  
Atlanta to Tokyo. Three Delta MD-11s are equipped with the bunks. 
</P>
<P>
	Until this year, crew members used walled-off sleeping quarters  
-- pilots called them ``the condo'' -- located in the middle of the 
business-class section. At nearly 7-feet tall and 5-feet wide, it 
was spacious enough for changing clothes and far enough from the 
cockpit's noisy hubbub. 
</P>
<P>
	The new bunks are located between the cockpit and the business  
class area and include a 2-inch thick curtain to keep out noise. 
Pilots have to assemble the bunks in front of the passengers, 
pulling them out from the wall in telescoping sections. 
</P>
<P>
	Berry said the captain can ask flight attendants to keep noise  
levels down when people are trying to sleep. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can do your best to create a facility that it conducive to  
sleep,'' Berry said. ``It's FAA-approved. It's the largest of its 
type of units used by other airlines.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Berry said Delta is looking into making improvements to the  
sleeping quarters, such as giving crew members a bit more elbow 
room. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
