<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Defends NATO Air Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- President Clinton said today that a united  
NATO is determined ``to maintain and intensify attacks'' against 
the Serbs to save Kosovo and to guarantee the security of its 
ethnic Albanians with an international force. He invited Russia to 
join such an effort. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton told the American Society of Newspaper Editors that the  
NATO air war will be waged until Slobodan Milsevic's forces are so 
weakened they yield their grip on the province or permit ethnic 
Albanian refugees to go home. 
</P>
<P>
	Answering editors' questions, Clinton said the mistaken bombing  
that the Yugoslavs said killed 75 refugees near the Albanian border 
was regrettable and tragic, but no reason to change the mission. 
</P>
<P>
	``You cannot have this kind of conflict without some errors like  
this occurring,'' he said. ``This is not a business of 
perfection.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And Clinton said the refugees would not have been in harm's way  
had not Milosevic's forces driven them from their homes. 
</P>
<P>
	``We cannot simply watch as hundreds of thousand of people are  
brutalized, murdered, raped, forced from their homes ... all in the 
name of ethnic pride,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton was asked how he would respond to radio talk show  
critics who question whether he has the moral authority to be 
commander in chief and how he would answer to an Air Force pilot. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he didn't have to. ``I am his commander in chief,'' and  
U.S. pilots are performing admirably. ``They don't deserve to hear 
that,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Raising the possibility of Russian aid in protecting ethnic  
Albanians once the bloodshed ends, Clinton it is ``the kind of 
mission I hope Russia can join as well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Russians, bitter opponents of the current air campaign,  
joined the peacekeeping force that settled ethnic strive in Bosnia 
in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	The president began by saying that the forum itself was striking  
evidence of the difference between a free press and a closed press. 
He said the government run press in Yugoslavia ``has created an 
alternative reality'' based on propaganda about Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``Thank goodness our press and the press around the world have  
tried to get at and get out the truth,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Long term, he said, NATO is fighting for the future and  
stability of multiethnic democracies in southeastern Europe, the 
historically troubled Balkans. 
</P>
<P>
	``We and our NATO allies are in Kosovo today because we want to  
stop the slaughter and the ethnic cleansing,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said Milosevic's aim was to drive the Albanian majority from  
the province even if it means turning Kosovo ``into a lifeless 
wasteland.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said the Yugoslav leader also sought to divide NATO, but  
after three weeks, the alliance is solid. He said ``NATO is more 
united today than when the operation began.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The tragedy in Kosovo is the result of a meticulously planned  
and long premeditated attack on an entire people,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said NATO will end it, and will at the same time increase  
efforts to help the more than 500,000 refugees driven from Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	One editor told Clinton that he had heard the Pentagon had  
intelligence that Milosevic's forces had chemical weapons. He asked 
what the U.S. response would be to use of such weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said it would be ``swift and overwhelming. ... I think  
they are well aware of the dangers of overly escalating this. ... 
That's all I should say right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At that point, Clinton's staff signaled an end to the  
question-and-answer session, but the president said he would go on. 
``They think the longer I stay up here, the greater my chances of 
screwing up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked about the lack of information released by the military  
about bombing attacks, Clinton explained that there were problems 
with weather and with coordinating the response with NATO. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm aware this is a difficulty, I am working on it, and trying  
to get NATO to do more as well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said he feels ``the more information we can get out  
there quickly, the better off we are.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Outside the convention hotel, several hundred protesters chanted  
``No war, no bombs, no new Vietnam.'' A smaller group demonstrated 
in support of the NATO campaign. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
