<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 22:51:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Bust Clouds Strawberry's Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- By most accounts, Darryl Strawberry was well  
on his way back to the major leagues. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York Yankees outfielder had completed chemotherapy  
treatment for colon cancer and was expected join Triple-A Columbus 
as early as next week. 
</P>
<P>
	He was involved in charitable activities and spoke this week  
about how his illness changed his perspective on life. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's made me more aware of my purpose of living and who I'm  
living for,'' the eight-time outfielder said on ABC's ``20/20'' 
during an interview aired Monday -- two nights before his arrest by 
Tampa police on drug and prostitution charges. 
</P>
<P>
	``You know, I'm not living for me, Darryl Strawberry, to play  
baseball and be a hero at that anymore. You know, I'm living for, 
you know, the grace that God has given to me and allowed me to -- to 
be able to walk, walk on the baseball field again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It didn't take the 37-year-old slugger long to figure out the  
consequences of his latest brush with the law. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said he was apologetic about the charges of possession of  
cocaine and soliciting a prostitute that cloud his future in 
baseball. 
</P>
<P>
	``He asked several times, if there was anything that we could do  
to change this situation, because this was going to ruin his 
career,'' an investigative report read. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an unfortunate thing for Mr. Strawberry, but there's no  
question in our mind what had transpired,'' police spokesman Joe 
Durkin said. 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry said the powder cocaine found wrapped in a $20 bill  
inside the outfielder's wallet did not belong to him. And while he 
acknowledged discussing sex with a female undercover officer 
Wednesday night, he insisted he was joking around. 
</P>
<P>
	Police estimated the street value of the cocaine at $20.  
</P>
<P>
	``The $20 bill was folded up to keep it in place,'' Durkin said,  
adding the .3 grams -- about 100th of an ounce -- was enough for 
about ``one hit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The arrest was the latest jolt in Strawberry's troubled personal  
and professional life, which has been beset by cocaine and alcohol 
abuse, income tax evasion, domestic strife, failure to make child 
support payments and -- last fall -- a diagnosis of colon cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Yankees owner George Steinbrenner, who lives in Tampa, was in  
Cleveland to attend a funeral and could not be reached. 
</P>
<P>
	Lonn Trost, the Yankees' general counsel, declined comment,  
saying the team would allow the legal process to run its course 
first. 
</P>
<P>
	Baseball commissioner Bud Selig called the arrest ``a painful  
episode.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, a lot of people are looking into it. We've been in  
contact with the players' association and the Yankees, and we have 
to let the justice system work here,'' Selig said. 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry was in seclusion, breaking from his daily routine of  
working out at the Yankees' minor-league complex, where he has been 
preparing for a comeback from his cancer surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's not here, and he's not going to be here for a while,''  
Mark Newman, the Yankees' vice president of player development 
said. ``I don't know what's going to happen down the road.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry, who waived his right to have an attorney present  
during questioning, told police the cocaine might have been left in 
the vehicle by a driver or passengers from the night before. 
</P>
<P>
	The outfielder said his wife's uncle, Rodney Simon, used the  
vehicle Tuesday night and it was possible Simon or others in the 
car might have left the folded $20 bill in the glove box where 
Strawberry found it Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry said he was joking around with the undercover officer  
about sex and drove off with no intention of meeting her at a 
nearby motel room. 
</P>
<P>
	``Where is the good stuff?,'' the police report quoted  
Strawberry as asking the undercover officer. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am the good stuff,'' the officer responded.  
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry: ``Where can I get some good stuff to party with.''  
</P>
<P>
	Officer: ``I don't have any, but you can get it from anyone  
walking down the street.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry: ``Do you want to party?''  
</P>
<P>
	Officer: ``Yes, I want to party. What do you want?''  
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry: ``I want it all.''  
</P>
<P>
	The baseball player, carrying $1,159.10 in cash, then arranged  
to have sex for $50, the police report said. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators interviewed Simon by telephone at Strawberry's  
urging. They were told Simon was using Strawberry's vehicle the 
previous night and that he had been accompanied by friends. 
</P>
<P>
	But Simon ``denied that he used or even saw cocaine last  
night,'' the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry, who hit .247 with 24 homers and 57 RBIs for the  
Yankees last season, is not a stranger to substance abuse problems. 
</P>
<P>
	He entered a center for alcohol rehabilitation in 1990 and spent  
four weeks undergoing treatent for a subtance abuse problem in 
1994. The following year, major league baseball suspended him for 
60 days after he tested positive for cocaine. 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry's had financial woes, too.  
</P>
<P>
	A federal court ordered him in 1995 to repay $350,000 in back  
taxes and sentenced him to six months of home confinement, except 
for games. He was once also accused of failing to make timely 
payments to an ex-wife. 
</P>
</TEXT>
