<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Stocks Rise / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks rose Friday morning on buying by  
foreign and domestic investors, rebounding sharply from the 
previous day's decline. The dollar edged lower against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nikkei Stock Average climbed 236.48 points, or 1.41 percent,  
to 16,963.56 at the end of the morning session. On Thursday, the 
average closed down 37.60 points, or 0.22 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 118.74 yen at late morning, down 0.06 yen from  
late Thursday in Tokyo and also below its level of 118.83 yen in 
New York. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, Tokyo share prices moved higher, boosted by  
heavy buying from investors anticipating economic improvement in 
Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	``Individual investors are very active,'' said Tsuyoshi  
Nomaguchi, a strategist at Daiwa Securities Co. 
</P>
<P>
	An earlier rally on Wall Street also encouraged investors in  
Tokyo, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 51.06 points  
-- or 0.5 percent -- to another record high of 10,462.72, topping the 
previous record close of 10,411.66 set Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Early gainers in Tokyo included Honda Motor Co. Its share price  
soared after the Nihon Keizai business daily reported that the 
Japanese automaker will build a new plant in the U.S. or Canada by 
2001. 
</P>
<P>
	Honda spokesman Yuzuru Matsuno later denied the report, saying  
his company had made no decision to build another North American 
plant. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
exchange's first section was up 15.78 points, or 1.18 percent, to 
1,353.71. The TOPIX closed down 5.42 points, or 0.40 percent, the 
day before. 
</P>
<P>
	On the foreign exchange market, the dollar drifted lower in the  
absence of major market-moving news ahead of the weekend, traders 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 126.46 yen, down  
from 128.27 yen late Thursday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the 10-year Japanese government bond rose to 1.600  
percent from its close of 1.575 percent Thursday, pushing its price 
down to 101.74 yen from 101.97 yen. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
