<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FCC Makes Phone Bills Clearer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal regulators approved a plan today  
designed to make all those charges on your monthly phone bill 
easier to understand. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Communications Commission's plan, which is backed by  
the Clinton administration, generally would have phone companies 
reorganize bills to flag new charges and service providers, give 
clear descriptions of all charges and information about how to 
contest them. The plan, adopted in a 4-1 vote, could take effect in 
a few months. 
</P>
<P>
	Local telephone and long-distance companies would have to abide  
by all of the FCC's provisions, but cellular and other wireless 
companies would have to comply with just some. Violations could 
trigger fines or other penalties. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission will require local, long-distance and wireless  
providers to identify the company associated with each charge. 
</P>
<P>
	Local and long-distance companies also will have to flag -- the  
FCC doesn't specify how -- when a new provider or charge that hadn't 
appeared on previous bills shows up. For example, the bills will 
have to show when a person's long-distance carrier was switched 
from, say, AT&AMP;T to MCI WorldCom, or the person is charged for calls 
to a psychic hotline. 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC also will require local and long-distance companies to  
use ``clear and non-misleading'' descriptions about their charges 
and provide information on when nonpayment could cause phone 
service to be cut off. For now, the FCC won't apply this provision 
to wireless companies but will seek comment on whether it should in 
the future, FCC officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the FCC's 30,000 complaints about phone charges involve  
local and long-distance companies, not wireless providers. 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC doesn't specify the language for the descriptions but  
encourages the industry to come up with uniform wording. 
</P>
<P>
	The clear-language requirement also will cover the many  
line-item charges that have been popping up on phone bills 
nationwide over the last two years. Those charges, under different 
names, come from a government overhaul of phone fees, from itemized 
charges for government-ordered subsidies once included in rates and 
to pay the costs of complying with other government requirements. 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC's plan requires standardized language for these  
line-items, with the wording yet to be determined, the officials 
said. If wireless companies include such line-items in their bills 
they also would be subject to uniform labeling. 
</P>
<P>
	Local, long-distance and wireless companies also will have to  
give people toll-free numbers to call with questions or to dispute 
charges. 
</P>
<P>
	For the most part, local and long-distance companies already  
provide such information about their own charges, but that 
information usually is not posted for charges from third parties. 
Often when unauthorized charges are ``crammed'' onto a bill, 
customers spend hours trying to track down companies charging for 
the unwanted services. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the nation's Bell companies have begun, or plan to make,  
changes in phone bills to make them easier to understand. 
</P>
<P>
	Phone companies and consumer advocates have been generally  
supportive of the FCC's goals. 
</P>
<P>
	FCC Commsioner Harold Furchtgott-Roth voted against the plan,  
saying the FCC had no legal authority to take such action. 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC also adopted rules giving U.S. phone companies more  
flexibility in cutting deals with foreign carriers to terminate 
calls in countries where there is some competition. Regulators 
expect the changes could make it cheaper for U.S. customers to call 
most Latin American countries, most of Europe and Japan. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
