<HEADLINE> Report: Ovitz Endorses LA Coliseum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The bid to return pro football to a remodeled  
Coliseum appeared to gain momentum with a report that Michael 
Ovitz, the Hollywood dealmaker who proposed building a new stadium 
on a former Carson landfill, had given up on that idea and was 
going to endorse the Coliseum. 
</P>
<P>
	The NFL has approached Fox Group, which owns the Los Angeles  
Dodgers, about the possibility of building a new baseball stadium 
next to the Coliseum. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it's the Coliseum, great,'' Ovitz told the Los Angeles  
Times for today's editions. ``The Dodger situation sounds like a 
great opportunity for the city, and that didn't exist a month ago. 
This changes things, and if this helps bring football back to Los 
Angeles, that has been our goal from the outset.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ovitz said in a statement Wednesday that his position is  
unchanged from last month. 
</P>
<P>
	``A couple of weeks ago, I met with commissioner Tagliabue after  
the NFL owners' meeting in Phoenix,'' Ovitz said. ``I told him that 
my partners and I were committed to doing whatever was in the best 
interest of bringing NFL football back to Los Angeles, even if that 
meant voluntarily withdrawing our Carson stadium proposal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ovitz said the league had encouraged his group to continue to  
pursue the Carson proposal. 
</P>
<P>
	``Next Tuesday, we expect that the NFL will select a stadium  
plan on which to focus its efforts over the coming months,'' Ovitz 
said. ``As I told commissioner Tagliabue, we will support the NFL 
in whatever decision is made and we will continue to pursue our 
goal of owning and operating a successful NFL franchise in Los 
Angeles.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A Carson councilman says that city won't wait in line for an NFL  
team if the league fails to make a deal with the Los Angeles 
Coliseum. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it is anticipated that Carson will be waiting in the  
wings if the Coliseum-Dodger stadium deal doesn't go through,'' 
said councilman Daryl Sweeney, who led the suburban city's bid to 
get a team. ``They're probably thinking we'll be there saying, 
`Come back to us.' But that's not the case.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sweeney anticipates an announcement next week when the NFL  
expansion committee visits Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think a decision is going to be made on Tuesday, and I think  
that decision is to go to the Coliseum and to give them some time 
to get their act together,'' Sweeney said Wednesday in a telephone 
interview. 
</P>
<P>
	Sweeney's reaction to the chances of the Dodgers' moving to  
Exposition Park near the Coliseum: ``That's never going to 
happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the March meetings in Phoenix, the NFL owners voted  
conditional approval to give the Los Angeles area the league's 32nd 
franchise, but did not choose between Carson and the Coliseum. 
</P>
<P>
	The offer carried a Sept. 15 deadline for whichever group was  
picked to present a stadium and financing plan that meets the 
owners' approval. 
</P>
<P>
	If no deal can be worked out with the Coliseum, Houston likely  
will get the expansion team. 
</P>
<P>
	Sweeney said that if Ovitz does endorse the Coliseum proposal,  
Carson officials won't feel shortchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we've gained a lot of positive press and publicity out  
of it,'' the councilman said. ``Now we're going to plan to go ahead 
(with the site), possibly with the building of a mall.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
