<DOCNO> APW19990415.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 00:54:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pentagon Nixes Shipbuilding Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Pentagon sank a proposed merger between  
two shipbuilders, saying it wanted to preserve competition in the 
rapidly consolidating defense industry. 
</P>
<P>
	The $2 billion deal between defense contractors General Dynamics  
Corp. and Newport News Shipbuilding would have created a single 
shipbuilder for the Navy's largest and most expensive ships. 
</P>
<P>
	Cost savings to the Navy would not justify that loss of  
competition, Defense Secretary William Cohen said in a statement 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Because the merger would collapse the two existing companies  
into a single entity, there would be a reduction in the likelihood 
of future competition,'' Cohen said. 
</P>
<P>
	General Dynamics, which is based in Falls Church, Va., made an  
unsolicited bid for Newport News in February. The deal required 
Pentagon review and also was subject to a review by the Justice 
Department's antitrust division. 
</P>
<P>
	If successful, General Dynamics would have dominated the $7  
billion annual market for Navy ships, including $4 billion aircraft 
carriers and submarines costing roughly half that. 
</P>
<P>
	Much of the Pentagon review concerned calculating possible cost  
savings, which Cohen called considerable, from having shipbuilding 
engineering, research and development talent concentrated in one 
place. 
</P>
<P>
	But Cohen said planned improvements at Newport News' Virginia  
shipyards could save nearly as much money as the merger offered, 
without a loss in competition. 
</P>
<P>
	In an agreement with Newport News announced at the same time  
Wednesday, the shipyard will renegotiate some Navy contracts and 
agree to a lower price, but will keep profits reaped from 
improvements in efficiency over the next few years. 
</P>
<P>
	Nicholas D. Chabraja, General Dynamics chairman and chief  
executive officer, called the Pentagon's merger decision 
``disappointing'' and said the firm had withdrawn its offer. 
</P>
<P>
	``General Dynamics believes that its proposed acquisition of  
Newport News Shipbuilding would have meant significant savings for 
the U.S. Navy, enhanced value for the shareholders of both 
companies, and still preserved jobs,'' Chabraja said. 
</P>
<P>
	Newport News Chairman and Chief Executive Officer William P.  
Fricks said Pentagon opposition meant the company would proceed 
with a previously planned buyout of another rival shipyard, 
Avondale Industries of New Orleans. He said the proposed tranaction 
had received antitrust clearance from the Justice Department. 
</P>
<P>
	General Dynamics employs 31,000 people and had 1998 earnings of  
$364 million on sales of nearly $5 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	It is the parent firm for Electric Boat in Groton, Conn., which  
builds nuclear submarines, and Bath Iron Works in Bath, Maine, 
which builds the Aegis destroyer. General Dynamics also builds the 
Abrams tank, high-speed Gatling guns for aircraft and helicopters, 
advanced fiber-optics products, and high-speed processors for 
satellites. 
</P>
<P>
	Newport News employs 18,000 people and earned $66 million last  
year on sales of $1.86 billion. It is the Navy's sole supplier for 
nuclear-powered aircraft carriers. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990415.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 20:32:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Tax-Mania Sweeps Post Offices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- As much as Americans despise paying taxes,  
Thursday brought music and back rubs to the nation's post offices, 
along with a spirit of camaraderie among last-minute filers jammed 
into lines. 
</P>
<P>
	``I got it done. I've just got to figure out where to send the  
money that I owe,'' said 21-year-old Steve MacIntyre as he rooted 
through a mountain of forms at Boston's main post office. 
</P>
<P>
	His paperwork was creased and grubby from being in the back  
pocket of his jeans. 
</P>
<P>
	``Aargh! No envelopes!'' he shouted, pounding the wall.  
</P>
<P>
	MacIntyre's was just one of 126 million tax returns the Internal  
Revenue Service expected to receive this year. The agency said it 
had already received more than half by late last month. 
</P>
<P>
	But it was the procrastinators, the forgetful and the flummoxed  
who took in the festive atmosphere at the nation's mailrooms on the 
final day of filing. Some post offices were open as late as 
midnight, with parties scheduled until closing time. 
</P>
<P>
	At New York's huge main post office across from Pennsylvania  
Station, hundreds of last-minute filers weaved through clogged 
sidewalks to fling their returns into a row of curbside bins. 
</P>
<P>
	At Boston's main postal office around 8 p.m., the atmosphere was  
downright celebratory. A pianist serenaded a crowd of about 50, and 
free bagels, donuts, ice cream bars and coffee were also on hand. 
</P>
<P>
	Will Bladt, 28, of Boston, a high school lacrosse coach, said he  
hadn't expected to find a buffet and free entertainment. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm astounded -- it's like a big party, and it's the farthest  
thing I expected,'' said Bladt, who said he anticipates getting a 
refund this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Cannon, a postal service spokesman, said it appeared  
there were more last-minute filers in Boston this year than in 
1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ninety percent of these people aren't getting a refund, so  
we're trying to make it as painless as possible,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	A party at the Springfield, Mass., post office on Thursday  
included four bands and food donated from eight restaurants. 
Taxpayers also had a chance to get even with IRS agents. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have two dunk tanks this year, not just one,'' boasted  
Postmaster Flossie Paluszec. 
</P>
<P>
	Other post offices around the country tried to rub out the  
anxiety of tax filing with free back and neck massages. 
</P>
<P>
	In Phoenix, fans going to Thursday night's Los Angeles  
Dodgers-Arizona Diamondbacks game at Bank One Ballpark could bring 
their tax returns out to the ballgame. A mobile post office was 
destined for the ballpark. 
</P>
<P>
	Aspiring actors and actresses might have wanted to pay their  
taxes in Newport Beach, Calif. The U.S. Department of Agriculture 
was capitalizing on the crowds at the post office by conducting 
screen tests for its ``Got Milk'' campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	In Springfield, Va., the certified public accountants of  
Crutchley, Marginot &AMP; Tosi P.C. closed the office early, and like 
accountants around the country, they planned to celebrate an end to 
80-hour work weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``We shut down at noon, we start our party at 2 p.m. and it goes  
through the night,'' said accountant Mary Ann Dougherty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990415.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 20:32:26 </DATE_TIME>
