<HEADLINE>  Tax-Mania Sweeps Post Offices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- As much as Americans despise paying taxes,  
Thursday brought music and back rubs to the nation's post offices, 
along with a spirit of camaraderie among last-minute filers jammed 
into lines. 
</P>
<P>
	``I got it done. I've just got to figure out where to send the  
money that I owe,'' said 21-year-old Steve MacIntyre as he rooted 
through a mountain of forms at Boston's main post office. 
</P>
<P>
	His paperwork was creased and grubby from being in the back  
pocket of his jeans. 
</P>
<P>
	``Aargh! No envelopes!'' he shouted, pounding the wall.  
</P>
<P>
	MacIntyre's was just one of 126 million tax returns the Internal  
Revenue Service expected to receive this year. The agency said it 
had already received more than half by late last month. 
</P>
<P>
	But it was the procrastinators, the forgetful and the flummoxed  
who took in the festive atmosphere at the nation's mailrooms on the 
final day of filing. Some post offices were open as late as 
midnight, with parties scheduled until closing time. 
</P>
<P>
	At New York's huge main post office across from Pennsylvania  
Station, hundreds of last-minute filers weaved through clogged 
sidewalks to fling their returns into a row of curbside bins. 
</P>
<P>
	At Boston's main postal office around 8 p.m., the atmosphere was  
downright celebratory. A pianist serenaded a crowd of about 50, and 
free bagels, donuts, ice cream bars and coffee were also on hand. 
</P>
<P>
	Will Bladt, 28, of Boston, a high school lacrosse coach, said he  
hadn't expected to find a buffet and free entertainment. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm astounded -- it's like a big party, and it's the farthest  
thing I expected,'' said Bladt, who said he anticipates getting a 
refund this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Cannon, a postal service spokesman, said it appeared  
there were more last-minute filers in Boston this year than in 
1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ninety percent of these people aren't getting a refund, so  
we're trying to make it as painless as possible,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	A party at the Springfield, Mass., post office on Thursday  
included four bands and food donated from eight restaurants. 
Taxpayers also had a chance to get even with IRS agents. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have two dunk tanks this year, not just one,'' boasted  
