<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wealthy Targeted in Bankruptcy Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Robert E. Brennan, head of the now-defunct  
First Jersey Securities, used to alight from his helicopter in 
nationwide TV ads and beckon investors to ``come grow with us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now he's a poster child in a campaign by Sen. Charles Grassley,  
R-Iowa, and the Securities and Exchange Commission to close a 
loophole that has allowed some notorious defendants in fraud cases 
to shelter income from creditors by filing bankruptcy under the 
same terms as corporations. 
</P>
<P>
	An SEC enforcement official says the change is needed to  
eliminate abuse of the laws by people like Brennan, who filed for 
bankruptcy protection in August 1995 after being ordered to pay $75 
million for swindling investors. 
</P>
<P>
	After his bankruptcy filing, Brennan proceeded to pay himself an  
annual salary of more than $1 million from the companies in his 
estate, according to court documents. And the bankruptcy court 
trustee alleged, among other things, that Brennan was paid for 
personal air-travel expenses in 1997 totaling $241,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Grassley, a senior member of the Senate Judiciary Committee, is  
proposing an amendment to major bankruptcy legislation that would 
tighten payment requirements for individuals who file for 
protection from creditors under Chapter 11 of the U.S. Bankruptcy 
Code. 
</P>
<P>
	The overhaul legislation, which would make it harder for  
individuals to sweep away their debts in bankruptcy, mostly applies 
to ordinary people who are not super-rich. 
</P>
<P>
	Chapter 11 was designed to be used by companies, as it has been  
in recent years by Eastern Airlines, Texaco Inc., Broadway producer 
Livent Inc. and a host of others -- but many celebrities and other 
wealthy individuals also have filed under it. Under Chapter 11, an 
insolvent company or individual attempts to reorganize debts while 
under bankruptcy court protection from creditors. 
</P>
<P>
	``Typically, higher-income professionals such as lawyers and  
doctors file under Chapter 11,'' said a summary of Grassley's 
proposed amendment released Wednesday. It noted that some 
celebrities such as Burt Reynolds also have done so. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike in Chapter 13, which most people file under if they wish  
to reorganize their debts under bankruptcy court supervision, 
debtors filing under Chapter 11 are not required to devote their 
future earnings to repay their creditors. Grassley's proposal would 
make such income available to creditors when an individual files 
under Chapter 11. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the current laws, Chapter 11 is especially attractive to  
securities fraud defendants because their current income, which 
they often draw from companies they own, is not available to 
creditors. That allows them ``to expend it to live in luxury while 
under the protection'' of the bankruptcy court, Judith R. Starr, 
assistant chief litigation counsel at the SEC, said in a letter 
Tuesday to a Grassley aide. 
</P>
<P>
	``This situation has attracted individual Chapter 11 filings by  
some of our most notorious defendants,'' Ms. Starr wrote. In 
addition to Brennan, she cited Andrew Bressman, who filed under 
Chapter 11 after being sued by the SEC for his role in a 
small-company stock fraud for which he was subsequently convicted, 
and Thomas Warde, who filed after an appeals court upheld the SEC's 
$3 million judgment against him for insider trading. 
</P>
<P>
	In June 1991, the Supreme Court ruled, 8-1, that individual  
debtors may seek protection from creditors under Chapter 11, even 
though it is mainly used by companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year 862 individuals and 7,524 businesses nationwide filed  
under Chapter 11, down from 1,071 individuals and 9,694 companies 
in 1997, according to the American Bankruptcy Institute, a group of 
6,400 attorneys, judges, bankers and professors that does not take 
positions on bankruptcy issues. 
</P>
<P>
	Bankruptcy legislation in the House does not include a provision  
similar to Grassley's amendment. An aide to Rep. George Gekas, 
R-Pa., the House bill's chief sponsor, had no immediate comment 
Wednesday on the amendment. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990415.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 07:45:05 </DATE_TIME>
