<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Asian Markets Surge Except Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian stock markets surged ahead Thursday,  
with Hong Kong blue chips hitting an 18-month high, although Tokyo, 
the region's largest market, bucked the trend and ended slightly 
lower. 
</P>
<P>
	Aggressive selling of technology issues pushed Japanese stock  
prices down slightly. The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average 
fell 37.60 points, or 0.22 percent, to close at 16,727.08. 
</P>
<P>
	Technology stocks fell after some high-tech companies in the  
United States took a hit overnight, with traders also worried about 
recent strengthening of the yen, which could weaken Japanese export 
profits. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, the dollar bought 118.80 yen in the late  
afternoon, down 0.39 yen from late Wednesday in Tokyo but above its 
late New York level of 118.68 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong share prices rose to an 18-month high, reaching levels  
unseen since Asia's financial crisis showed signs of its toll on 
the territory's stock market. 
</P>
<P>
	The blue-chip Hang Seng Index closed up 1.1 percent, or 128.1  
points, at 11,962.23. The Hang Seng had fallen 0.5 percent 
Wednesday, but the index has surged 8 percent over the past eight 
sessions. 
</P>
<P>
	Foreign brokerages scooped up shares amid expectations that  
stocks will extend their gains as the outlook for regional 
economies improves, market participants said. 
</P>
<P>
	Australia's key index hit another record high, driven by a gains  
in resource-related stocks. The All Ordinaries index closed up 0.2 
percent, or 6.3 points, at 3,094.5. 
</P>
<P>
	In Seoul, share prices on the Korea Stock Exchange ended up 5  
percent, as funds piled into the market in response to falling 
local interest rates, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kopsi index closed up 34.60 points to end at 722.01, its  
highest in almost 18 months. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Indonesian shares ended higher on the back of continued  
foreign buying in shares of export-related companies that are seen 
cheap in dollar terms. The JSX Composite index ended up 2.7 
percent, or 11.923 points, to close at 447.479. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Malaysian shares finished slightly higher as fears  
of upheaval following the conviction Wednesday of Malaysian former 
deputy prime minister Anwar Ibrahim subsided. The 100-company 
Composite index ended at 581.90 points, up 3.79 points, or 0.7 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Philippine shares rose to an 11-month high as traders  
prepared for money to flow into the market as the central bank cuts 
the amount of cash commercial banks must keep on hand. The 
30-company PSE index gained 8.95 points, or 0.4 percent, to close 
at 2,177.36. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: The key index ended slightly higher. The Straits  
Times Index closed up 3.40 points, or 0.2 percent, at 1,706.13 
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: The key index closed at a 33-week high as investors  
bought commodity-related stocks in anticipation of rising product 
prices generating solid profits. The Weighted Price Index gained 
99.52 points, or 1.34 percent, to 7,498.17. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand shares finished slightly higher,  
supported by hefty gains made by local pulp and paper stocks. The 
NZSE-40 capital index gained 5.18 points, or 0.2 percent, to 
2,154.55. 
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Financial markets were closed for the Buddhist New Year  
holidays. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
