<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nichols Again Asks for New Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Information given to Terry Nichols near the end of  
his Oklahoma City bombing trial contained enough leads about 
another suspect to warrant a new trial, his attorney argued 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	In renewing his request for a hearing on Nichols' motion for a  
new trial, attorney Michael Tigar rejected prosecutors' contentions 
that the information had previously been turned over to the 
defense. 
</P>
<P>
	``Government counsel argued that Mr. Nichols mixed the bomb and  
that he was with Mr. (Timothy) McVeigh for long periods on April 17 
and 18,'' Tigar wrote. ``The withheld evidence contradicts this key 
government theory.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nichols, 44, was convicted Dec. 23, 1997, of conspiracy and  
eight counts of involuntary manslaughter in the April 19, 1995, 
bombing of the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building. The blast killed 
168 people and injured hundreds more. He is serving a life prison 
term. 
</P>
<P>
	McVeigh has appealed his death sentence after he was convicted  
of murder and weapons-related charges in the blast. 
</P>
<P>
	During Nichols' trial, defense attorneys sought to show others  
were involved by calling witnesses who said they saw McVeigh with 
an unknown suspect identified as John Doe No. 2 or other people 
during key periods. 
</P>
<P>
	At issue in the new trial motion are dozens of FBI lead sheets  
given to the defense attorneys on Dec. 11, 1997. The sheets are 
used to record information taken during informal interviews or from 
callers. 
</P>
<P>
	Tigar identified several FBI lead sheets which he said had  
``truly helpful information'' that the defense would have pursued. 
</P>
<P>
	``The government actively concealed these sheets,'' he said.  
``We did not discover them until we smoked them out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Oklahoma, Nichols has been charged with 160 counts of  
first-degree murder and three other felony charges stemming from 
the bombing. If convicted, he faces the death penalty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990415.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 17:52:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Drug-maker Perrigo To Cut 150 Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALLEGAN, Mich. (AP) -- Perrigo Co. announced Thursday it will cut  
120 to 150 jobs in a bid to save between $5 million and $6 million 
next year. 
</P>
<P>
	The maker of store-brand over-the-counter drugs said the job  
cuts will affect professional, managerial, administrative and 
support staff -- but not production workers. The company said the 
cuts will focus on salaried workers. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said it anticipates 80 to 100 jobs will be  
eliminated through attrition, redeployments and early retirements. 
The other affected workers face layoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``The staff reductions are based on our need to tightly manage  
costs and are not a reflection on the quality of work or the 
commitment of those people being displaced,'' Michael Jandernoa, 
the company's chairman and chief executive, said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The company also said Thursday it will incur fourth-quarter  
costs of between $3 million and $4 million relating to an early 
retirement offer. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
