<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Rain and thunderstorms struck Thursday in Minnesota, Iowa and  
Missouri along with parts of the Southeast. 
</P>
<P>
	Virginia, the Carolinas and Georgia were hit, along with eastern  
Tennessee south into far western Georgia. Tornadoes ripping through 
middle Georgia injured at least 30 people and caused extensive 
damage in two counties. 
</P>
<P>
	A twister late Wednesday in southern Mississippi also caused  
damage and killed one man. 
</P>
<P>
	Lighter rain fell from South Carolina north into southern  
Pennsylvania and Maryland. Rain also extended from Ohio and West 
Virginia west into Minnesota, Iowa and Missouri. 
</P>
<P>
	Temperatures were cold enough to support a mix of rain and snow  
across parts of northwestern Missouri. Kansas City, Mo., reported 
rain mixed with snow. 
</P>
<P>
	Wind gusted to near 50 mph from the Dakotas south into Oklahoma  
and Arkansas. Skies were mostly cloudy across the Dakotas. 
</P>
<P>
	High pressure over the western United States continued to  
dominate much of the West Coast, Great Basin and Southwest, with 
fair and dry weather. Some showers were scattered in the Rockies 
with snow in Cuchara and Beulah in Colorado. 
</P>
<P>
	The afternoon high in the lower 48 states was 88 degrees in West  
Palm Beach, Fla. The low was minus 3 in Yellowstone, Wyo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990415.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 17:43:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tyco To Cut 4,000 AMP Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EXETER, N.H. (AP) -- Tyco International Ltd. will cut 4,000 jobs  
from recently acquired AMP Inc., which already has undergone 
massive rounds of layoffs in the past year. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're trying to have AMP regain the leadership in its  
market,'' Tyco spokesman Brad McGee said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	AMP, based in Harrisburg, Pa., is one of the world's largest  
makers of connectors for electric and electronic devices that are 
put into just about everything from refrigerators to missiles. The 
company has been hit hard by the Asian economic crisis and a failed 
expansion last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyco, which is based in Bermuda and has its U.S. headquarters in  
Exeter, completed its $11.3 billion purchase of AMP two weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The 4,000 layoffs at AMP come on the heels of 4,200 layoffs AMP  
has made in the past year. 
</P>
<P>
	No Tyco jobs will be cut, McGee said.  
</P>
<P>
	McGee said he had no details about where the jobs would be cut.  
AMP has about 45,000 workers at 125 plants in more than 50 
countries. Most of its 68 U.S. plants are in Pennsylvania and North 
Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyco, a widely diversified manufacturer, is the world's largest  
manufacturer and installer of fire protection systems, the largest 
provider of electronic security services and the largest 
manufacturer of flow control valves. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
