<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton To Address Editors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton is making his case for U.S.  
engagement in Kosovo to a crowd of influential opinion-makers in 
San Francisco on the first stop of a two-day trip that mixes his 
roles as commander in chief and leader of his political party. 
</P>
<P>
	The president was speaking today to the annual meeting of the  
American Society of Newspaper Editors before traveling to Detroit 
and Boston to raise money for House and Senate Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	The address to the editors' meeting was another chance for  
Clinton to emphasize why he believed NATO needed to act against the 
forces of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic. 
</P>
<P>
	``The chance to speak to newspaper editors who, on a daily  
basis, speak to their readers back home, offered us a unique 
opportunity to go and make the case,'' White House press secretary 
Joe Lockhart said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Outside the hotel, about 50 protesters carrying signs denouncing  
U.S. involvement in Kosovo chanted ``No war! No bombs! No new 
Vietnam!'' Their signs also assailed news coverage of the crisis in 
the Balkans: ``Journalistic credibility? Where?'' 
</P>
<P>
	A smaller knot of protesters supported NATO with signs saying  
``Stop the Hitler of the Balkans'' and urging the alliance to arm 
the Kosovar guerrillas. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton has been making almost daily pronouncements on NATO's  
airstrikes and the effort to aid the hundreds of thousands of 
refugees fleeing Kosovo to Albania, Macedonia and Montenegro. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's important that the president continues to make the case,  
both on a day by day basis about what's going on in the military 
campaign, but also more broadly about what our interests are,'' 
Lockhart said. 
</P>
<P>
	At the outset of the Kosovo operation last month, Clinton  
canceled a fund-raising swing through Western states to devote his 
full attention to the U.S.-led NATO operation. 
</P>
<P>
	But with the campaign into its fourth week, the White House  
wanted to show that Clinton also was tending to other business. In 
Detroit and Boston on Friday he was expected to raise more than $1 
million for Democratic House and Senate candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	``The business of this country is ongoing,'' Lockhart said.  
``One of the things that any president does, whether it's a 
Democrat or a Republican, whether it's the '90s or the '80s, is, as 
a leader of the party, participates in party politics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also in Detroit, Brian Atwood, the head of the Agency for  
International Development, and James Lee Witt, director of the 
Federal Emergency Management Administration, was to join Clinton to 
highlight efforts to help Kosovar refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States has sent nearly $150 million in humanitarian  
aid to the region since 1998, including $50 million since the NATO 
confrontation with Yugoslavia began March 24. But U.S. officials 
admit they were unprepared for the scale of the exodus from Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
