<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ford Earnings Jump 20 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Ford Motor Co. said today that strong sales in  
North America helped it post a 20 percent increase in operating 
earnings during the first quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	The world's No. 2 automaker reported operating earnings of $1.81  
billion, or $1.46 a share, in the first three months of the year 
compared with $1.51 billion, or $1.22 a share, in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford's results were higher than Wall Street analysts'  
expectations. The average estimate of 19 analysts recently surveyed 
by First Call Corp. was for operating earnings of $1.39 a share. 
</P>
<P>
	The operating earnings exclude onetime gains that boosted the  
net income figures in both the latest period and in the first 
quarter a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales totaled $38 billion, compared with $36.6 billion a year  
ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Ford team is energized and focused, and we were determined  
to make a fast start in 1999,'' said Jacques Nasser, president and 
CEO. 
</P>
<P>
	``The best news for our consumers and shareholders is that the  
transformation of Ford is really just getting started.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ford reported a one-time, after-tax gain of $165 million from  
the sale of its share in the AutoEuropa joint venture in Portugal 
with Germany's Volkswagen AG. In last year's first quarter, Ford 
had a one-time, noncash gain of $15.9 billion from the spinoff of 
The Associates, in addition to $177 million in earnings from the 
former financial subsidiary. 
</P>
<P>
	With the one-time factors included, Ford's earnings totaled  
$1.98 billion, or $1.60 a share in the first quarter, compared with 
$17.65 billion, or $14.23 a share a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford's car business earned $1.47 billion, up 20 percent from a  
year ago, with surging sales in North America making up for a 
break-even quarter in Europe and losses in South America. Worldwide 
sales were $32 billion, up 10 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In North America, Ford said it earned $1.59 billion, up 57  
percent from a year ago. Ford said its high-profit truck sales were 
up 20 percent in the quarter, and car sales were up 10 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Without the AutoEuropa gain, Ford said it would have broke even  
in Europe for the quarter, compared with earnings of $230 million a 
year ago. Ford's losses in South America grew substantially, rising 
to $165 million from $45 million a year ago. The company says it 
does not expect to earn a profit there this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Visteon, Ford's parts subsidiary, said it earned $208 million in  
the first quarter, up 10 percent from $189 million a year ago. 
Revenue for the quarter was $4.8 billion, up 9 percent from $4.4 
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford Credit said it earned $300 million, up 8 percent from $278  
million last quarter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
