<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Pinochet To Be Extradized to Spain  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Britain's Home Secretary dashed Gen. Augusto  
Pinochet's hopes of immediately returning home by ruling today that 
Spain can continue seeking the former Chilean dictator's 
extradition. The ruling means that even though the House of Lords 
drastically reduced the case against the 83-year-old general last 
month, Home Secretary Jack Straw considered the remaining charges -- 
which include torture and conspiracy to torture -- serious enough to 
go forward. Pinochet, who remains under armed guard at a mansion 
outside London, now faces the prospect of months or possibly years 
in British courts battling Spain's attempt to bring him to trial 
for allegedly torturing opponents while in power. 

</P>
<P>
	Serbs, NATO Dispute Bombing Claims  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Yugoslavia accused NATO jets of  
blasting apart a convoy of refugees under Serb police escort 
yesterday. The alliance said its pilots fired on military vehicles 
only, and the Pentagon suggested that Serbs may have been 
responsible for the carnage. NATO targeted military barracks, 
transmitters carrying the state-run television program and a series 
of bridges earier today that reportedly injured three people the 
official Tanjug news agency said. 

</P>
<P>
	Pakistan Ups Nuclear Ante With India  
</P>
<P>
	ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) -- Pakistan tested a second  
nuclear-capable missile earlier today, upping the ante in the 
missile race with its uneasy neighbor India. The missile tested was 
the Shaheen I, the first in a new series of missiles. Pakistan 
tested its first nuclear-capable missile yesterday in response to a 
similar test carried out by India last Sunday. It wasn't 
immediately clear why Pakistan chose to conduct a second test or 
whether it would prompt India to respond. Since the two countries 
exploded nuclear devices last year and declared themselves nuclear 
powers, the international community has been trying to avert an 
arms race. 

</P>
<P>
	Mich. May Not Let Kevorkian Starve  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- The state of Michigan reversed its policy  
allowing the force-feeding of prisoners on the same day Dr. Jack 
Kevorkian went to prison vowing to begin a hunger strike. The 
assisted-suicide advocate, sentenced Tuesday to 10 to 25 years in 
prison, said he would begin a hunger strike immediately, The 
Oakland Press reported yesterday. State prison officials said they 
reversed their policy on force-feeding the same day the 70-year-old 
retired pathologist was sentenced. They denied the change had 
anything to do with Kevorkian. 

</P>
<P>
	Cancer Researchers Await Results  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Cancer researchers and patient advocates are  
bracing for new confusion and controversy over whether women with 
advanced breast cancer should try costly and arduous bone marrow 
transplants. Researchers will release preliminary results today 
from long-awaited studies on whether the treatment really helps. 
But the data are expected to be inconclusive -- raising fears about 
whether insurance companies will continue to cover the procedure. 

</P>
<P>
	Pentagon Nixes Shipbuilding Merger  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Pentagon sank a proposed merger between  
two shipbuilders, saying it wanted to preserve competition in the 
rapidly consolidating defense industry. The $2 billion deal between 
defense contractors General Dynamics Corp. and Newport News 
Shipbuilding would have created a single shipbuilder for the Navy's 
largest and most expensive ships. Cost savings to the Navy would 
not justify that loss of competition, Defense Secretary William 
Cohen said in a statement. 

</P>
<P>
	Japanese Stocks Edge Lower  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks edged slightly lower today on  
weakness in technology shares triggered partly by a fall in the 
U.S. Nasdaq index. The Nikkei Stock fell 37.60 points to close the 
day at 16,727.08. 

</P>
<P>
	Strawberry Arrested for Cocaine  
</P>
<P>
	TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- New York Yankees outfielder Darryl Strawberry  
was charged with possession of cocaine and soliciting a prostitute 
last night, police said. Strawberry has been in Tampa a the 
Yankees' extended spring training camp while he works back into 
shape following colon cancer surgery last Oct. 3. He was released 
on $6,000 bond. 

</P>
<P>
	Blues Bust Mighty Ducks 3-1  
</P>
<P>
	ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- Michel Picard and Geoff Courtnall scored  
goals 25 seconds apart in the first period and St. Louis beat 
Anaheim 3-1 last night, moving the Blues one point ahead of the 
Mighty Ducks in the Western Conference playoff race. Grant Fuhr 
stopped 31 shots, and was impenetrable until the third period when 
his shutout bid was spoiled by Paul Kariya. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAN BOYLAN  

</P>
