<HEADLINE> Deadly Storm Hits Mississippi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SOSO, Miss. (AP) -- Powerful storms ripped into southern  
Mississippi, destroying homes and downing power lines as they 
churned east. One man was killed and more than two dozen injured. 
</P>
<P>
	J.B. Pickering, 71, from rural Soso, died of massive injuries as  
a result of an apparent tornado that destroyed his mobile home, the 
Jones County coroner's office said. Three other family members were 
injured. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities early today were trying to determine the full scope  
of the damage caused by the storms that hit the area 60 miles 
southeast of Jackson late Wednesday. A Jones County sheriff's 
dispatcher said deputies reported numerous downed trees and power 
lines and widespread damage. 
</P>
<P>
	As many as 50 families had been displaced by the storm and  
needed shelter, said James Grimes, a communications officer with 
the sheriff's office. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have had enough officers and other resources out during the  
night that we are confident now that we don't have anyone 
missing,'' he said. ``Everyone is accounted for as far as we 
know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Officials at South Central Regional hospital in nearby Laurel  
said they had treated 25 to 30 people for minor injuries, mostly 
cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	Heavy rain and windy conditions were reported throughout  
Mississippi, but the majority of the damage appeared to be in 
Jones, Jasper and Covington counties. 
</P>
<P>
	In Covington County, one home was destroyed and two were heavily  
damaged. Trees were down and livestock was reported killed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
