<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Martinsville Has New-Look Pit Road </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MARTINSVILLE, Va. (AP) -- A reconfigured pit road at NASCAR's  
oldest oval has drawn mixed reviews from Winston Cup drivers 
preparing for the Goody's Body Pain 500. 
</P>
<P>
	Sunday's race at Martinsville Speedway will mark the first time  
all 43 drivers pit on the front stretch. Many drivers have lauded 
the change as an equalizer, but others are reserving judgment until 
after the race. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past, half the field pitted on the front straightaway and  
half pitted on the back, with the second group hugely 
disadvantaged. No driver since Lee Petty in 1959 has won at 
Martinsville from the back pits. 
</P>
<P>
	Points leader Jeff Burton said that setup wasn't fair.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think in Winston Cup racing today, the penalty for  
qualifying poorly shouldn't be that you can't win the race,'' said 
Burton. ``I think everybody ought to have a chance to win the 
race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Burton's older brother, Ward, isn't so sure he agrees.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know why they did it,'' Ward Burton said. ``We either  
need to run frontstretch-backstretch pits or mile-and-a-half tracks 
with one long pit. I know they're trying to make things better for 
the guys on the backstretch, but I'm not sure this is the way to 
go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ward Burton is seventh in the points race after seven races.  
</P>
<P>
	A big concern for many drivers is the pit road speed of 35 mph,  
which will make the drive down pit road unusually long and 
frustrating. Pit road opens at the entrance to turn No. 3 and exits 
coming out of No. 2. 
</P>
<P>
	On a track that measures .526 miles, that's a long way at 35  
mph. 
</P>
<P>
	``The one thing it will do is really change the way you approach  
the place,'' Jeremy Mayfield said. ``You have to make really good 
decisions on when to pit. The key is going to be avoiding pitting 
under green if you can. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was a time when you might drop in early if you thought  
you were on the verge of some kind of problem. Make a quick stop, 
lose one lap and figure you could get it back. You drop it now and 
you're going to come out three or four laps down. You aren't going 
to make that up on the racetrack.'' 
</P>
<P>
	John Andretti expects pitting under a caution to be tricky, too,  
especially for cars on the tail end of pit road. He said the pit 
situation could lead to yet another strategic change on NASCAR's 
shortest track. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll know a lot more after the race,'' Andretti said. ``You  
sure want to get good fuel mileage. That might be a first for a 
short track.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
