<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> First Union Profit Down 11 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- First Union Corp. reported an 11 percent  
drop in first-quarter profits Thursday as the nation's 
sixth-largest bank absorbed the cost of buying CoreStates Financial 
Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	First Union posted net income of $706 million, or 73 cents a  
share, for the first three months of the year, down from $790 
million, or 81 cents a share for the first-quarter last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank's profits from operations totaled $965 million, or $1 a  
share, excluding an after-tax charge of $259 million for its 
merger. 
</P>
<P>
	That figure, however, includes a one-time gain from the sale of  
its interest in Electronic Payment Systems. Without that gain, 
First Union earned 88 cents a share. That was the number Wall 
Street expected, but during the quarter the bank had guided 
analysts to lower their estimates. 
</P>
<P>
	In the first quarter of 1998, First Union reported profits from  
operations of $809 million, or 84 cents a share. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were pleased in the first quarter with the disciplined way  
our company focused on reducing our cost structure,'' Edward E. 
Crutchfield, First Union's chairman and chief executive, said in a 
statement. ``Although we view 1999 as a challenging year, we 
continue to invest in areas that promise higher revenue growth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	First Union announced last month it was cutting 5,850 jobs and  
leaving two non-core businesses as it restructured following the 
$16.1 billion merger with CoreStates. Expenses are expected to grow 
by about 3 percent in 1999 after the restructuring plan, the bank 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Charlotte-based bank reported a return on average  
stockholders' equity of 24.3 percent and a return on average assets 
of 1.74 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenue from fees and other income rose 41 percent to $1.9  
billion, excluding securities transactions. The growth was led by 
residential mortgage income, capital markets and capital 
management. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, First Union saw a 3 percent drop in net interest  
income for the quarter from $1.86 billion last year to $1.81 
billion. The decline reflected the sale or securitization of $5 
billion in residential mortgages and student loans late last year 
which were not fully reinvested until late in the first quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	First Union had assets of $223 billion at the end of the first  
quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	First Union's shares closed up 81 1/4 cents at $55.87 1/2 on the New  
York Stock Exchange. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
