<HEADLINE> Tornadoes Rip Through Georgia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VIENNA, Ga. (AP) -- Tornadoes ripped through two rural counties  
in middle Georgia on Thursday, injuring at least 30 people and 
destroying several businesses and homes. 
</P>
<P>
	The first twister touched down Thursday morning in Vienna, about  
50 miles south of Macon, causing extensive damage downtown. Up to 
30 people were injured by flying debris, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	At least 25 homes were destroyed and another 40 were damaged,  
prompting Gov. Roy Barnes to declare a state of emergency. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a house that was just taken from the foundation, moved  
10 or 15 feet back and then just flattened,'' Barnes said after 
touring the area. 
</P>
<P>
	Barnes also declared a state of emergency in Metter, about 100  
miles east. At least two people were injured and four mobile homes 
were destroyed or damaged there when a tornado hit at about 1:30 
p.m. north of town, according to the National Weather Service. 
</P>
<P>
	The storm spawned a third tornado around 3 p.m. near Metter,  
about 60 miles west of Savannah. 
</P>
<P>
	In North Carolina, severe thunderstorms brought high winds to in  
eastern North Carolina. One person was killed and others were 
injured when the storms overturned mobile homes in Robeson County. 
</P>
<P>
	Hail, heavy rain and downed power lines were reported elsewhere.  
</P>
<P>
	Late Wednesday in southern Mississippi, a tornado tore through  
rural Jones County, killing a 71-year-old man and smashing homes 
and cars in several small communities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
