<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reform of Students' Funding Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Schools that fail to educate students  
shouldn't benefit from an $8 billion federal program to boost the 
learning of poor children, education officials told Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	The money should go to the student, who would be free to take it  
to schools that work, said Diane Ravitch, a New York-based 
education analyst. 
</P>
<P>
	Ravitch and others told the House Education and Workforce  
Committee on Wednesday that federal money spent on poor 
schoolchildren had done little to improve their progress. 
</P>
<P>
	``The current system breeds bureaucracy,'' said Ravitch, an  
Education Department official during the Bush administration. 
``Schools would get money depending on how many poor kids are 
enrolled. Period.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The program, commonly known as Title I, along with other federal  
education aid is up for renewal by Congress this year. The money is 
distributed to states and districts according to the percentage of 
poor students they have. 
</P>
<P>
	Experts said the program -- the largest federal  
kindergarten-through-12th grade program -- has little to show for 
itself after 34 years. They cite consistent gaps in the test scores 
of poor and wealthy children. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let's be creative,'' said Maris Vinovskis, a University of  
Michigan researcher. ``Like welfare reform, let's see what works 
and what doesn't.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although many large education groups, including teachers'  
unions, want to leave the program untouched, there isn't enough 
research to prove that's a good idea, Vinovskis told the panel. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Casserly, who heads an organization of large-city school  
districts, said Title I hasn't been all bad. As of last year, it 
served 71 percent more urban students than in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	The House and Senate are debating how to spend federal education  
money overall; today, they planned to put the finishing touches on 
the so-called ed-flex bill, which will free states from federal 
rules tied to funding. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the federal government supplies, on average, 7 percent  
of a state's total education budget, some cash-strapped states like 
Mississippi and Alabama get 15 percent to 20 percent of their 
school dollars from the program. 
</P>
<P>
	Conservative lawmakers want to convert the money to grants for  
states to use more freely. 
</P>
<P>
	But some Democratic members are resisting that idea, saying  
money not tied to a school district could follow a poor child to a 
school that doesn't need the money or might not spend it on the 
child who brought it. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a foot in the door for vouchers,'' Rep. Matthew G.  
Martinez, D-Calif., said of the suggestion that public money be 
given to poor students to spend on the schools of their choice, 
even if they are private or religious schools. 
</P>
<P>
	But critics complain that after more than 30 years and more than  
$100 billion spent, achievement lags for students who are poor and 
disadvantaged. 
</P>
<P>
	Even Education Department researcher Alan Ginsburg acknowledged  
it was hard to measure whether the program has helped poor and 
disadvantaged students. He cited some gains in national test 
scores, but added that large gaps remain between rich and poor 
students. 
</P>
<P>
	The Title I program was created in 1965 to help poor children by  
paying for items such as reading instruction and staff hiring. The 
law, originally focused on remedial education, was changed in 1994 
to focus on high standards. It now allows schools with 50 percent 
poor students to use the money on all students, rather than 
providing extra help to a limited number. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
