<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Steelers Coach Has Kidney Platform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Pittsburgh Steelers assistant Kevin Gilbride  
took the offensive Thursday against a disease that killed his 
father and afflicts four siblings. 
</P>
<P>
	Gilbride, the former San Diego Chargers coach hired in January  
as the Steelers' offensive coordinator, asked Congress for more 
money for polycystic kidney research, saying scientists are very 
close to finding a cure. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've made the home turn and are just looking for the fuel  
to get across the finish line,'' Gilbride said during a House 
Appropriations subcommittee hearing. 
</P>
<P>
	Many scientists believe they are within five years of finding a  
cure, and Gilbride said he would be disappointed if they lose their 
momentum for lack of funding. 
</P>
<P>
	``Current and future generations of families like mine ... need  
the assurance that we will win out over (the disease) sooner, not 
later,'' he said. ``I implore you to act decisively to end this 
scourge once and for all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gilbride, 47, was introduced at the hearing by Rep. J.C. Watts,  
R-Okla., a former Oklahoma football star. Gilbride was Watts' 
quarterback coach with the CFL Ottawa Rough Riders in the 
mid-1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	Polycystic kidney disease causes fluid-filled cysts to form in  
the kidneys, preventing them from functioning properly. More than 
600,000 Americans have the disease, which is passed through genes 
and can cause such symptoms as high blood pressure, chronic pain, 
and urinary problems. 
</P>
<P>
	The Polycystic Kidney Research Foundation is seeking $20.2  
million in 2000 for basic research projects, specialized research 
centers and related programs. Current funding is about $10 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Dan Larson, president of the foundation, said polycystic kidney  
disease has not received as much funding or attention as other 
disorders because it has fewer celebrities making the pitch. He 
said he hoped Gilbride would help fill the void. 
</P>
<P>
	Gilbride said he has advocated research funding ``more quietly  
through the years'' and is now playing a more visible role -- just 
as four younger siblings reach an age at which symptoms may begin 
to develop. 
</P>
<P>
	``All you have to do is experience one family member going  
through the affliction,'' he told reporters. ``Watching my dad die 
is painful, watching him deteriorate, degenerate over time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His father died from the disease at age 45. His grandmother and  
an aunt died as well, while an uncle and two cousins needed kidney 
transplants. Gilbride and two other siblings did not inherit the 
disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
