<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Eagles Re-sign QB Hoying </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Just as the Philadelphia Eagles appear  
poised to use the second pick in Saturday's NFL draft on a 
quarterback, the team re-signed restricted free agent quarterback 
Bobby Hoying on Thursday to a one-year contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoying, the team's starter heading into the 1998 regular season,  
lost his job midway through the year and may still be traded for a 
draft pick this weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Two weeks ago at the club's minicamp, Hoying said he hoping for  
a new start. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a new coaching staff, and I'm trying to put last year  
behind me,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He may have to do so with a new team. The Eagles already signed  
veteran Doug Pederson as an unrestricted free agent and named him 
the starting quarterback for 1999. Koy Detmer played well in his 
five starts to close the '98 campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	The odd quarterbacks out, should the Eagles use the No. 2 pick  
Saturday on a quarterback, would appear to be Hoying and Rodney 
Peete. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoying completed just 50.9 percent of his passes last year, and  
threw zero touchdowns and nine interceptions in 224 attempts. He 
was a third-round pick of the Eagles in 1996. It was a terribly 
disappointing performance for Hoying, who had given the Eagles hope 
the year before that he might become a ``franchise'' quarterback 
after he passed for 11 touchdowns in six starts in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Now the Eagles are giving strong signs they are going to use the  
second pick in this year's draft on another player they hope is a 
``franchise'' quarterback. 
</P>
<P>
	The Eagles also announced on Thursday the signing of 10th-year  
veteran free agent safety Tim Hauck to a one-year contract. The 
32-year-old is coming off his finest NFL season posting 
career-highs in both tackles (83) and forced fumbles (2) for the 
Indianapolis Colts in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
