<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> `Erotica USA' Expo Debuts in NYC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Wandering through a sprawling Manhattan  
convention center on Thursday, chastity belts and electric body 
zappers seemed almost commonplace. 
</P>
<P>
	Even cell phone companies and Tower Records had stands at  
``Erotica USA,'' an expo -- complete with theme CD -- of nearly 
everything having to do with sex. It's debuting in New York before 
it travels to Miami, Chicago, Boston and other cities. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's definitely a lot different from the car show,'' exclaimed  
Bob Miles, a retired banker, as he wandered between a stand selling 
chocolate genitalia and a stage where erotic dancers performed. 
``They advertised it at my gym. It's -- uh -- interesting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miles was one of thousands of people, mostly men, who paid the  
$30 fee to get a peek at the expo's debut in this country after 
three years in London. ``Erotica USA'' will be in New York for four 
days. 
</P>
<P>
	There were 78 exhibits at the Jacob Javits Convention Center,  
plus performers and talks by experts on sexuality. The show even 
had its own CD, ``Erotica Primal,'' which, along with other music 
and videos, was on sale at a Tower Records stand. 
</P>
<P>
	Another company was selling cell phones because ``We think  
everybody needs to keep in touch, whether it's erotic or not,'' 
said salesman Hector Lugo, adding ``I never expected to be working 
at an erotica expo.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Paul and Brigitta Tooker, owners of Access Denied, one of the  
few companies in the United States to make chastity belts, said 
that within the first hour of the expo, they had already gotten 
orders for two of their belts, which cost as much as $440. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the biggest show we've been to,'' Brigitta Tooker  
said. She called the belts ``quite sweet actually,'' and said some 
people wear them to feel protected and safe. 
</P>
<P>
	But not everyone was charmed by the exhibit, just blocks from  
Times Square, which until recently a haven for sex shops. 
</P>
<P>
	Carla Redix, of Garden City, stood alone inside a police  
barricade across the street shouting her objections into a 
megaphone. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's disgraceful. It's really bad,'' she told anyone who would  
listen. ``I would like for there to be a larger turnout here. This 
is a battlefield. It truly is. It's just that not everyone is up to 
the battle.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite a brief news conference held by the nonprofit group  
Morality in Media, in which a handful of clergy and others 
condemned the expo as pornographic and illegal, opposition to the 
expo seemed minimal. 
</P>
<P>
	Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, famous for his tough opposition to sex  
shops, said only that he found it ``inappropriate'' the expo was 
held at a convention center with government connections. 
</P>
<P>
	Fred Bari, an organizer of ``Erotica USA,'' said the mayor had  
been ``wonderfully silent'' about the expo and noted he did not 
understand all the fuss about sex. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a basic, primal, human need. Without it, none of us would  
be here,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	At least a few visitors found it anything but basic.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's like an adult bookshop -- a really big adult bookshop,''  
said Ed Heubner, a railroad worker from Massapequa Park. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
