<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Military Tests New Technologies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMP PENDLETON, Calif. (AP) -- In 24 years with the Marines  
Corps, Wayne Medeiros learned a few things about communication in 
battle. 
</P>
<P>
	``It seemed like the guy on the ground was always the last to  
get data,'' the retired major said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Medeiros has designed a device known as the End User  
Terminal, or EUT -- a mobile, wireless computer communication and 
tracking system that soldiers can wear into battle. 
</P>
<P>
	The device was one of several high-tech systems demonstrated  
Wednesday as troops staged a raid on a mock city of cinderblock 
buildings at Camp Pendleton, 40 miles north of San Diego. 
</P>
<P>
	The EUT allows combat soldiers to pinpoint the location of  
friendly and enemy troops in the area. Then they can relay that 
information in real time back to commanders, who can then send in 
air strikes or reinforcements. 
</P>
<P>
	``What it is designed to do is eliminate the fog of war,''  
Marine Col. Mark Thiffault said. 
</P>
<P>
	Worn like a backpack, the EUT includes an ultra-small notebook  
computer, a power amplifier and global positioning system receiver. 
Medeiros, a designer for Litton PRC of McClean, Va., said the 
12-pound pack costs about $5,500. 
</P>
<P>
	The EUT is part of a larger battlefield communications project  
that has a four-year budget of between $20 million and $30 million 
annually. Most of the systems are still being tested or developed. 
</P>
<P>
	The demonstration for top military brass, foreign observers and  
reporters was an overall show of strength by the Marine Corps. F-18 
jets swooshed overhead. Cobra attack helicopters rumbled at the 
edge of the valley. Two Sea Knight transport helicopters lumbered 
above two buildings, depositing teams of Marine squads to take the 
city. 
</P>
<P>
	Some troops liked the EUT, but it has some faults.  
</P>
<P>
	Lance Corporal Tae Yun, 24, from Columbia, Md., said he had  
trouble hearing commands over the headphones or making himself 
understood through the voice-activated microphone during 
explosions. 
</P>
<P>
	Other soldiers worried about what would happen if the computer  
took a beating on the battlefield, became infected with chemical 
weapon residue or fell into enemy hands -- with precise data on 
troop locations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990415.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 22:51:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Questions Remain Over Browns Draft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	As the Browns make their final preparations for the NFL draft,  
the two most important players for the team to evaluate might be 
Tom Condon and Leigh Steinberg. 
</P>
<P>
	Condon, who represents Tim Couch, and Steinberg, Akili Smith's  
agent, were both contacted this week by the Browns, who have made 
it known their two clients are among three players -- along with 
Ricky Williams -- Cleveland is considering taking with the No. 1 
pick in Saturday's draft. 
</P>
<P>
	And as months of speculation, rumors and analysis are reduced to  
hours, the Browns continue to insist they haven't decided what 
they'll do. 
</P>
<P>
	Couch is apparently the frontrunner to go to Cleveland, with  
Smith now likely to be selected by either Philadelphia with the No. 
2 pick or Cincinnati at No. 3 if the Eagles go for another 
quarterback, Donovan McNabb. 
</P>
<P>
	While appearing on ``The Late Show with David Letterman'' on  
Thursday night, Couch said he didn't know where he might wind up. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know. I wish I knew,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Couch isn't alone. It seems everyone thinks they know who the  
Browns are going to take. 
</P>
<P>
	Reports have them taking Couch with the first selection as long  
as a contract can be worked out with Condon of Cleveland-based IMG 
before Saturday. But the Browns maintain they haven't anointed the 
Kentucky quarterback the chosen one yet, and that it's still a 
three-man race for No. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are actually in continuing negotiations with agents for all  
three of the picks under consideration,'' Browns team spokesman 
Alex Martins said Thursday. ``The organization has not made a final 
determination as of this point as to which player we will select on 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The negotiating process will continue over the course of the  
next few days, and we don't anticipate making a decision on the 
pick until Saturday morning.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's the same thing the Browns said last month and again last  
week. So either they're still unsure of who to take or they're 
playing a mean game of poker, savoring every moment of holding an 
unbeatable hand. 
</P>
<P>
	Whomever the Browns take first will be a rich man. Condon is  
reportedly seeking a seven-year, $44 million deal, plus a $12 
million signing bonus. Last year, the Indianapolis Colts gave the 
top pick, quarterback Peyton Manning, a six-year, $48 million 
package. 
</P>
<P>
	As the Browns' No. 1 derby comes down to the wire, it appears to  
have become a two-man duel between Couch and Smith. Williams has 
apparently dropped from consideration and will probably be taken by 
Indianapolis with the No. 4 pick after the Colts traded running 
back Marshall Faulk to St. Louis on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Couch and Smith appear together on the cover of this week's  
Sports Illustrated with both wearing Browns No. 99 jerseys -- Couch 
in brown, Smith in white. They're sitting side-by-side as ``Big 
Dawg,'' the leader of Cleveland's Dawg Pound, stands behind them 
holding a bone. 
</P>
<P>
	Browns coach Chris Palmer, director of football operations  
Dwight Clark and other Cleveland front office personnel have spent 
the week behind closed doors dissecting game films, scouting 
profiles and background checks on the pair of passers. 
</P>
<P>
	Palmer, a quarterback guru, is thought to favor the more mobile,  
more mature Smith over Couch, who was put through a rigorous, 
90-minute workout by the Browns in Lexington, Ky., last weekend. 
Palmer was reportedly displeased with Couch's initial workout and 
wanted to see how Couch responded to some hands-on coaching. 
</P>
<P>
	Clark, who drew wide criticism in 1997 while in San Francisco  
for taking QB Jim Druckenmiller over Jake Plummer, has been a Couch 
proponent and thinks the 21-year-old's ``upside'' might be greater 
than Smith, who is 23. 
</P>
<P>
	Whatever differences exist, team president Carmen Policy  
promises the Browns will be of ``like mind'' when draft day 
arrives. 
</P>
<P>
	Palmer said he and Clark have been going over draft day  
scenarios for weeks and feels a difference in opinion is healthy. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dwight and I have been on the same page since I started with  
the Cleveland Browns,'' he said. ``Every time I've started off in a 
different direction we've come back to the same thing.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
