<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hog Farmers Hope To Force Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Hog farmers who want to stop paying federally  
mandated promotion fees say they are one step closer to forcing a 
vote on the issue. 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents of the so-called ``checkoff fees'' planned to announce  
at a news conference today in Des Moines, Iowa, that they had 
gathered 16,500 signatures on a petition -- more than the 14,986 
required by the Agriculture Department to call for a referendum on 
the issue. 
</P>
<P>
	The signatures, which must represent 15 percent of all hog  
producers and importers, must still be verified by federal 
officials before a referendum can be set, but organizers said they 
were confident. 
</P>
<P>
	``To end up with 2,000 more I think says something,'' said  
Rhonda Perry, a Missouri organizer for the Campaign for Family 
Farms. ``There is a lot of opposition to a program that has 
absolutely no accountability to the people who are paying for it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Petitioners would like USDA to hold a referendum in 60 to 90  
days. Federal law, however, sets no specific timetable for setting 
a referendum once the signatures have been verified. A referendum 
would be decided by a simple majority vote. 
</P>
<P>
	The fee or checkoff requires pork producers to pay 45 cents for  
every $100 of animal value. 
</P>
<P>
	The money goes to the quasi-governmental National Pork Board,  
which contracts promotion services through the National Pork 
Producers Council, a trade group. 
</P>
<P>
	An audit released last week by the Agriculture Department's  
inspector general said the pork board was too closely tied to the 
industry group and recommended that it take steps to separate. The 
audit found no evidence, however, that the pork board had misused 
checkoff dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Perry and others contend producers get very little for  
the millions they pay each year. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you're a business person and you continue to throw money  
into a program in which your business does not see a return on 
investment, people would say you're a bad manager,'' Perry said. 
``In agriculture, that's called a mandatory checkoff.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hog farmers have been especially stressed this year as an  
oversupply dropped prices to their lowest level in four decades. 
They also point to the disparity between the prices producers are 
getting and what retailers are charging consumers. 
</P>
<P>
	Cattle producers are already collecting signatures for a vote on  
their checkoff fees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990415.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 14:25:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Drug-maker Pfizer Stock Plummets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Pfizer Inc.'s stock skidded 10 percent Thursday  
after the drug company reported a drop in sales of Viagra and 
warned that profit growth would slow in the second quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Pfizer, which released its first-quarter results Thursday, said  
it will fall far short of the 35 percent profit growth it enjoyed 
last spring due to the explosive initial sales of the 
anti-impotence pill Viagra. Pfizer also hinted that overall 1999 
earnings would be slightly below expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	In the just-ended quarater, Pfizer earned $815 million, or 62  
cents per share, up 27 percent from $692 million, or 53 cents a 
share, in the same quarter a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Pfizer revenues jumped 29 percent to $3.93 billion from $3.04  
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Earnings met analysts' expectations, according to surveys by  
First Call. Yet, many traders had quietly hoped the company would 
beat Wall Street's already rosy forecasts. Pfizer stock fell $14.75 
to $129.88 on Thursday in New York Stock Exchange trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said Pfizer could have posted higher profits, but  
instead chose to spend more on research and building its sales 
staff. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a very smart strategy for the long haul, but does not  
help the short term,'' said Steven Gerber, an analyst with CIBC 
Oppenheimer. 
</P>
<P>
	Pfizer, the world's fourth-largest drug company, has been a  
pharmaceutical dynamo the past three years. It owns or sells the 
three fastest growing new drugs in pharmaceutical history: Viagra; 
the cholesterol drug Lipitor, which it markets with Warner-Lambert; 
and the arthritis pill Celebrex, which it markets with Monsanto. 
</P>
<P>
	The three drugs combined are expected to generate more than $4  
billion in 1999 sales. 
</P>
<P>
	With such high expectations, analysts said Pfizer's stock was  
vulnerable to a big selloff, especially during a week when 
investors are moving from growth stocks to cyclical stocks, those 
that tend to rise and fall with the economy, and to smaller company 
stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	Pfizer said profit growth would be in the single digits in the  
second quarter, far below the 20 percent to 30 percent Wall Street 
has come to expect. 
</P>
<P>
	Pfizer posted $193 million in worldwide Viagra sales during the  
first quarter, down 18 percent from $236 million in the fourth 
quarter. In the second quarter of 1998, Viagra had $411 million in 
sales. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Viagra sales rose slightly to $149 million in the first  
quarter of 1999, up from $131 million in the prior three months. 
</P>
<P>
	Viagra sales should improve markedly in the second quarter with  
the drug's launch in Japan and Canada, Pfizer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Weak Viagra sales in the United States were attributed to the  
leveling off of the curiosity factor related to the drug and to 
limits insurers have placed on coverage for it, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the demand for the first-ever impotence pill are  
startling. More than 9 million prescriptions have been written for 
4 million patients since its launch in April 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``Despite the Viagra problems, as far as overall sales and  
earnings growth, Pfizer is still a rising company,'' said Hemant 
Shah, analyst with HKS &AMP; Co. in Warren, N.J. 
</P>
<P>
	Pfizer's biggest-selling drug, Norvasc, a hypertension  
medication, posted a 24 percent increase in first quarter sales to 
$703 million. Sales of the antibiotic Zithromax rose 44 percent to 
$441 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues that Pfizer gets from marketing other companies' drugs,  
such as Lipitor and Celebrex, rose 168 percent to $403 million. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990415.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 09:15:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Storms Kill Two in Miss. and Tenn. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SOSO, Miss. (AP) -- Powerful storms swept through parts of the  
South, destroying homes, damaging a marina and downing power lines 
as they churned eastward. Two people killed and more than two dozen 
injured. 
</P>
<P>
	J.B. Pickering, 71, died as a result of an apparent tornado that  
destroyed his mobile home in rural Soso, the Jones County coroner's 
office said. Three other family members were injured. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tennessee, a tree blew onto a mobile home in the Castlelaw  
Trailer Park in Crockett County late Wednesday, killing a woman. 
</P>
<P>
	Straight line winds blew down trees and power lines throughout  
the county, crushing 50 to 60 boats at the Mansard Island Marina on 
Kentucky Lake's Big Sandy Basin. 
</P>
<P>
	Marina owner Cee Koenig said the wind picked up one portion of  
the dock with the boats moored to it, and dropped it on another 
portion of the dock. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the height of our fishing season and we had a full  
house of guests,'' Koenig said. Nobody was injured. 
</P>
<P>
	In Alabama, high wind destroyed a mobile home in Russell County  
while downing trees and power lines in several locations, but no 
one was reported injured. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities in Mississippi worked today to determine the scope  
of the damage caused by the storms that hit the area 60 miles 
southeast of Jackson late Wednesday. Heavy rain and wind were 
reported throughout Mississippi, but the majority of the damage 
appeared to be in Jones, Jasper and Covington counties. 
</P>
<P>
	At least 36 residences, 21 of them mobile homes, were reportedly  
damaged or destroyed in Jones County. As many as 50 families had 
been displaced by the storm, said James Grimes, a communications 
officer with the Jones County sheriff's office. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have had enough officers and other resources out during the  
night that we are confident now that we don't have anyone 
missing,'' Grimes said. ``Everyone is accounted for as far as we 
know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Officials at South Central Regional hospital in Laurel said they  
had treated 25 to 30 people for minor injuries, mostly cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	In Covington County, one home was destroyed and two were heavily  
damaged. Trees were down and livestock was reported killed. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheila Crosby and her neighbors gathered outside her white,  
woodframe home in Soso at midmorning today, looking over the damage 
left by the storm and giving thanks they survived. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just a blessing from the Lord,'' Crosby said as she  
looked over the twisted remains of two vacant mobile homes that 
were torn from their plots beside her home. ``It's Jesus that this 
house is still standing.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
