<DOCNO> APW19990415.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 05:56:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Algerian Candidates Charge Fraud </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) -- Algerians were urged to vote today in a  
presidential election left with a lone contender after six other 
candidates abruptly pulled out, alleging vote fraud. 
</P>
<P>
	The surprise developments on the eve of the election were a blow  
to hopes that the voting would help mend fractures in this nation 
caught up in a cycle of violence since 1992, the start of an 
Islamic insurgency. Some 75,000 people have been killed. 
</P>
<P>
	The single remaining contestant, Abdelaziz Bouteflika, widely  
viewed as the candidate of the powerful military, said he would 
accept victory only if backed by a large majority and a massive 
turnout. 
</P>
<P>
	Turnout was light as polls opened this morning in the North  
African nation of 31 million people. Results were not expected 
until Friday, according to officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Many saw the election to give Algeria its first civilian  
president since 1965 as a step toward democracy. 
</P>
<P>
	The pullout was to protest alleged fraud in early voting by  
army, police and customs personnel in Algeria's vast Saharan 
expanse. It also represented an act of defiance against the 
army-backed old order, which has bred fraud and corruption since 
Algeria gained independence from France in 1962. 
</P>
<P>
	The candidates, from across the political spectrum, pulled out  
after President Liamine Zeroual refused to meet with them on the 
fraud charges, suggesting instead they file formal complaints. 
</P>
<P>
	Zeroual, a retired general who is stepping down 18 months before  
his five-year term ends, sharply criticized the candidates' 
withdrawal in a nationwide television address and ordered the 
election to continue. 
</P>
<P>
	Casting his ballot early today, Zeroual continued his rebuke of  
the withdrawal, saying that ``history will judge the positions of 
each'' one of the candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	``But the main thing is that the right to speak is given to the  
people so they can make their choice,'' Zeroual added. 
</P>
<P>
	Experts in electoral law said such a withdrawal would not halt  
an election. 
</P>
<P>
	Bouteflika has for months been billed in the press as the  
``candidate of consensus.'' The statement is a derogatory reference 
to his backing from a large segment of the establishment, including 
the powerful UGTA union, a moderate Islamic party in the coalition 
government and the National Liberation Front, which ruled Algeria 
for three decades. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview with The Associated Press, Bouteflika said that  
to become president, he needed ``a massive participation of the 
people and a score that gives me the capacity to meet the extremely 
numerous challenges which just have been complicated.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He did not say what figures would be acceptable. Without a huge  
success at the polls, ``I'll go home,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked to explain what he thought would happen if he failed to  
meet his own conditions, he replied: ``The institutions are there. 
The state won't collapse. It's not the end of the world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He called the withdrawal of the six a ``flagrant twisting of the  
law.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, he skirted the issue of whether the army tapped him.  
</P>
<P>
	``I feel a bit hurt to see the intelligentsia of my country not  
knowing how to negotiate this particularly delicate turn,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Algeria is in the process of rebuilding its institutions,  
dismantled in an army coup that canceled 1992 legislative elections 
the now-banned Islamic Salvation Front was poised to win. 
</P>
<P>
	The move triggered the insurgency and the country veered into  
near chaos. 
</P>
<P>
	A measure of the hope placed in the election was the call by the  
Salvation Front for Algerians to vote ``en masse,'' after boycott 
calls in three previous elections. 
</P>
<P>
	The statement issued last week by the banned party's exiled  
leaders in Europe praised all the candidates for their will to seek 
national reconciliation, while asking citizens to cast ballots for 
Ahmed Taleb Ibrahimi, a former minister sympathetic to the Islamic 
cause and one of the six who withdrew Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990415.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 05:56:12 </DATE_TIME>
