<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Continental Earnings Slip 4 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Continental Airlines on Thursday handily beat  
analysts' expectations for first-quarter earnings, but its income 
of $78 million marked a slight drop from a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The Houston-based carrier earned $1.03 per share, down from $81  
million, or $1.06 per share, in the first three months of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	However, analysts surveyed by First Call Corp. anticipated  
earnings of 93 cents per share. It's the second straight first 
quarter that Continental beat Wall Street's predictions by a dime. 
</P>
<P>
	The income figure excludes non-recurring gains and charges that  
pushed the company's actual first-quarter profit to $84 million, or 
$1.11 per share on a diluted basis. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenue rose 10.9 percent to $1.9 billion from $1.7 billion.  
</P>
<P>
	The carrier credited continued increases in passenger loads  
despite slumping travel on Asian routes. Continental also has 
endured increased fuel costs, in contrast to plunging fuel prices 
this time last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Thursday, Continental announced it would increased its  
stock repurchase program by $500 million to a total of $800 
million. The company has spent about $266 million on its own stock 
since last year. 
</P>
<P>
	As of May 4, the ticker symbol for the airline's widely traded  
class B shares will change to CAL from CAI.B. The carrier's class A 
shares will become CAL.A instead of CAI.A. Both classes of stock 
trade on the New York Stock Exchange. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
