<HEADLINE> Orioles' Ripken Makes Double Error </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- It's Cal Ripken's glove that resembles iron  
these days, not the player. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken made a double error in the second inning of the Baltimore  
Orioles' game against the New York Yankees on Thursday night, 
leading to five unearned runs. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken, a two-time Gold Glove who had just eight errors last  
season and holds or shares 12 fielding records, has five of his 
team's first six errors this year. 
</P>
<P>
	With Baltimore ahead 4-0 and the bases loaded with two outs in  
the second, Luis Sojo hit a grounder to third that Ripken bobbled, 
then threw past first as two runs scored. 
</P>
<P>
	Chuck Knoblauch hit a two-run double off the glove of left  
fielder B.J. Surhoff on the next pitch, and Derek Jeter's double 
gave New York a 5-4 lead. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken, who has been bothered by a bad back this season, had two  
throwing errors in Sunday's 9-5 loss to Toronto, including one on a 
rundown that turned the game around. 
</P>
<P>
	Baseball's Ironman, who broke Lou Gehrig's record for  
consecutive games played, also misplayed Chili Davis' first-inning 
grounder in Baltimore's 14-7 loss to New York on Wednesday night, 
leading to the third run of the inning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
