<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Saints' Hazing Lawsuit Dismissed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MADISON, Wis. (AP) -- A lawsuit Jeff Danish filed against  
linebacker Andre Royal over a hazing incident during the New 
Orleans Saints training camp last summer was dismissed Thursday on 
a technicality. 
</P>
<P>
	Royal did not respond to the lawsuit, and Danish's lawyers  
hadn't pursued the case further. U.S. District Court dismissed the 
suit because it did not want idle cases clogging its docket, 
Danish's lawyer, Richard Barker, said. 
</P>
<P>
	Barker said that he may refile the lawsuit depending on what  
Danish wants to do. ``I'm waiting for further word from my 
client,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Danish said in the lawsuit he was forced to ran a gantlet of  
Saints players who were hitting, kicking and pounding on him with a 
bag of coins Aug. 20, the last night of training camp at the 
University of Wisconsin-La Crosse. 
</P>
<P>
	Danish had sued the Saints, Royal, an assistant coach and five  
other players, demanding that the team pay him more than $650,000 
for physical and emotional suffering, lost wages, medical expenses 
and humiliation. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit against the Saints and the six others was settled in  
February. Terms of that settlement weren't released as part of a 
confidentiality agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	Royal, who admitted to NFL investigators that he took part in  
the gantlet, was traded to Indianapolis and played last season with 
the Colts. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was one of the players who did not respond, so we did not  
represent him,'' Peder Arneson, a La Crosse lawyer who represented 
the players, said of Royal. ``As part of the settlement with the 
Saints, Danish reserved the right to make claims against Royal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Danish, a defensive tackle from Richmond, N.Y., broke a  
dormitory window when he hit it after running the gantlet in a 
third-floor hallway. He required 14 stitches to his left arm and 
hand. 
</P>
<P>
	Rookie Andy McCullough also was hazed that day, as were No. 1  
draft pick Kyle Turley, second-round pick Cam Cleeland, No. 6 pick 
Chris Bordano and seventh-round pick Andy McCullough. 
</P>
<P>
	Cleeland missed time with headaches and blurred vision in one  
eye. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
