<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Trial To Probe Great Chicago Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- The defendant claims he is being framed because  
of ethnic prejudice. The prosecution insists he is not only guilty 
of perjury but responsible for a fire that is etched in American 
history. 
</P>
<P>
	A mock trial today at John Marshall Law School will attempt to  
get to the bottom of one of the city's most enduring mysteries -- 
the circumstances of the Great Fire. 
</P>
<P>
	Yes, that Great Fire, the one that leveled a third of Chicago in  
October 1871, left more than 100,000 people homeless and never 
relinquished its grip on popular imagination. The one often blamed 
on the cow in Catherine O'Leary's barn. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors will attempt to show that Daniel ``Peg Leg''  
Sullivan lied in his testimony about the fire. 
</P>
<P>
	``Although we are not charging him with starting the fire, by  
the end of the trial it will be clear why he lied,'' declared Anna 
Demacopoulos, a Cook County prosecutor who will lead the team 
trying Sullivan. 
</P>
<P>
	Counters Sullivan -- in the person of actor Andrew White, who  
will play him at the trial -- ``It seems like a conspiracy to try 
and demean the Irish people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some believe Sullivan started the fire accidentally in the barn  
the night of Oct. 8, 1871, then tried to escape responsibility by 
telling authorities he had seen the first flames while sitting 
outside a nearby house. 
</P>
<P>
	However it started, the fire spread quickly, overwhelming the  
fire department's ability to fight it. Rain helped put out the 
flames 29 hours later. 
</P>
<P>
	By then, as many as 300 people were dead, tens of thousands of  
homes were gone, businesses were reduced to ashes and even ships on 
the Chicago River were burned. 
</P>
<P>
	The official Board of Police and Fire Commissioners report did  
not fix blame. But the legend of Mrs. O'Leary and her cow became 
widely accepted. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am 100 percent convinced that `Peg Leg' Sullivan started the  
Great Chicago Fire,'' said Dick Bales, a lawyer and author of a 
history of the fire. 
</P>
<P>
	After studying little-known real estate records, Bales concluded  
two years ago that Sullivan could not have seen what he told 
investigators he did -- the first flames -- because a house would 
have blocked his view of the O'Leary barn. 
</P>
<P>
	Sullivan's tale of dashing into the barn to try to save the  
animals, then running off to get help is also doubted by some who 
point out that his wooden leg would have made so much running 
difficult. 
</P>
<P>
	White -- already in character as Sullivan in an interview in  
advance of the trial -- insisted in a rich Irish brogue that he 
testified truthfully during the inquiry into the fire's cause. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he will be found innocent by the jury, which will  
include former DePaul University basketball coach Ray Meyer, 
television newsman Bill Kurtis and the city police superintendent. 
</P>
<P>
	Other actors from Lookingglass Theatre Company will be taking  
the roles of Mrs. O'Leary and other figures from the time. Sullivan 
will be tried in front of a Cook County judge by county prosecutors 
and criminal defense attorneys. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's never been a resolution of any kind,'' said Ralph  
Ruebner, a professor at John Marshall who has led the project the 
past two years. ``No one was ever indicted. We wanted to have a 
trial here to see where the truth may lie.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, Chicago's City Council exonerated Mrs. O'Leary, who  
survived the fire, and her cow, which did not. 
</P>
<P>
	Northwestern University professor Carl Smith said the dark side  
of the O'Leary legend is the attempt to blame the fire on Irish 
Catholic immigrants. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is also a thing to turn into a kind of almost a whimsical  
joke, that this whole city was burned down by a clumsy cow, and it 
hides in some ways more serious things,'' he said. ``The city 
burned down because it was unprotected against such things.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
