<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cohen: Yugo Conflict Won't Be Quick </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration is signaling that  
the U.S.-led NATO air campaign in Yugoslavia could stretch into 
summer. Defense Secretary William Cohen cautioned Congress today 
that ``this is not going to be quick or easy or neat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To those who say that NATO should commit ground forces to the  
effort, Cohen said, ``The reason that we have gone forward as we 
have with an air campaign is that there was not a consensus in the 
NATO alliance to do anything but this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Testifying before the Senate Armed Services Committee, Cohen  
said he regretted the death of civilians that resulted when a NATO 
bomb struck a convoy Wednesday. ``It was under extraordinary 
circumstances,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen said anti-aircraft artillery fire was directed at the  
pilot, who had to make a split-second decision. ``We go to 
extraordinary lengths to protect civilians,'' the secretary said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do value human life,'' said Cohen, who appeared before the  
committee with Gen. Henry H. Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs 
of Staff. ``We do try to reduce the risks to innocent human 
beings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, meanwhile, was testifying  
before the House Appropriations Committee as officials put together 
an emergency budget request to pay the U.S. share of NATO 
operations. 
</P>
<P>
	White House budget chief Jacob Lew met for nearly an hour  
Wednesday with Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., who said 
the Clinton administration was discussing something in the range of 
$4 billion to $8 billion. He said the administration wants to pay 
for the entire Balkans package using the expected federal surplus, 
including costs of caring for at least 500,000 refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, that's not what we'll get our members to go along  
with,'' Lott said. 
</P>
<P>
	Many Republicans seem eager to pay for military costs of the  
crisis with the surplus while finding budget cuts to pay for the 
rest of it. 
</P>
<P>
	In his testimony, Cohen recalled an earlier warning to Congress  
that ``this is not going to be quick or easy or neat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He amended his earlier statements about the possibility of U.S.  
casualties to say that there was the ``probability of casualties.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This really is a battle of freedom over fear,'' Cohen said,  
``... it's a battle of democracy over dictatorship.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In closed-door meetings this week with congressional officials,  
U.S. military leaders suggested NATO is poised to continue the 
3-week-old air campaign for several weeks longer, possibly into 
midsummer if Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's forces 
continue fighting Kosovar Albanians in the Serbian province of 
Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Shelton told lawmakers that while bombing has been frequently  
hampered by weather, conditions usually improve in the Balkans in 
June and July, the officials said, speaking on condition of 
anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is going to be a sustained campaign,'' said one lawmaker  
who was briefed. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S.-led Gulf War in 1991 lasted only six weeks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
