<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Religion Briefs / Religion Briefs  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Rev. Roy Magee, a Presbyterian minister based in  
Northern Ireland who has worked to resolve sectarian conflict 
there, was named the recipient of the Peace Activist Award 
presented by theTanenbaum Center for Interreligious Understanding. 
</P>
<P>
	Magee, a senior research fellow at the University of Ulster,  
said religious groups should contribute more toward ending the 
centuries-old strife between Catholics and Protestants. 
</P>
<P>
	Churches have often made their members more entrenched in their  
positions, Magee said in an interview Tuesday, one day before the 
award ceremony in New York. Religious groups should risk preaching 
to people outside their circles, he said. He noted that his own 
decision to work with Protestant militant groups in the 1980s was 
initially unpopular with his church. In 1994, he helped broker a 
cease-fire involving these groups. 
</P>
<P>
	``When a church person is involved with people committing murder  
and mayhem, others in church are not happy about it,'' he says. 
``But I couldn't stand aloof from people, if they were asking me to 
challenge them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Magee also said he favors bringing United Nations mediators to  
talks on the future of Northern Ireland, which resumed this week. 
</P>
<P>
	``No matter what the (politicians) decide, they've got to keep  
talking,'' he says. ``They can't let the people die.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
 *Catholic, Orthodox leaders set agenda    	
</P>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- When Catholic and Orthodox Christian leaders  
meet in June, they will look for similarities of the two churches 
separated for almost a millennium. 
</P>
<P>
	Cardinal William Keeler and Archbishop Spyridon, primate of the  
Greek Orthodox Church, outlined plans at a meeting at the Basilica 
of the Assumption. 
</P>
<P>
	Keeler said, ``The work now is to see where the church was  
before the division'' between Roman Catholic and Orthodox Christian 
faiths in 1094. ``We have to get to know each other better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The meeting, their first ever in the Western Hemisphere, will  
take place at Mount St. Mary's College in Emmitsburg, chosen for 
its rural seclusion and abundance of chapels and libraries, Keeler 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1988, Catholic-Orthodox dialogue has produced three joint  
statements on theological issues. A 1993 statement, produced at a 
meeting in Lebanon, was essentially an agreement by Catholics not 
to proselytize among the Orthodox, a tension-filled issue that has 
dominated the dialogue for most of the past decade. 
</P>
<P>
	Among issues to be addressed: The possibility of full communion  
between the two churches and the state of churches in Central and 
Eastern Europe since the collapse of communism. 
</P>
<P>
	The Orthodox Christian Church has 300 million followers  
worldwide. It ranks third in size among world Christian 
denominations, behind Roman Catholicism, with about 981.5 million 
and Protestantism, with about 404 million. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
 *Idaho's Lutheran Vietnamese    	
</P>
<P>
	BOISE, Idaho (AP) -- A church has been dedicated to help  
Vietnamese refugees in Idaho's Treasure Valley, who number up to 
3,000. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no other Christian group actively reaching out to  
them because they're not big enough,'' said the Rev. Dan Kramer, 
head of the Peace in Jesus Lutheran Church. He said he expected the 
church to help ``with English classes, tutoring, even giving them 
coats to get through winter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kramer became involved in the cause while interning as vicar of  
two churches in Boise and Nampa, learning some of the language 
while helping church elder Robert Vinh Phan interpret a Bible 
study. 
</P>
<P>
	Phan said his fellow Vietnamese are more familiar with Buddhism  
and Catholicism than with the Lutheran religion, but, he added, 
they are willing to adapt if necessary. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a place where people who don't know English can learn  
it, where people who are having trouble with welfare can get help, 
where people who need to get a driver's license can learn how,'' 
Phan said. ``It's a place where we can meet other Vietnamese and 
take in food for the spirit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
 *Religious miner wins back pay    	
</P>
<P>
	LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- A western Kentucky mining company has  
been ordered to reinstate a miner with full back pay and benefits 
and to pay $25,000 in damages in what the Kentucky Commission on 
Human Rights said was a case of religious discrimination. 
</P>
<P>
	Ted Baker of Beaver Dam had been an employee of Grand Eagle  
Mining Co. of Henderson for 18 years. The company said he was fired 
for sleeping on the job and poor attitude. The commission said 
Baker was fired without a prior written reprimand for poor 
performance or attitude. 
</P>
<P>
	Baker said his problems began in May 1996, when he became a  
Baptist and asked for Sundays off for religious reasons. The 
company had a seven-day work schedule, with exceptions for 
religious observances. 
</P>
<P>
	Baker told his manager about his religious beliefs and took off  
Sunday, June 9, 1996, even though he was scheduled to work. 
</P>
<P>
	Grand Eagle suspended Baker for three days, even though the  
commission said company policy did not call for a suspension until 
the third unexcused absence. 
</P>
<P>
	Later that month, Baker was in his bulldozer awaiting a fuel  
truck when his supervisor came on the scene. Baker was later called 
to the office and accused of sleeping on the job. 
</P>
</TEXT>
