<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Union Pacific Completing Move </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- Union Pacific Corp. is moving the rest of its  
Dallas-based holding company's operation to Omaha, effective July 
1. 
</P>
<P>
	Fifteen people work in the corporate offices, and at least one  
will move to Omaha, one is retiring and one is moving to the 
Washington office, spokesman Gary Schuster said. Others could apply 
for UP job openings in Omaha or elect to leave the company, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Chairman Dick Davidson said moving corporate finance people to  
Omaha last spring proved that corporate offices and the Omaha-based 
railroad operations need to be closer together. 
</P>
<P>
	Davidson said he and other Union Pacific officials will continue  
to spend a lot of time in Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Davidson established an office of the chairman to  
strengthen customer service in the Houston area, at the heart of 
the railroad's chemical belt. Texas also was the heart of the 
railroad's service problems two years ago. The railroad is getting 
back up to speed after gridlock hurt its service nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	Schuster said Union Pacific first moved its corporate  
headquarters to Dallas from Pennsylvania in 1997 to be closer to 
operations with its Skyway Freight and Overnight Transportation 
subsidiaries, but Skway Freight has been sold and Overnight 
probably will be. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
