<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> More Obstacles in Bankruptcy Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A dispute over abortion threatened to scuttle  
a Senate bill to rewrite the bankruptcy laws, while some Democrats 
on Thursday denounced the bill as a giveaway to credit card 
companies that would hurt hard-pressed families. 
</P>
<P>
	A proposal by Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., would require  
bankrupt people found to have violated laws protecting abortion 
clinics to pay those penalties. Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del., called 
the proposal a ``poison pill'' that could kill the bankruptcy 
legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	The way ``to make sure nothing happens (with legislation) is to  
say 'abortion,''' Biden, who supports the bankruptcy overhaul bill, 
said as the Senate Judiciary Committee began a drafting session. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, Sen. Bob Smith, R-N.H., is pushing an opposing  
amendment prohibiting doctors who declare bankruptcy from writing 
off penalties they owe from medical malpractice claims related to 
abortion. 
</P>
<P>
	It's the second time the bipartisan legislation, which would  
make it tougher for people to erase their debts in bankruptcy 
court, has become entangled in sensitive social issues. Last year 
Hillary Rodham Clinton, along with consumer groups and some 
Democrats, complained that the measure would make single mothers 
and children who are owed support by bankrupt fathers take a back 
seat to credit card companies in collecting debts. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House threatened in 1998 to veto a House-passed  
bankruptcy overhaul bill and the Senate adjourned without voting on 
the measure. 
</P>
<P>
	The new Senate bill split the Democrats on the Judiciary  
Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	``It basically stinks,'' Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., said at  
the drafting session. ``You talk about special-interest 
legislation: you've got it right here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He was referring to an ongoing lobbying push for the legislation  
by credit card companies and retail businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, credit card giant Visa USA Inc. increased its  
lobbying bill to $3.6 million from $900,000 in 1997, new disclosure 
reports show. MasterCard International's lobbying expenses rose to 
$1.8 million from $430,000. 
</P>
<P>
	On the other side, consumer groups, unions, civil rights groups  
and bankruptcy attorneys oppose the legislation, saying it favors 
corporate profits over the needs of families struggling with debt. 
</P>
<P>
	Kennedy said the bill had been stripped of consumer protections  
that were included in earlier versions. 
</P>
<P>
	Schumer is proposing amendments that would, for example, bar  
credit card companies from imposing special fees on consumers who 
pay their balances off. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Russ Feingold, D-Wis., called the bill ``irresponsible''  
and ``a gift to special interests.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Biden insisted that the bill is not an attempt to ``stiff  
consumers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Biden, whose home state Delaware is the headquarters site for  
many credit card issuers, and Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., are 
co-sponsors of the bill with Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is essential that we do not allow partisan politics to get  
in the way of implementing fair and reasonable reforms to the 
nation's bankruptcy laws,'' said Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, the 
Judiciary Committee's chairman. ``Under this legislation, if people 
are able to repay their debts, they will be required to do so.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The committee adjourned without completing work on the bill and  
planned to resume next week. 
</P>
<P>
	Both the Senate and House bills would allow federal bankruptcy  
judges to determine a debtor's ability to repay. They would use an 
IRS standard to estimate living expenses and calculate whether the 
payback could be 25 percent or more of the total debt within three 
years. If so, the debtor could be forced into a Chapter 13 
reorganization plan. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Chapter 13 of the U.S. Bankruptcy Code, people must repay  
their debts according to a court-ordered plan. Credit card 
companies complain that too many people take shelter under the more 
lenient Chapter 7, which erases debts, when they could afford to 
restructure debts under Chapter 13. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
