<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> BankBoston Earnings Down Slightly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- BankBoston Corp. reported a 6 percent decline in  
profits for the first quarter on higher expenses and lower venture 
capital income. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank on Thursday posted net income of $223 million, or 75  
cents a share, just 2 cents above Wall Street's estimate. 
BankBoston earned $207 million, or 79 cents a share in the first 
quarter last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues were $1.23 billion, up 19 percent from $1.03 billion in  
the year-ago period. 
</P>
<P>
	``We experienced healthy growth across a number of our  
businesses especially in the fee-based activities,'' Chad Gifford, 
chairman and chief executive of BankBoston, said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank's shares rose $1.56 1/4 to close at $51 on the New York  
Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	The Boston-based company announced last month it would be  
acquired by Fleet Bank, making the combined bank the nation's 
seventh-largest. The deal is expected to close in the second half 
of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	BankBoston reported first-quarter expenses of $806 million, down  
slightly from the end of last year, but up 22 percent from the 
first quarter last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Profits declined for the bank's venture capital arm because of  
lower level of transactions. At the end of March, the Private 
Equity portfolio had a value of $1.4 billion compared with $1.2 
billion in the year-ago period. 
</P>
<P>
	In Brazil, BankBoston's income rose 40 percent, although mutual  
fund fees were down because of the drop in value of the local 
currency. In Argentina, net income improved by 25% from the first 
quarter of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	It's investment banking arm, Robertson Stephens, reported pretax  
income of $30 million, double its income from the fourth quarter 
when financial markets were still shaky. 
</P>
<P>
	BankBoston ended the quarter with total assets of $75.7 billion.  

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
