<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Indy Entry List Totals 84 Cars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Jaques Lazier, the seventh rookie and the  
younger brother of former Indianapolis 500 winner Buddy Lazier, is 
among the final group of entries announced for the May 30 race. 
</P>
<P>
	Another six cars whose entries were postmarked before last  
Friday's deadline were added to the list, raising the total to 84 
eligible to compete for the 33 starting spots. Seventy-five cars 
were entered last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Lazier, 28, who raced in the Indy Lights series last season, was  
assigned to two cars entered by DR-Lazier Racing, a team owned by 
his father, former Indy driver Bob Lazier. Buddy Lazier, the 1996 
winner, is one of three former champions entered in the race and 
will drive for Hemelgarn Racing with teammate Johnny Unser. 
</P>
<P>
	The other former winners are Eddie Cheever, who won last year,  
and Arie Luyendyk, a two-time winner who plans to retire after the 
race. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides Jaques Lazier, the other late entries were for veterans  
Scott Harrington, who was 15th in his only previous start at 
Indianapolis in 1996, and Jimmy Kite, 11th as a rookie last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The others in the 1999 rookie class who have been assigned cars  
are Mike Borkowski, John Hollansworth Jr., Dave Steele, Wim 
Eyckmans, Robby McGehee and Jeret Schroeder. Eyckmans is Cheever's 
teammate and protege; Steele is a Panther Racing teammate of Indy 
Racing League season points leader Scott Goodyear. 
</P>
<P>
	Hemelgarn and A.J. Foyt Enterprises each entered six cars, more  
than any other team. Defending IRL champion Kenny Brack and last 
year's Indy 500 pole winner Billy Boat are driving for Foyt, while 
another teammate could be added later for one of Foyt's other 
entries. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the other drivers is Tony Stewart, a former IRL champion  
who left Team Menard to compete in the NASCAR Winston Cup series 
for team owner Joe Gibbs. Stewart has two cars entered by Tri-Star 
Motorsports, an Indy team he recently put together with Larry 
Curry, his former team manager with Menard, and Andy Card, a former 
Menard public relations man. 
</P>
<P>
	Taking Stewart's place this season with Menard is Greg Ray, who  
had the fastest speed during the recent open testing at the 
Speedway at more than 227 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	Full practice will begin on May 15, with qualifications on May  
22-23. 
</P>
</TEXT>
