<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gillette Earnings Up Slightly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Gillette's earnings rose 4 percent during the  
first quarter as its consumer products businesses turned in a mixed 
performance. 
</P>
<P>
	The personal products maker reported Thursday it earned $269  
million, or 24 cents a share, up from $268 million, or 23 cents a 
share, during the first quarter of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Gillette warned that some of its businesses would  
have disappointing results for the quarter. The company said 
Thursday its earnings were also reduced by higher interest costs 
for its share buyback program. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenue dropped from $2 billion last year to $1.9 billion.  
</P>
<P>
	The company's MACH3 shaving system, which went on sale in the  
United States last July, fed a 33 percent increase in the company's 
North American blade business. But overall sales were tempered by a 
weaker than expected results in the Braun business and in some 
international markets, said Alfred M. Zeien, the company's retiring 
chairman and chief executive officer. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said first-quarter sales and profits for its blade  
and razor division were considerably higher than the year before. 
Sales from Duracell batteries were virtually unchanged, while 
profits were lower. 
</P>
<P>
	Oral-B sales were little changed, but profits grew sharply.  
</P>
<P>
	Gillette stock finished unchanged at $50.31 1/4 a share in New York  
Stock Exchange trading. 
</P>
</TEXT>
