<DOCNO> APW19990415.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 16:45:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore, Bush Lead 2000 Fundraising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Steve Forbes, who spent $37.5 million of his  
own money on his presidential campaign four years ago, reported 
Thursday he is lagging behind most other Republican presidential 
contenders in spending and fund raising. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes gave his campaign $694,000 of his own money and raised  
only $18,538 during the first quarter of 1999, according to 
campaign disclosure reports filed Thursday. He had spent $599,004 
and had just $113,539 in the bank as of March 31. 
</P>
<P>
	At the other end of the fund-raising spectrum, Texas Gov. George  
W. Bush reported raising $7.6 million and Vice President Al Gore, 
the Democratic front-runner, raised $8.9 million. Each had more 
than $6 million in the bank, a huge lead over their competitors. 
</P>
<P>
	GOP candidates Gary Bauer, John McCain and Dan Quayle also broke  
the million-dollar fund-raising barrier, as did former Democratic 
Sen. Bill Bradley, Gore's lone challenger. 
</P>
<P>
	Only Elizabeth Dole, the former head of the American Red Cross,  
trailed Forbes in fund raising among the top GOP contenders. 
</P>
<P>
	One Republican, Lamar Alexander, reported running in the red at  
the end of March. 
</P>
<P>
	Spokeswoman Juleanne Glover Weiss said Forbes didn't begin  
raising money for his campaign until this month, after the deadline 
for reporting. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's been on the phone a great deal,'' Weiss said. ``You won't  
see the seven-digit number until the next filing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Among the expenditures Forbes reported was $254,000 for polling.  
</P>
<P>
	Forbes' ability to finance his own campaign allows him to forgo  
federal matching funds and the spending limits that accompany them. 
The fear that Forbes will spend millions of dollars in the early 
primary states of Iowa and New Hampshire has Bush considering 
whether he, too, will give up the federal funds. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Election Commission report showed Bush raising money  
at a pace of just over $271,000 a day. He had spent $854,000, and 
had $6.8 million in the bank as of March 31. 
</P>
<P>
	``I said I want to make sure the fund raising is real before I  
commit,'' said Bush, who has yet to formally declare his candidacy. 
``I wanted to make sure that behind the polls there was some solid 
support. It appears there is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore led all candidates in fund raising, taking in contributions  
from more than 45,000 people. He spent $2 million, including 
$693,089 for fund raising, and had $6.9 million in the bank. 
</P>
<P>
	At least 6,000 people gave $1,000 each to Gore, including  
actress and singer Barbra Streisand, Eastman Kodak Chief Executive 
Officer George Fisher, and Alex Ferrari, head of MTV Networks. Gore 
has more than 50 people raising $50,000 apiece for him. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley remained financially competitive, raising $4.3 million  
during the first three months of 1999 and finishing the quarter 
with $2.9 million in the bank. He received $1,000 apiece from 
former Chicago Bulls basketball star Michael Jordan and his wife 
Juanita; and $1,000 apiece from former New York Knicks teammate 
Phil Jackson and his wife June. Bradley reported raising another $2 
million in New York City Thursday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Among Republicans:  
</P>
<P>
	--Quayle, the former vice president, raised more than any other  
GOP hopeful except Bush, taking in $2.1 million. But much of that 
money was raised through direct mail, which is expensive; he spent 
$1 million on fund raising. Quayle had 35,251 contributors, more 
than the 23,339 people who gave to Bush. Overall, Quayle spent $1.6 
million on the campaign and had $500,443 in the bank. 
</P>
<P>
	--McCain reported raising $1.8 million and transferred another $2  
million from his Senate campaign fund. He spent $1 million and had 
$2.8 million in the bank. 
</P>
<P>
	--Bauer raised $1.4 million, but ate most of that up by spending  
$881,518. His cash on hand, $489,367, is scarcely more than the 
debts the campaign owes, $425,563. 
</P>
<P>
	--Alexander reported owing $212,405 and having just $86,916 in  
the bank. He raised $748,773 during the first quarter of 1999 and 
spent $661,856. His chief fund-raiser, Ted Welch, said the campaign 
is just starting to take in money; 26 fund-raisers are scheduled 
between May 4 and June 23. ``There's every reason to believe we're 
going to be able to compete in Iowa and New Hampshire and gain the 
momentum needed to raise the additional funds,'' political director 
Brian Kennedy said. 
</P>
<P>
	--Dole raised $685,253 and spent $108,210. She had $578,042 in  
the bank. Spokesman Ari Fleischer said Dole's fund raising is just 
getting under way. ``We consider the first quarter spring training, 
which doesn't count toward the regular season,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	--Another GOP hopeful, Rep. John Kasich of Ohio, is not  
disclosing how much his campaign has raised and spent. Federal 
election law allows potential candidates to raise and spend money 
without disclosing any information as long as the funds are used 
solely to gauge support for a campaign. Kasich campaign officials 
have said the congressman has raised more than $1 million. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990415.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 13:55:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Text of Clinton Remarks to Editors / Presidential Speech  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Text of President Clinton's remarks to the American Society of  
Newspaper Editors on Thursday in San Francisco, as transcribed by 
the Federal Document Clearing House: 
</P>
<P>
	CLINTON: Thank you. Thank you very much, Mr. Seaton,  
distinguished officers and members of the American Society of 
Newspaper Editors. I want to thank you for giving me the 
opportunity to address the crisis in Kosovo, why we're there, what 
our objectives are, how this fits in with our larger vision of the 
future. 
</P>
<P>
	Since I'm here I can't help noting that one of the truly  
striking aspects of this moment is the stark contrast it 
illuminates between a free society with a free press and a closed 
society where the press is used to manipulate people by suppressing 
or distorting the truth. 
</P>
<P>
	In Belgrade today, independent journalists are being persecuted.  
This week, one brave editor was murdered in cold blood. Meanwhile, 
the government-run press has constructed an alternative reality for 
the Serbian people in which the atrocities their soldiers are 
committing in Kosovo simply don't exist. 
</P>
<P>
	Under those conditions, decent people can remain in denial,  
supporting policies that lead them to political and economic ruin. 
Thank goodness our press and free press throughout the world have 
tried to get at and get out the truth to ensure that words like 
``refugees,'' ``displacement,'' ``ethnic cleansing,'' don't become 
stale and lifeless but remain causes for action. 
</P>
<P>
	The tragedy in Kosovo is the result of a meticulously planned  
and long premeditated attack on an entire people simply on the 
basis of their ethnicity and religion -- an attack grounded in a 
philosophy that teaches people to dearly love a piece of land while 
utterly dismissing the humanity of those who occupy it. 
</P>
<P>
	That is what Mr. Milosevic has been doing ever since Yugoslavia  
started breaking up in 1989. For a decade he has been trying to 
build a greater Serbia by using military force to rearrange the 
ethnic character of the nations which emerged from Yugoslavia. That 
is what he did for years in Croatia and horribly in Bosnia -- what 
he is doing in Kosovo now. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, he drove hundreds of thousands of people from their  
homes into the frigid mountains and let them back only after NATO 
threatened to use force. He is now determined to crush all 
resistance to his rule, even if it means turning Kosovo into a 
lifeless wasteland. 
</P>
<P>
	As these difficult days proceed, it is important to remember  
that we have no quarrel with the Serbian people. They were our 
allies in World War II. They have often been our allies. In a 
sense, they are victims of this tragedy, too. And we must 
understand the anguish of Serbian-Americans, who like 
Albanian-Americans are worried about their loved ones back home. 
Americans should not blame Serbs or look down on Serbian-Americans 
because we disagree with the Milosevic government. We must not let 
his ethnic cleansing provoke us to ethnic bias. 
</P>
<P>
	We and our 18 NATO allies are in Kosovo today because we want to  
stop the slaughter and the ethnic cleansing, because we want to 
build a stable, united, prosperous Europe that includes the Balkans 
and its neighbors, and because we don't want the 21st century to be 
dominated by the dark marriage of modern weapons and ancient 
ethnic, racial and religious hatred. 
</P>
<P>
	We cannot simply watch as hundreds of thousands of people are  
brutalized, murder, raped, forced from their homes, their family 
histories erased, all in the name of ethnic pride and purity. NATO 
was pivotal to ending the killing and ethnic cleansing in Bosnia. 
We can do so again and this time we have responded more quickly. 
</P>
<P>
	Were we to stand aside, the atrocities in Kosovo would go on and  
on. Neighboring democracies, as you see, would be overwhelmed by 
permanent refugees and demoralized by the failure of democracy's 
alliance. The Kosovar Albanians would become a people without a 
homeland, a burden to host countries, a magnet for radical 
ideologies, a breeding ground for unending warfare in the Balkans. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO would be discredited -- yes, because it made promises not  
kept, but more important because its values and vision of Europe 
would be profoundly damaged. Ultimately, the conflict in Kosovo 
would spread anyway, and we would have to act anyway. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, when we decided to launch the air campaign after Mr.  
Milosevic rejected peace, we believed there was at least a 
possibility that our readiness to act would deter him from moving 
forward, as it had in the past. But we also understood clearly that 
with 40,000 troops and over 250 tanks massed in and around Kosovo, 
he might intensify his repression and go on with his planned 
attack, as I made clear in my address to the nation the night the 
airstrikes began. 
</P>
<P>
	There was only one possibility that we and our NATO allies were  
not willing to entertain: that the international community would 
look the other way in the face of this brutality. Now, the NATO air 
campaign has been underway for three weeks, often interrupted or 
limited by bad weather. This is, however, a good time to assess 
what has been accomplished and where we're going. 
</P>
<P>
	Mr. Milosevic's strategy has been to complete the ethnic  
cleansing, then break the unity of NATO by taking the bombs and 
offering phony concessions. But NATO is more united today than when 
the operation began. Whether they are conservatives in Spain, 
socialists in France, New Labor in Britain, or Greens in Germany, 
the leaders of Europe and the people they represent are determined 
to maintain and intensify our attacks until Mr. Milosevic's forces 
leave Kosovo and the refugees return under the protection of an 
international force, or until his military is weakened to the point 
when he can no longer keep his vice-like grip on Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	At the beginning of the operation, we focused properly on  
Serbia's highly developed air defenses to reduce the risks to our 
pilots. There are still significant air defenses up, and therefore 
there is still risk with every mission. But we have degraded the 
system to the point that now NATO can fly 24 hours a day, not 
simply at night. We've struck at Serbia's machinery of repression, 
at the infrastructure that supports it. We've destroyed all of 
Serbia's refineries, half of its capacity to produce ammunition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990415.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 05:25:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Congress Complains About Tax System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- This being income tax day, Congress is once  
again chorusing complaints about the burdens, complexities and, by 
Republican accounting, excessive rates of the system it created. 
</P>
<P>
	As usual, the talk will yield to inaction on sweeping reform --  
and another round of targeted tax breaks will make it more 
complicated next time. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton wants an array of them, Republicans want fewer  
breaks and across-the-board rate cuts, too. The GOP budget seeks 
about $800 billion in tax reductions over the next decade, up to 
$15 billion of them next year. Details are to come. 
</P>
<P>
	So the 1999 debate will be about how much to cut, and for whom,  
without the push for a simplifying overhaul the Republicans had 
said was coming. 
</P>
<P>
	At the top of the GOP list now is an end to the marriage tax  
penalty, which causes about 21 million couples to pay more on their 
joint income than they would if they were single. Proposals to do 
that are geared to income, meaning new instructions and tax forms. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton wants targeted tax breaks for child care, senior care,  
education and more. The administration has just proposed $300 tax 
credits for middle-income Americans who invest in proposed new 
personal retirement accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	All those changes for specific purposes and groups would add to  
the more than 2.8 million words in the tax code, triple the Bible, 
the complexity critics note. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past two years, Congress voted 1,260 changes in the  
system, reflected in 11 new forms and 177 revised ones issued by 
the IRS for 1998 income taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	By IRS estimate, it takes 11 hours and 34 minutes for the  
average taxpayer to prepare the basic Form 1040 for income taxes. 
Itemize deductions and it's another 4 hours, 28 minutes. With 
capital gains, add 6 hours and 41 minutes. Figuring taxes on 
interest and dividends takes an additional hour and 12 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	That's why more than half the taxpayers filing an estimated  
126.1 million returns this year paid to get them prepared by tax 
professionals. 
</P>
<P>
	And it is why the complexity complaints are a fixture. There is  
a Republican effort in Congress to fix it by decree -- scrap the 
current income tax code at the end of 2003, to be replaced by a 
simpler system, a flat tax or consumption tax. 
</P>
<P>
	That deadline is a fallback; the earlier one was the end of  
2001. 
</P>
<P>
	The later one won't succeed, either. Democrats oppose the idea  
of ending the graduated income tax, and there is no Republican 
consensus on whether or how to do it. GOP leaders had said they'd 
settle on a plan in 1998 and act on it this year, but they didn't 
and they won't. 
</P>
<P>
	The tax code is built into the American economic system, and it  
would take time to build it out, assuming the political agreement 
and will to do it. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Forbes, the Republican presidential candidate who made the  
flat tax his issue and pushed it, briefly, to the top of the 
campaign agenda in 1996, is running for the 2000 nomination, still 
advocating a simple, 17 percent tax. This time, his agenda is 
broader, and while he says there is broadening support for tax 
simplification, he acknowledges it is not an easy issue to sell 
because people mistrust what politicians tell them about taxes. 
``It gets to the feeling that it's like the weather,'' Forbes said. 
``That no matter what you say, not much is going to be done about 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said it will be a presidential campaign issue, and there will  
be action to simplify the system within four or five years. 
</P>
<P>
	A poll conducted for The Associated Press showed 66 percent of  
Americans think the system is too complicated, compared with less 
than half in a survey three years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	More than half in the poll late last month liked the idea of a  
flat tax -- but only a third said they'd be willing to give up their 
current deductions. 
</P>
<P>
	An earlier Fox News poll reflected the doubts about targeted tax  
breaks. In that survey, 62 percent said that when Clinton talks 
about targeted tax cuts, they think it means a cut for someone 
else, not for them. An NBC News-Wall Street Journal poll showed 53 
percent of Americans think they are paying more than their fair 
share in taxes. Forty-five percent said their tax share is about 
right. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- Walter R. Mears, vice president and special  
correspondent for The Associated Press, has reported on Washington 
and national politics for more than 30 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990415.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 11:35:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bill Rodgers Returns to Marathon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- There will be a familiar sight at the start of the  
Boston Marathon Monday: Bill Rodgers, a knit hat atop his thick 
blond hair, his hands covered with white gloves and a big smile on 
his face. 
</P>
<P>
	Rodgers will be back in his element, and the hundreds of  
thousands of spectators lining the 26-mile, 385-yard course will be 
cheering loudly for ``Boston Billy,'' even though he has no chance 
of winning the race. 
</P>
<P>
	Rodgers is 51 now, and his goals are different than they were  
nearly 25 years ago, when he won his first of four Boston Marathon 
titles. 
</P>
<P>
	This time, he will be aiming to break the over-50 course record  
for an American of 2 hours, 31 minutes, 34 seconds, set by Norm 
Green in 1983. 
</P>
<P>
	``I run for marks,'' Rodgers said. ``I've got my sights set on  
several age-group records.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last Sunday, he tried breaking another of Green's records,  
52:53, for 10 miles, at the Cherry Blossom Run in Washington, but 
he missed by 1:11. However, he did finish 33rd overall among the 
6,200 entrants in the race. 
</P>
<P>
	Rodgers still is a bundle of energy and youthfulness -- despite  
his age -- and never has lost his enthusiasm for racing. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, he ran 29 races at various road distances, up from  
his usual quota of 20 or 22. Since 1987, when he turned 40, he has 
been consistently ranked among the top masters runners in the 
world. In 1997, he set six U.S. records for 49-year-olds at 
distances from 5 kilometers (3.1 miles) to the half-marathon (13.1 
miles). 
</P>
<P>
	This will be Rodgers' first serious Boston Marathon since 1990  
and his first serious marathon anywhere since 1992. He ran in 
Boston's centennial marathon in 1996, but only ``on cruise 
control'' with friends, clocking 2:53. 
</P>
<P>
	He had intended to run Boston last year, but didn't ``train  
properly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This time, he has been preparing diligently since December, but  
even though this will be the 58th marathon of his illustrious 
career and 16th at Boston, he surprisingly has some trepidation. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is trickier and I'm nervous, because it's my first real  
marathon in seven years,'' he said. ``But I'm psyched for the 
race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rodgers' last ``real'' marathon was the inaugural Vietnam  
International Marathon in 1992. Rodgers was determined to win that 
race and at 21 miles, he was in front. But the 90-degree heat and 
100-percent humidity took its toll. 
</P>
<P>
	``I started to crumble and had to walk the last three miles,''  
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rodgers staggered across the finish line at 3:19 -- 43 minutes  
slower than his previous worst marathon performance. 
</P>
<P>
	In his last true Boston Marathon nine years ago, he finished  
fifth in the Masters Division at 2:20:46. He ran his first Boston 
race in 1973 and did not finish. The following year, he was 14th at 
2:19:34, then made his big breakthrough in 1975, winning at 
2:09:55. 
</P>
<P>
	He broke the American record held by 1972 Olympic gold medalist  
Frank Shorter and the course record of 2:10:30 set by England's Ron 
Hill in 1970. That was despite stopping four times for water and 
once to tie a shoe lace. 
</P>
<P>
	``Winning that race changed my life,'' he said. ``Before that, I  
was just another American marathoner. To crack 2:10 at Boston was 
unbelievable. 
</P>
<P>
	``After that, I was ranked the fourth-best marathoner in the  
world. I started becoming an international runner. I felt I could 
win any race. Before that, I was a competitive runner but didn't 
think I could win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rodgers went on to win Boston again in 1978, 1979 (breaking his  
American and course records with a 2:09:27) and 1980. He also won 
the New York City Marathon four times -- from 1976-79. Overall, he 
has 21 marathons victories, the last being the Orange Bowl Marathon 
at Miami in 1983. He also has run 28 marathons under 2:16, the most 
in history. 
</P>
<P>
	Rodgers knows he can't run nearly that fast now.  
</P>
<P>
	``If I can break 2:31, I will walk away very happy ... just as  
happy as the winner,'' he said. ``Those records are the carrots ... 
That's what lures me.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
