<DOCNO> APW19990415.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 16:35:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Vanderbilt, DiNardo Claim Victory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Both Vanderbilt and Gerry DiNardo  
claimed victory Thursday in their long-running dispute over whether 
the former football coach broke his contract and owes the 
university $281,886. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Cincinnati sided with  
Vanderbilt on Wednesday in finding DiNardo broke terms of a 
five-year contract in 1994 when he took the coaching job at LSU. 
</P>
<P>
	But the court sent the case back to U.S. District Court in  
Nashville to determine whether he also violated the terms of a 
two-year contract extension he signed that year. 
</P>
<P>
	``We won 75 percent of the case, and it was a draw on 25  
percent,'' Vanderbilt lawyer John Callison said. '' ... From our 
perspective, it's a great victory. It's not just about money, it's 
a matter of principle. We honor our contracts with the coaches; the 
coaches should honor their obligation to us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	DiNardo said in a statement from Baton Rouge, La., he was ``very  
pleased'' with the appellate court decision. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Robert Echols ruled in 1997 that DiNardo  
owed Vanderbilt $281,886 for the final year of the original 
five-year contract and the two-year extension. 
</P>
<P>
	The figure came from the base salary of $91,781 per year for the  
three years, plus $6,541 for the time between DiNardo's Dec. 12, 
1994, resignation and the Jan. 5 expiration date on his contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Callison said because the appeals court ruled DiNardo broke his  
original contract, he owes the school a minimum of one year's 
salary plus interest. 
</P>
<P>
	DiNardo said he will pay one year's salary if Vanderbilt drops  
the case. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to restate that I remain prepared to satisfy my  
obligations under my original employment agreement. In fact, I have 
filed papers with the federal district court in Nashville stating 
that I would fulfill that obligation,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Callison says Vanderbilt isn't willing to settle for that.  
</P>
<P>
	``We have said all along that we are entitled not only to the  
last year, but to the two-year extension. We entered into them in 
good faith. We expect coach DiNardo to honor them in good faith,'' 
Callison said. 
</P>
<P>
	The key questions are whether DiNardo's brother and lawyer,  
Larry DiNardo, had to approve the extension before it became 
enforceable and whether Larry DiNardo's failure to object to the 
terms amounted to approval. 
</P>
<P>
	On Aug. 17, 1994, Gerry DiNardo signed the extension but told  
then-Vanderbilt athletic director Paul Hoolahan, ``Larry needs to 
see a copy before this thing is finalized,'' according to court 
documents. 
</P>
<P>
	The Tennessean reported on Aug. 20, 1994, that DiNardo's  
contract had been extended and the coach stated publicly that he 
was ``excited'' about it. 
</P>
<P>
	Four days later, Callison faxed an unsigned copy of the draft to  
Larry DiNardo, writing on it to ``let me know if you have any 
questions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Sept. 27, Callison faxed Larry DiNardo about his brother's  
television and radio contract, adding that: ``I would like your 
comments on the contract extension.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Larry DiNardo testified that he neither participated in the  
drafting nor suggested any changes to the contract extension. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is not unreasonable to infer that the parties had not  
completely negotiated the details of the contract extension; the 
original contract did not expire for another year,'' Appeals Court 
Judge John Gibson wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	``We cannot say that Larry DiNardo's failure to object by Dec.  
12, 1994, constitutes an acceptance of the addendum.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990415.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 12:35:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Delta Changes Boeing Jet Order </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Delta Air Lines announced today it has scrapped  
an order for four Boeing 777 jets, which were to be delivered early 
next year, because its pilots have yet to agree on a labor contract 
for flying the new planes. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, Delta has asked Boeing to deliver four 767-300ER  
aircraft. The smaller plane seats 197 passengers, compared with 273 
in Delta's configuration of the 777. 
</P>
<P>
	Delta had ordered a total of 14 Boeing 777s for use on its  
international routes. It has already taken delivery on the first 
two, which are to be put into service May 1. The order scrapped 
Thursday was for four more to be delivered between December and 
next April. 
</P>
<P>
	Airline spokesman Bill Berry said Delta and the Air Line Pilots  
Association are far apart in their negotiations on a contract that 
would cover pay and work rules for pilots flying the 777. 
</P>
<P>
	Delta has offered its pilots an ``industry-leading'' pay package  
for the 777, but the union's current offer is 47 percent higher 
than that, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We felt that there was a likelihood our pilots would not be  
flying these airplanes when they were delivered, and we took the 
action to defer them indefinitely.'' 
</P>
<P>
	ALPA spokeswoman Karen McGuffey said the union was surprised by  
Delta's decision because the negotiations are still at an early 
stage. 
</P>
<P>
	``For them to represent this as a consequence of pilot  
negotiations ... in our opinion is a confrontational move and does 
not really reflect the realities of the negotiating process,'' she 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if an agreement would have been likely before the 777s  
arrived, she said, ``We are committed to reaching a fair 
agreement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Berry said he's not sure whether future deliveries of 777s might  
be affected if the negotiations drag on. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're very concerned about the 777 program overall,'' he said.  
``But at the moment all we've done is indefinitely deferred four 
orders.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The two planes that will begin flying May 1 can be operated for  
six months under the current pilot contract. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990415.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 10:46:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Cohen: US Casualties Could Be High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration, signaling that the  
NATO air campaign in Yugoslavia could stretch into summer, said 
today the prospect for American casualties was ``very real and 
high.'' U.S. officials expressed regret for an accidental NATO 
attack on a refugee convoy. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do try to reduce the risks to innocent human beings,''  
Defense Secretary William Cohen said, testifying before the Senate 
Armed Services Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen sought to explain the ``extraordinary circumstances''  
surrounding Wednesday's incident in Kosovo, saying the pilot was 
under anti-aircraft artillery fire and had to make a split-second 
decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``We go to extraordinary lengths to protect civilians,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Cohen and Gen. Henry H. Shelton, chairman of the Joint  
Chiefs of Staff, when asked if the campaign could continue for 
``many, many, many weeks or even months,'' said yes. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not going to be quick or easy or neat,'' Cohen said.  
</P>
<P>
	Shelton said NATO has been very fortunate in losing only one  
plane, the downing of an F-117A stealth fighter March 27. The pilot 
was rescued. Three U.S. soldiers also were captured near the 
Macedonian-Yugoslav border and remain in Serb custody. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the prospect for casualties remains very real and  
high,'' Shelton said, echoing Cohen's warning there's a probability 
of U.S. deaths. ``There is no such thing as a risk-free military 
operation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen and Shelton said using ground troops is not under  
consideration and they urged lawmakers to give the air campaign, 
which began March 24, more time to work to stop Yugoslav President 
Slobodan Milosevic's fight against ethnic Albanians in the Serbian 
province. 
</P>
<P>
	``The reason that we have gone forward as we have with an air  
campaign is that there was not a consensus in the NATO alliance to 
do anything but this,'' Cohen said. ``This really is a battle of 
freedom over fear. ... It's a battle of democracy over 
dictatorship.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, testifying before a House  
Appropriations subcommittee, said the flood of refugees and their 
brutal treatment have steeled NATO's determination against 
Milosevic. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're prepared to inflict such damage on his military that he  
either accepts the outcome we seek, or the balance of power in 
Kosovo will shift against him at a time when his actions, far from 
destroying his opposition, are galvanizing its strength and 
determination,'' Albright said. 
</P>
<P>
	Members of the foreign operations subcommittee expressed concern  
that the United States is spreading its resources too thin. Rep. 
C.W. Bill Young, R-Fla., chairman of the Appropriations Committee, 
told Albright that resources being taken from the Korean region -- 
including an aircraft carrier, U2 surveillance planes and F15 
fighter jets -- and moved to the Balkans were increasing U.S. 
vulnerability. 
</P>
<P>
	``I worry about North Korea,'' he said. Young said that the $4  
billion figure on an emergency supplemental bill to pay for Kosovo 
that that administration is suggesting ``would be totally 
inadequate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to do more than just replace the bullets and the  
missiles,'' Young said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration is putting together an emergency  
budget request to pay the U.S. share of NATO operations. White 
House budget chief Jacob Lew met for nearly an hour Wednesday with 
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., who said U.S. officials 
were discussing something in the range of $4 billion to $8 billion. 
He said the administration wants to pay for the entire Balkans 
campaign, including refugees, using part of the expected $111 
billion federal surplus. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, that's not what we'll get our members to go along  
with,'' Lott said. 
</P>
<P>
	Many Republicans seem eager to pay for military costs of the  
crisis with the surplus while finding budget cuts to pay for the 
rest of it. 
</P>
<P>
	House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., said today he had asked  
President Clinton to explain to the American people the long- and 
short-term goals in Kosovo and to provide a ``realistic appraisal 
of what this is going to cost.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the House would debate the matter once he receives an  
emergency funding request from the administration. ``I plan to have 
an open debate on that,'' he said. ``That's where the Congress has 
its just place in this scenario'' since it controls the 
government's purse strings, Hastert said. 
</P>
<P>
	The NATO air campaign is in its fourth week.  
</P>
<P>
	The U.S.-led Gulf War in 1991 lasted only six weeks.  
</P>
<P>
	In the latest incident of NATO-caused civilian casualties, NATO  
officials said today that a preliminary investigation shows an 
allied aircraft ``mistakenly'' dropped a bomb on a vehicle in a 
convoy of ethnic Albanian refugees in Kosovo on Wednesday. NATO 
aircraft had been targeting a military convoy, but also apparently 
struck at a nearby mixed military-civilian convoy. 
</P>
<P>
	``Serb police or military vehicles may have been in or around  
the (refugee) convoy,'' NATO said in a statement from Brussels, 
Belgium. ``NATO regrets any harm to innocent civilians.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yugoslav officials had said Wednesday that NATO had struck a  
tractor in the refugee convoy, killing 64 people and wounding 20. 
But officials at NATO and the Pentagon initially denied the report 
and suggested the Serbs had attacked refugees in retaliation for 
the NATO airstrike. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, U.N. officials said 600 women and children refugees  
reported being attacked by Serb aircraft as they fled from Prizen, 
Kosovo, toward Albania, according to the Pentagon. 
</P>
<P>
	In a move to bolster NATO forces, Apache attack helicopters  
began arriving in Albania on Wednesday and the full contingent of 
24 was expected by today or Friday. NATO and President Clinton need 
to give final approval for the gunships to be used in battle. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly 80 fresh U.S. warplanes also were arriving today in  
Europe to join NATO airstrikes, including 24 F-16 jet-fighters, 
four low-flying A-10 attack airplanes, six Marine EA-6B radar 
jammers to interfere with Serb air defenses, 38 refueling tankers 
and half a dozen cargo planes. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pentagon said Serbs have fired dozens of surface-to-air  
missiles at allied planes in the past two days in the biggest 
demonstration yet of anti-aircraft fire. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of the buildup, the Clinton administration is preparing  
within days to call up at least several thousand military 
reservists and approve deploying 300 more warplanes to join NATO 
airstrikes. That would bring the total air power to 1,000 aircraft 
-- two-thirds of them American. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990415.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 10:46:40 </DATE_TIME>
