<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Flyers' Recchi To Undergo Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Philadelphia Flyers forward Mark Recchi,  
given a scare by his second injury in three weeks, will undergo 
post-concussion tests Friday to determine when he can return to the 
ice. 
</P>
<P>
	Recchi, acquired from Montreal on March 10 to bolster the  
Flyers' offense for the playoffs, is out for at least the two 
remaining regular-season games. His status for the playoffs depends 
on the result of the tests and exams by neurosurgeons in Pittsburgh 
scheduled for Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The safest thing I can tell you is, he's certainly not going  
to play in the two remaining games,'' Flyers team doctor Jeff 
Hartzell said Thursday. ``The question is, what about the first 
round of the playoffs? I still can't give an answer to that 
question.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Recchi suffered his second concussion in three weeks, and third  
of his career, when he was checked into the glass in a 2-2 tie with 
Buffalo Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	He also suffered a concussion March 22 when he missed a check  
and went head first into the glass at Toronto. Recchi sat out for 
three games, came back and experienced some post-concussion 
symptoms after an April 1 game against Nashville, the same game in 
which team captain and leading scorer Eric Lindros suffered a 
season-ending collapsed lung. 
</P>
<P>
	Recchi was hospitalized for one night in Nashville after  
complaining of nausea and dizziness and was sidelined for two more 
games before returning to the lineup last Thursday against 
Pittsburgh. 
</P>
<P>
	This time, he's complained of headaches and neck soreness, but  
nothing like the pain he felt in Nashville. Tests will determine 
whether his neurological readings have strayed from the baseline 
measurements many athletes receive to guard against post-concussion 
syndrome. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel great physically,'' said Recchi, who can work out but  
not participate in contact drills. ``Obviously, I'm very frustrated 
and disappointed. I really want to help this team right now, and 
it's kind of up in the air with what's happening.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Recchi still doesn't believe he came back too soon after the  
first concussion. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's real easy to say now,'' Recchi said. ``I don't believe I  
did. I felt good. I felt 100 percent, and it's just unfortunate. 
There's always going to be skeptics. I felt good enough to play, 
and I wanted to help. That's the bottom line.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lindros is out for at least the first round of the playoffs  
while recovering from a collapsed right lung. Lindros was released 
from the hospital Monday, four days after having blood clots 
surgically removed from his chest cavity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
