<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court May Hear Immigration Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Gov. Gray Davis asked a federal  
appeals court Thursday to mediate a dispute over a ballot measure -- 
bottled up in court for five years -- that seeks to cut off 
schooling to illegal immigrants. 
</P>
<P>
	Approved by 59 percent of voters in 1994, Proposition 187 has  
not been implemented. A federal court found the measure 
unconstitutional last year, but then-Gov. Pete Wilson appealed that 
decision. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis, a Democrat who opposes Prop 187, could have thwarted the  
initiative by refusing to pursue Wilson's appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, Davis asked the U.S. 9th Circuit Court of Appeal's  
mediation panel to resolve the proposition. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm a governor, not a judge. I have taken an oath to enforce  
all the laws of our state and our nation, regardless of my personal 
views on those laws,'' Davis said. 
</P>
<P>
	The initiative would exclude illegal immigrants from public  
schools and eliminate non-emergency health and welfare services for 
which they remain eligible. It also would require public agencies 
and employees to report suspected illegal immigrants. 
</P>
<P>
	The question of whether to continue the appeal has developed  
into the most significant political quandary of the early months of 
Davis' administration. 
</P>
<P>
	He was faced with the dilemma of pursing the appeal and angering  
Hispanics and other opponents to the proposition, or letting the 
appeal drop and anger those who voted in favor of the measure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
