<DOCNO> APW19990415.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 14:45:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> USDA Pricing Overhaul Opposed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Less than a month after Agriculture Secretary  
Dan Glickman released his plan to overhaul the federal milk pricing 
system, some members of Congress have introduced legislation to 
overturn the proposal. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency's recommended changes for the prices of fluid milk  
would hurt dairy farmers and consumers, lawmakers said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The secretary's action defies common sense,'' said Rep. John  
McHugh, R-N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
	Added Rep. Bob Etheridge, D-N.C.: ``A reform plan for dairy  
pricing that puts farmers out of business and does not benefit 
consumers is a complete failure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A department spokesman, Andy Solomon, responded: ``During the  
debate over the farm bill, Congress chose not to address this issue 
and left the massive task of reform to Secretary Glickman. Without 
hesitation, we've really worked aggressively to bring about that 
reform.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers defended their decision to move forward with a bill  
even though Glickman's proposal must win approval from dairy 
farmers before it could take effect Oct. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that would be irresponsible of this Congress, to say  
we're going to see what farmers are going to do,'' McHugh said. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 100 members of Congress are supporting the bill. The  
National Milk Producers Federation, which represents dairy farmers, 
also supports changing Glickman's plan. The International Dairy 
Foods Association, which represents processors, initially had 
expressed reservations with Glickman's proposal but said Thursday 
the plan was ``a much-needed step towards reform.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At issue are the nation's milk pricing regions, which are  
divided into what are called milk marketing orders. The orders set 
the price that processors pay dairy farmers, much like a minimum 
wage. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1996 farm law ordered Glickman to consolidate the nation's  
current 31 orders. Glickman's proposal reduces those regions to 11 
but it also changes some of the formulas by which dairy farmers are 
paid -- the main point of contention for the bill's supporters. 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents to the USDA plan say it would lower the minimum price  
received by dairy farmers, potentially costing them nearly $200 
million a year, according to the National Milk Producers 
Federation. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, they want to see Glickman use an option that was part  
of his draft proposal released last year and supported by many 
lawmakers. That version is closer to the price levels now in place, 
so it would not hurt producers, proponents say. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can make it more market-oriented without forgetting that  
both consumers and farmers benefit from it,'' said Jerry Kozak, 
chief executive officer of the milk producers group. 
</P>
<P>
	Charles Garrison, executive director of the South East Dairy  
Farmer Association, said many southeastern states already have a 
shortage of dairy farmers and more could leave the business if 
revenues were projected to drop. 
</P>
<P>
	``That ultimately could make milk higher for consumers because  
it costs more to bring milk in,'' Garrison said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
