<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Pleads Guilty to Clinton Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EUGENE, Ore. (AP) -- A man who planted two pipe bombs at an  
airport prior to a visit by President Clinton pleaded guilty 
Thursday to threatening to kill him. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeffery Loring Pickering, 50, pleaded guilty to five federal  
charges, one of which carries a mandatory 10-year sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	Pickering admitted planting the pipe bombs June 12, 1998, one  
day before Clinton arrived to meet with families of victims from a 
fatal high school shooting in nearby Springfield, Ore. 
</P>
<P>
	The bombs were found in a culvert behind the Oregon Air and  
Space Museum adjacent to the Eugene Airport. A police bomb squad 
detonated the explosives and the president's visit was not 
disrupted. 
</P>
<P>
	Pickering also admitted to threatening Clinton by making  
telephone calls saying the president would be shot or blown up by 
explosives planted along his motorcade route. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
