<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3:20 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	3 Die in Mormon Library Shooting  
</P>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Two people were killed and four others  
were shot today by a gunman who entered the Mormon church's Family 
History Library and began firing before being fatally wounded by 
police. Police SWAT teams were combing the building to determine 
whether another gunman was inside the building more than two hours 
after the shooting began. Thirty people remained on the second 
floor and it was feared they were being held by a second gunman. 
But they later told police by telephone they had locked themselves 
in a room, said Salt Lake police Lt. Phil Kirk. Mayor Deedee 
Corradini told reporters that a library security guard and a female 
patron had died of their wounds and the unidentified suspect had 
also died. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Defends NATO Air Campaign  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- President Clinton defended NATO air raids  
in defense of Kosovo today, telling America's newspaper editors the 
bombing stems from ``a meticulously planned and long premeditated 
attack on an entire people,'' the ethnic Albanians driven from the 
province by the Serbs. ``We and our NATO allies are in Kosovo today 
because we want to stop the slaughter and the ethnic cleansing,'' 
Clinton told the American Society of Newspaper Editors. 

</P>
<P>
	Cohen: Prospect of Casualties High  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Signaling that the NATO air campaign in  
Yugoslavia could stretch into summer, the Clinton administration 
said today the prospect for American casualties is ``very real and 
high,'' and U.S. officials expressed regret for an accidental NATO 
attack on a refugee convoy. ``We do try to reduce the risks to 
innocent human beings,'' Defense Secretary William Cohen said. 
Cohen and Gen. Henry H. Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of 
Staff, told the Senate Armed Services Committee to give the air 
campaign more time to work. 

</P>
<P>
	Congress Approves Final 2000 Budget  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- With unusual speed, Congress approved a final  
$1.74 trillion budget for fiscal 2000 today that Republicans hope 
will sharpen their image as tax cutters and as a party that has 
moved beyond President Clinton's impeachment. The Senate approved 
the GOP-written plan today by a 54-44 vote that was along party 
lines. The House passed the package yesterday by 220-208 in another 
sharply partisan vote. The measure maps a 10-year tax cut of at 
least $778 billion. Passage today marks only the second time 
Congress has completed the measure on time since setting the April 
15 deadline in 1987. 

</P>
<P>
	Evidence of New Solar System Found  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- The first evidence of the existence of  
another solar system somewhat like our own was reported today. The 
discovery indicates that the Milky Way, which contains about 200 
billion stars, probably has numerous planetary systems, San 
Francisco State University researchers said. Astronomers knew one 
planet was circulating around Upsilon Andromedae, 44 light years 
from Earth. But after studying 107 stars for 11 years at the Lick 
Observatory near San Jose, scientists said evidence of two 
additional planets has been spotted. ``It implies that planets can 
form more easily than we ever imagined,'' said researcher Debra 
Fischer. 

</P>
<P>
	House Impeachment Probe Cost $1.2M  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House paid its top impeachment  
investigators as much as $20,000 a month, part of the $1.2 
million-plus price tag for the five-month congressional proceedings 
that ended with President Clinton's acquittal, expense records 
show. In addition, chief Republican investigator David Schippers 
and Democratic counsel Abbe Lowell were given special consultant 
status that allowed them to bypass congressional restrictions. 
While Democrats have attacked the entire inquiry as an unnecessary 
expense, committee chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill., said Schippers and 
Lowell were worth the money. 

</P>
<P>
	Man Arrested for Fake News Report  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- An employee of California-based PairGain  
Technologies Inc. was arrested today on federal charges of 
fabricating a Bloomberg news service report and posting it on the 
Internet, driving up the company's stock. The FBI arrested Gary 
Dale Hoke at his Raleigh, N.C., home on charges of securities fraud 
for allegedly disseminating false information about the company, 
the U.S. attorney's office in Los Angeles said. Securities fraud is 
punishable by 10 years in prison and a $1 million fine. 

</P>
<P>
	Pinochet May Not Be Freed Soon  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Former Chilean dictator Gen. Augusto Pinochet  
faces the prospect of more months -- if not years -- under guard 
after Britain's top law enforcement official ruled today that Spain 
can continue seeking his extradition. The 83-year-old general must 
remain confined to his rented mansion outside London, guarded 24 
hours a day, while his lawyers battle with Spanish prosecutors. 
Human rights groups hailed the decision. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Up 25, Nasdaq Down 20  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 3 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were  
down 25.25 points at 10,436.91. On the NYSE, advancers led 
decliners 1,658-1,303. The Nasdaq was down 20.77 at 2,486.51. 

</P>
<P>
	Gretzky Promises Decision by Sunday  
</P>
<P>
	RYE, N.Y. (AP) -- If Wayne Gretzky does decide to retire,  
tonight's game in Ottawa will be his last in his native land. The 
game against the Senators will be broadcast nationally in Canada 
and as many as 200 journalists are expected. Gretzky, 38, says 
he'll decide by Sunday whether to end his 20-year NHL career. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
</P>
</TEXT>
