<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TIJUANA, Mexico (AP) -- A Mexican university has canceled a U.S.  
professor's photo exhibit critical of the North American Free Trade 
Agreement and working conditions in Tijuana factories. 
</P>
<P>
	The Autonomous University of Baja California, in the border city  
of Tijuana, abruptly called off the exhibit April 8 after receiving 
complaints from local factory owners about leaflets advertising the 
show. 
</P>
<P>
	Fred Lonidier, a professor in the visual arts department at the  
University of California, San Diego, distributed the leaflets, said 
Rene Andrade Peterson, the school's vice rector. 
</P>
<P>
	``What bothers us is that he's using the university for this,''  
Andrade said. ``We, as a university, cannot be for or against the 
free trade agreement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lonidier said his photos are intended to provoke discussion  
about NAFTA -- the 1994 agreement that created a free-trade zone 
among the United States, Mexico and Canada -- and conditions in 
export-assembly factories known as maquiladoras. 
</P>
<P>
	Factory conditions are a sensitive issue in Tijuana, which has  
about 600 maquiladoras, more than any other city in Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- A moderate explosion shook the crater of the  
Popocatepetl volcano Thursday, sending a plume of ash two miles 
into the air. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Center for the Prevention of Disasters said the  
eruption could cause a light fall of ash northeast of the 
17,925-foot volcano, which is about 40 miles southeast of Mexico 
City. 
</P>
<P>
	Popocatepetl has been spewing vapor, ash and rock intermittently  
since December 1994. Until then, it had been largely dormant since 
1927. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	TUCUMAN, Argentina (AP) -- Researchers exploring a volcanic  
region in northwest Argentina have found the remains of a baby, 
believed to be hundreds of years old, an archeologist said 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The skeletal body of an infant, apparently 4 to 6 months old,  
was virtually intact and swaddled in brittle leather, said Dr. 
Carlos Aschero, an archeologist at the University of Tucuman. 
</P>
<P>
	He said his staff was conducting tests to determine the baby's  
sex and date the remains. 
</P>
<P>
	The baby was found buried in a fetal position under four feet of  
volcanic rock, the archeologist said. 
</P>
<P>
	Aschero said the remains were discovered in December, but were  
widely publicized only after other recent discoveries. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, a team led by American archeologist Johan Reinhard  
announced the discovery of three 500-year-old Inca mummies in 
near-perfect condition. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) -- A two-day strike by secondary  
school teachers kept 300,000 students out of class on Thursday. 
Organizers said they would return to work on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The teachers' union said about 18,000 teachers were taking part  
in the strike to demand that their salaries be raised to about 
$3.18 per hour from $1.70 over the next four years. 
</P>
<P>
	Education Minister Ramon Calix Figueroa threatened to dock the  
teachers' pay for any time missed during the strike. 
</P>
<P>
	Secondary school teachers earn an average of about $200 a month,  
working six-hour days. The average wage in Honduras is $500 a 
month. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) -- The son of former military leader  
Gen. Omar Torrijos holds a strong lead in Panama's presidential 
race, according to a poll published Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin Torrijos, a 35-year-old economist from the governing  
Democratic Revolutionary Party, was favored by 44 percent of those 
polled by the Cid Gallup company, the newspaper El Panama America 
reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Mireya Moscoso, from a coalition led by the Arnulfista Party,  
was second with 34 percent and banker Alberto Vallarino, from 
another coalition, was third with 13 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The poll of 1,200 people was conducted earlier this month and  
had a margin of error of 2.8 percentage points. 
</P>
<P>
	Omar Torrijos led a military coup that deposed former President  
Arnulfo Arias 11 days after he took office in 1968. He remained in 
power until he died in a 1981 airplane crash. 
</P>
<P>
	Moscoso is Arias' widow.  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	LIMA, Peru (AP) -- Police on Thursday seized 2.2 tons of cocaine  
paste worth $90 million buried in plastic drums on a farm on Peru's 
southern coast. 
</P>
<P>
	The drug was to be refined into cocaine at a laboratory on the  
farm near the village of Grocio Prado, 130 miles southeast of Lima, 
Interior Minister Gen. Jose Villanueva said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cocaine paste is a semi-processed form of cocaine.  
</P>
<P>
	Police have arrested 13 Peruvians from a gang called ``The  
Camels.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Police found 2.3 tons of cocaine hidden among frozen fish two  
weeks ago in Lima's port city of Callao. It was being smuggled by 
the same group, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Peru is one of the world's largest producers of cocaine paste.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
