<DOCNO> APW19990415.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 18:16:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Tax-Mania Sweeps Post Offices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- As much as Americans despise paying taxes,  
Thursday brought music and back rubs to the nation's post offices, 
along with a spirit of camaraderie among last-minute filers jammed 
into lines. 
</P>
<P>
	``I got it done. I've just got to figure out where to send the  
money that I owe,'' said 21-year-old Steve MacIntyre as he rooted 
through a mountain of forms at Boston's main post office. 
</P>
<P>
	His paperwork was creased and grubby from being in the back  
pocket of his jeans. 
</P>
<P>
	``Aargh! No envelopes!'' he shouted, pounding the wall.  
</P>
<P>
	MacIntyre's was just one of 126 million tax returns the Internal  
Revenue Service expected to receive this year. The agency said it 
had already received more than half by late last month. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the procrastinators, the forgetful and the flummoxed who  
took in the festive atmosphere at the nation's mailrooms on the 
final day of filing. Some post offices were open as late as 
midnight, with parties until closing time. 
</P>
<P>
	A piano player was set to play in Boston's main post office  
Thursday. Outside, an actress dressed as Mother Nature was hired by 
a vitamin company to hand out free packets of kava root, which is 
supposed to ease stress. 
</P>
<P>
	A party at the Springfield post office included four bands and  
food donated from eight restaurants. Taxpayers also had a chance to 
get even with IRS agents. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have two dunk tanks this year, not just one,'' boasted  
Postmaster Flossie Paluszec. 
</P>
<P>
	About 3,000 miles away, a Seattle radio station sent an anti-tax  
message by re-enacting the Boston Tea Party on an old sailing ship. 
</P>
<P>
	Other post offices around the country tried to rub out the  
anxiety of tax filing with free back and neck massages. 
</P>
<P>
	In Phoenix, fans going to Thursday night's Los Angeles  
Dodgers-Arizona Diamondbacks game could bring their tax returns out 
to the park where a mobile post office was being set up. 
</P>
<P>
	Aspiring actors and actresses might have wanted to pay their  
taxes in Newport Beach, Calif. The U.S. Department of Agriculture 
was capitalizing on the crowds at the post office by conducting 
screen tests for its ``Got Milk'' campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``They will give you a milk mustache and a screen test,'' said  
postal spokesman David Mazer. 
</P>
<P>
	For those who didn't want to deal with stamps and envelopes,  
electronic filing was increasingly popular. 
</P>
<P>
	IRS spokesman Don Roberts said 17 percent more people paid their  
taxes either online or by telephone this year than last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the postal service hadn't noticed its business declining.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's the same number that we see every year,'' said Bob  
Cannon, a Massachusetts postal service spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	In Springfield, Va., the certified public accountants of  
Crutchley, Marginot &AMP; Tosi P.C. closed the office early. Like 
accountants around the country, they planned to celebrate an end to 
80-hour work weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``We shut down at noon, we start our party at 2 p.m. and it goes  
through the night,'' said accountant Mary Ann Dougherty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990415.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 10:55:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Patriots Seek Better Draft Fortunes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FOXBORO, Mass. (AP) -- The names of possible Patriots draft picks  
swirl around: Damien Woody, Edgerrin James, maybe even Ricky 
Williams. 
</P>
<P>
	What New England really needs, though, isn't on any team's draft  
board. Where do you find final vindication or guaranteed health? 
</P>
<P>
	The team gets its last chance Saturday to make a big score out  
of the six compensatory picks it received for losing coach Bill 
Parcells and free-agent running back Curtis Martin to the New York 
Jets. 
</P>
<P>
	Pressure? Not for Bobby Grier, the team's vice president of  
player personnel. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't feel any pressure at all,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	As compensation for letting Parcells become coach of the Jets,  
the Patriots received picks in the third and fourth rounds in 1997, 
second round in 1998 and first round this season. So far, the picks 
yielded running back Sedrick Shaw, who has played sparingly, and 
two spot starters -- tackle Damon Denson and wide receiver Tony 
Simmons. 
</P>
<P>
	When Martin departed before last season, the Patriots received  
two picks -- a first-rounder (running back Robert Edwards) and 
third-rounder (defensive end Greg Spires, who plays in pass rushing 
situations). 
</P>
<P>
	Edwards had a solid season as the NFL's second-leading rookie  
rusher with 1,115 yards. But he had a shattering offseason, 
suffering a career-threatening knee injury in a beach football game 
that is just the latest in a series of physical blows to the heart 
of the Patriots. 
</P>
<P>
	They started last season with a 4-1 record but, as the injuries  
mounted, they went 5-6 in their last nine games and got into the 
playoffs as a wild card, losing in the first round at Jacksonville. 
</P>
<P>
	Last season, they had seven players on injured reserve,  
including wide receiver Terry Glenn and linebacker Ted Johnson. 
Quarterback Drew Bledsoe missed the last three games, including the 
playoffs, with a broken finger. 
</P>
<P>
	With Edwards gone at least for next season, the Patriots were  
trying to trade with Washington for the fifth pick in the draft to 
take another running back in the first round -- Williams of Texas 
or, more likely, James of Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	``Luck has quite a bit to play with it,'' Grier said. ``We never  
thought we'd be in this situation, looking for a running back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Patriots have Williams and James rated close together and  
there's a dropoff to the next best running back. That's one reason 
the team was willing to package several picks this year, and 
perhaps even one next year, to have a chance to draft one of them. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're really two unique, outstanding players that you don't  
get a chance to get that often,'' coach Pete Carroll said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have the ability to pull (the trade) off if it's not just  
ridiculous'' in terms of what Washington wants, Grier said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Patriots have 11 picks in the seven rounds of the two-day  
draft, including their own first-rounder, the 20th overall, and the 
Jets' choice, the 28th. If they keep them, they could choose Boston 
College center Woody because last year's center, Dave Wohlabaugh, 
left for Cleveland as a free agent. 
</P>
<P>
	``Regardless of how it goes, we'll have good picks in the first  
round,'' Carroll said. 
</P>
<P>
	Their first-round picks haven't been all that good in Carroll's  
two drafts with the team. In 1997, they took cornerback Chris 
Canty, who was pulled from the starting lineup after the ninth game 
last year. And last year they chose Edwards and Tebucky Jones, who 
struggled with the transition from safety to cornerback, but has 
potential. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think we'll get two good players if we remain where we  
are,'' Grier said. ``This is an unusual draft, because the 
quarterbacks are going to really make an impact.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The first three choices could be quarterbacks: Kentucky's Tim  
Couch, Oregon's Akili Smith and Syracuse's Donovan McNabb. 
</P>
<P>
	That's one position New England doesn't need. Bledsoe was the  
first pick of the entire 1993 draft, starting a string of four 
years of successful opening-round choices. The Patriots took 
defensive end Willie McGinest in 1994, cornerback Ty Law in 1995 
and Glenn in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Glenn, however, has been plagued by injuries and ended last  
season with a fractured ankle. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got good players. We think we've got a good team,''  
Grier said. ``We've got to get our guys healthy and get them on the 
field.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990415.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 18:16:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
