<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Promises More Kosovo Info </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- President Clinton told newspaper editors on  
Thursday the military should ``get more information out more 
quickly,'' answering a media complaint about a scarcity of details 
on the Kosovo campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said the Pentagon had difficulty working through the  
NATO command structure in Europe, and he added that early 
assessments of the bombing had been obscured by bad weather. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm aware that this is a difficulty, I agree that we should  
try to do more, more simultaneous with the actions, and I am 
working on it and trying to get NATO to do more as well,'' Clinton 
told the American Society of Newspaper Editors. 
</P>
<P>
	``Unless there is some specific security-related reason that  
some issue shouldn't be talked about, I think the more information 
we can get out there the more quickly, the better off we are.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He told the editors he hoped the situation improved within a few  
days. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, several news organizations, including The  
Associated Press, delivered a letter to Defense Secretary William 
Cohen expressing concern that few details of the air campaign 
against the Serbs had been released, especially compared with 
voluminous detail released about earlier bombings of Iraq. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe that detailed information about the allied  
operation is vital to an informed public discussion of this matter 
of national interest,'' the editors wrote to Cohen. They asked for 
information about targets hit, planes involved in operations, 
greater access to troops and officers and daily summaries of bomb 
damage. 
</P>
<P>
	``The lack of specific data day to day makes it impossible to  
analyze the effectiveness of the air campaign, something that has 
to be known to the Yugoslav authorities but is concealed from the 
American public,'' the letter said. 
</P>
<P>
	News executives said they were pleased with Clinton's comments  
and would be looking for results. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're encouraged to hear the president talk abut greater  
public access to the military campaign in Europe,'' said Jonathan 
P. Wolman, managing editor of the AP. ``Information has been more 
tightly held than in the past and we've been glad to see a small 
improvement even in the last few days.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leonard Downie, executive editor of The Washington Post, who  
asked the question that brought Clinton's response Thursday, said, 
``What pleased me was that he had already begun to discuss this. 
... I hope that's going to bear fruit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Parks, editor and executive vice president of the Los  
Angeles Times, said, ``We've seen some improvement. We're going to 
continue to press.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And Edward Seaton, ASNE president and editor in chief of The  
Manhattan (Kan.) Mercury said, ``We're delighted with his promise 
and hope he lives up to it.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
