<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Impeachment Coverage Criticized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- President Clinton's impeachment trial  
damaged not only his credibility but the media's as well, according 
to a panel addressing a convention of the nation's newspaper 
editors. 
</P>
<P>
	Impeachment proceedings ``weakened the basic institutions of  
government across the board,'' from the presidency and Congress to 
the press and the public, former White House Chief of Staff Leon 
Panetta said Wednesday at the American Society of Newspaper Editors 
convention. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's domestic credibility and leadership were damaged,  
added David Broder, a Pulitzer Prize-winning political 
correspondent for The Washington Post. But he said the scandal hurt 
the media's credibility, deepened cynicism about politics and 
government and ``added to the public perception that Washington is 
a snake pit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not everyone agreed.  
</P>
<P>
	Sherry Bebitch Jeffe, an instructor at the School of Politics  
and Economics at Claremont Graduate University and a contributing 
editor for the Los Angeles Times, said most of the nation already 
distrusted politicians. 
</P>
<P>
	There was ``not much hand-wringing over this,'' she said.  
``People couldn't be any more cynical about Washington than they 
were.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Exhaustive coverage of the Clinton sex scandal brought  
controversial issues to the forefront at most newsrooms. Having it 
happen at a time when Web sites compete to get the latest 
information out quickly also brought its own set of challenges, 
panelists said. 
</P>
<P>
	Newspapers relied heavily on anonymous sources, according to a  
survey designed by the Committee of Concerned Journalists and 
conducted by Princeton Survey Research Associates last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the front-page impeachment-related stories appearing in The  
New York Times, Los Angeles Times, St. Louis Post-Dispatch, The 
Washington Post and The Washington Times between January 21-24, 38 
percent relied on anonymous sources. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were trying to do our job, but we didn't always do as well  
as we wanted,'' said Thomas Rosenstiel, director of the Project for 
Excellence in Journalism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
