<HEADLINE> Driver in Van Crash Pleads Guilty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BELOIT, Wis. (AP) -- The 20-year-old driver in a van crash that  
killed seven members of a magazine sales crew pleaded guilty to 
vehicular homicide on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeremy Holmes changed his mind to spare himself and the victims'  
families from the trauma of a trial, said his attorney Brenna 
Lisowski. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's been very anxious not to drag this out and put other  
people through the agony of this any further,'' Lisowski said. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators said Holmes, of Clinton, Iowa, tried to switch  
places with a passenger because he had been spotted speeding and 
was driving without a valid license. 
</P>
<P>
	The van was carrying 14 young magazine sellers on March 25 when  
it veered off the freeway at 80 mph and barrel-rolled off 
Interstate 90 near Janesville. Twelve people were thrown from the 
vehicle. 
</P>
<P>
	The group had been selling magazine subscriptions door to door  
and was on its way back to a hotel. 
</P>
<P>
	In exchange for Holmes' guilty pleas to seven counts of  
vehicular homicide and five counts of causing great bodily harm, 
the district attorney said he would ask the judge to decide the 
prison sentence for vehicular homicide without any recommendation 
from the prosecution. 
</P>
<P>
	The maximum prison sentence for vehicular homicide is 14 years.  
</P>
<P>
	The van's occupants, ages 15 to 25, had been selling magazines  
for YES, an affiliate of Subscriptions Plus of suburban Oklahoma 
City. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the crash, the Oklahoma Labor Department issued eight  
citations against Subscriptions Plus alleging 123 Worker's 
Compensation Act violations. 
</P>
<P>
	Subscriptions Plus also was accused of a child labor citation  
involving a 15-year-old Madison, Wis., girl injured in the crash. 
The company has denied the allegations and did not return telephone 
messages seeking comment Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
