<HEADLINE> Rhode Island Names DeGregorio Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SOUTH KINGSTOWN, R.I. (AP) -- Rhode Island promoted assistant  
Jerry DeGregorio to basketball coach on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	DeGregorio takes over for Jim Harrick, who left March 31 to take  
over as coach of Georgia. It is DeGregorio's first head coaching 
position. 
</P>
<P>
	Dave Cowens, a former Boston Celtics star, said earlier Thursday  
on WSKO-AM radio that he had withdrawn his name from consideration. 
Cowens, who quit earlier this season as coach of the NBA's 
Charlotte Hornets, said he would seek another NBA coaching 
position. 
</P>
<P>
	DeGregorio, 37, has been an assistant at Rhode Island since 1997  
and was the chief recruiter. He won widespread support in his bid 
for the head coaching position from players and boosters. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a dream come true,'' DeGregorio said. ``I appreciate  
the faith the university has shown me in giving me this 
opportunity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thursday's press conference at Mackal Field House was the second  
in two weeks that Rhode Island scheduled to announce a hiring. On 
April 1, the school planned to announce that Harrick had changed 
his mind and would remain at Rhode Island. But he backed out. 
</P>
<P>
	Rhode Island moved quickly with its selection of a replacement  
for Harrick with national signing day approaching. Only DeGregorio, 
Cowens and Loyola of Chicago coach Larry Farmer were interviewed. 
</P>
<P>
	Before coming to Rhode Island, DeGregorio was athletic director  
and basketball coach at St. Thomas Aquinas High School in New 
Britain, Conn., his hometown. 
</P>
<P>
	DeGregorio was an assistant at Hofstra from 1985-88, an  
assistant at St. Thomas Aquinas College for one season and coach at 
Mattatuck Community College from 1990-1992. 
</P>
<P>
	``Jerry DeGregorio is well known and well liked by our boosters  
and our players,'' athletic director Ron Petro said. DeGregorio, 
``a proven recruiter and motivator ... impressed our search 
committee with his commitment, loyalty and emphasis on academic 
achievement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Harrick took Rhode Island into the NCAA tournament the last two  
years and DeGregorio acknowledged he would have to match high 
standards. 
</P>
<P>
	``I learned a lot from you, coach Harrick. I love you,''  
DeGregorio said during the press conference. 
</P>
<P>
	DeGregorio also will act as a fundraiser while the school tries  
to raise $15 million in contributions for a new arena. 
</P>
<P>
	The team also faces an uncertain future, with star forward Lamar  
Odom considering entering the NBA draft. DeGregorio has been Odom's 
mentor for years and plans to speak with Odom and his family this 
weekend. The school hopes for a decision next week. 
</P>
<P>
	Odom was a member of the search committee and supported  
DeGregorio. But Petro said DeGregorio was not chosen in an attempt 
to persuade Odom to stay at Rhode Island. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
