<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Non-Division I Programs Recognized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SOUTH BEND, Ind. (AP) -- Florida A&AMP;M halfback Willie Galimore and  
North Dakota linebacker Jim LeClair were among eight players and 
coaches from non-Division I programs named to the College Football 
Hall of Fame on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Galimore led the Rattlers to four conference championships from  
1953-56 and was an NAIA All-American in 1954. He later was drafted 
by the Chicago Bears and played in the NFL from 1957-63, when his 
career was cut short by a fatal car accident. 
</P>
<P>
	LeClair was an All-American at North Dakota in 1971 and later  
played for the Cincinnati Bengals and the USFL's New Jersey 
Generals. 
</P>
<P>
	Other players elected to the hall were George Bork, quarterback,  
Northern Illinois, 1960-63; Teel Bruner, defensive back, Centre 
(Ky.), 1982-85; George Floyd, defensive back, Eastern Kentucky, 
1978-81; and Randy Trautman, defensive tackle, Boise State, 
1961-64. 
</P>
<P>
	Billy Nicks and James Sochor were elected as coaches. Nicks  
coached Morris Brown from 1930-42 and Prairie View A&AMP;M from 1945-47 
and 1952-65. He had a 189-55-9 record. Sochor was 158-42-5 from 
1970-89 at California Davis. 
</P>
<P>
	The players and coaches will be inducted into the hall during a  
December ceremony in New York and have their plaques unveiled 
during a ceremony next August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
