<HEADLINE> Intel's Stock Drops Despite Profits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Intel Corp. shares fell 6 percent Wednesday  
after the leading chip maker announced first-quarter revenues that 
fell slightly short of expectations and warned that future sales 
could drop. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors focused on the sales figures instead of Intel's  
better-than-expected profit, which rose 57 percent in the quarter 
amid cost-cutting. The financial results, announced late Tuesday, 
had reassured some analysts that problems in the personal computer 
business may be mostly confined to its biggest chip customer, 
Compaq Computer Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	But Intel, whose chips supply the brainpower for 90 percent of  
the world's personal computers, expects second-quarter revenue to 
stay the same or fall slightly from its first-quarter revenue of 
$7.1 billion, citing ``seasonal factors'' in the microprocessor 
business. Some analysts had expected a slight increase. 
</P>
<P>
	Intel's stock price dropped $3.50 to $57 on the Nasdaq Stock  
Market. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
