<HEADLINE> Nixon's Daughter Will Testify </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Nixon's younger daughter will be  
allowed to testify in a court battle over whether the government 
should compensate her father's estate millions of dollars for 
presidential papers and tapes it seized when he resigned in 1974. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge John Garrett Penn on Thursday rejected a  
Justice Department motion to exclude the testimony of Julie Nixon 
Eisenhower, who is 50 and lives near Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	The government also fought the Nixon estate's plan to have its  
lead attorney, R. Stan Mortenson, testify about the government's 
chief appraiser, but the judge has not decided whether to allow 
Mortenson take the stand. 
</P>
<P>
	At a court hearing on Wednesday, Justice Department attorney  
Neil Koslowe accused the estate of trying to call the two new 
witnesses to present new information in the rebuttal stage of the 
case. He said this would delay the trial and force the government 
to take new depositions and possibly recall witnesses. 
</P>
<P>
	The government did not comment on the judge's ruling.  
</P>
<P>
	During the trial, which has lasted 69 days, government witnesses  
have testified that the former president had no intention of 
selling any of his presidential materials. The government contends 
that if anything must be paid to compensate the Nixon estate, a 
fair market value for the materials would be no more than $2.2 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	Appraisers for the Nixon estate place the value at $30 million  
or more -- and with interest, compensation could total $210 million. 
</P>
<P>
	After the hearing Wednesday, Mortenson said Mrs. Eisenhower was  
expected to testify that her father planned to put his papers in a 
traditional presidential library. If he had known the government 
was not going to establish one, his plans would have changed and 
some items might have been sold to ensure proper funding for a 
private repository, Mortenson said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
