<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Arkansas Derby Winner Investigated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK (AP) -- Oaklawn Park asked state racing authorities  
Thursday to investigate whether jockey Billy Patin used an 
electrical device to make his horse run faster when it won the 
Arkansas Derby. 
</P>
<P>
	Valhol had not won in two outings before last Saturday's  
$500,000 Arkansas Derby and was a 30-1 shot when the horses left 
the gate. He paid $62.80 to win. 
</P>
<P>
	Oaklawn president Charles J. Cella told a hastily called meeting  
of the state Racing Commission that he wanted the commission to 
investigate. He said an employee found a device on the track. 
</P>
<P>
	He asked the commission to order the track to suspend  
distribution of the purse to the owner and rider and have race 
stewards investigate. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission voted unanimously to go along with both requests.  
When the motion to suspend the purse came up for a vote, Cella 
intervened to make certain the purse suspension applied to the 
jockey. 
</P>
<P>
	Cella also said that, if the commission decides the rules of  
racing were violated, ``those involved should be dealt with in the 
appropriate and severe manner.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Valhol owner James D. Jackson of Rockdale, Texas, said he was  
``absolutely distraught'' about the situation. He told The 
Sentinel-Record in Hot Springs that legal action would be ``very 
shortly under way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He denied use of an electrical device by the trainer or jockey.  
He also said the first he heard about the investigation was from 
the media. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson, at a Grand Prairie, Texas, motel for the races at Lone  
Star Park, called the investigation a ``witch hunt.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Patin was scheduled to ride Dixie Gem in Thursday night's second  
race at Lone Star Park in Grand Prairie, Texas, but he was not 
available and was replaced on the horse. 
</P>
<P>
	Valhol won the Arkansas Derby by 4 1/2 lengths.  
</P>
<P>
	The first-place check for the race was to be $300,000.  
Withholding those earnings would put Valhol's status in question 
for the May 1 Kentucky Derby. If there are more than 20 3-year-olds 
entered at Louisville, preference goes to the top 20 in graded 
money earned. The Arkansas Derby is a Grade II race and the 
first-place check would easily qualify Valhol for a spot in the 
race. 
</P>
<P>
	Cella said Oaklawn officials first became aware of possible  
irregularities in the running of the Arkansas Derby shortly after 
the race was declared official. 
</P>
<P>
	``We immediately informed the stewards and the local  
Thoroughbred Racing Protective Bureau -- the investigative branch of 
the thoroughbred racing industry,'' Cella said. ``By Monday night 
and Tuesday, Oaklawn management uncovered additional evidence 
regarding the race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That evidence also was turned over to the national office of the  
TRPB in Maryland. 
</P>
<P>
	``All parties have concurred that the evidence is substantial  
enough to warrant further investigation,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander said an Oaklawn employee found an electronic device on  
the racetrack sometime after the Arkansas Derby. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have not seen it and I think, at this time, it's best for us  
to not comment,'' Alexander said. ``All the evidence will come out 
at a later time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pressed about the evidence, Alexander said the commission had  
been aware of Oaklawn's investigation for some time. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had to have hard cold facts to start an investigation,'' he  
said. ``If we did not feel there was an infraction, we would not be 
having this meeting today.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
