<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Scoured for Next Ronaldo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- A budding teen-age soccer star is  
spotted by Dutch scouts and whisked away to Europe. But he balks at 
a multimillion-dollar transfer to the Ukraine and flees back to 
Brazil. 
</P>
<P>
	It's the storyline of a popular Brazilian TV soap opera, but the  
premise is real. Europe's top soccer clubs are racing to sign 
promising young Brazilians, in hopes they will become tomorrow's 
superstars. 
</P>
<P>
	Some clubs have contracts with local scouts and coaches,  
granting them priority for a potential diamond in the rough. 
</P>
<P>
	Feyenoord of the Netherlands thinks it found one in Alan Vicente  
do Rego. In January, it signed the 13-year-old after he was 
recommended by the director of a neighborhood soccer school linked 
to the Dutch club. 
</P>
<P>
	``Alan now has a Brazilian `nanny,' who is a club employee,  
looking after him in Holland,'' says the director, Jose Joao. ``He 
phones me to tell me about the goals he scores.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil, the only country to win four World Cups, is the world's  
biggest exporter of soccer players. In 1998, some 530 players left 
to play abroad, up from 152 players in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Barely a decade ago, only established stars were signed by  
European clubs, usually for huge transfer fees. But today, many 
youngsters head overseas in their early teens. 
</P>
<P>
	Ronaldo, twice voted FIFA player of the year, was only 16 when  
Cruzeiro acquired him in 1993 from second-division side Sao 
Cristovao for just $10,000. A season later, he was sold to the 
Dutch club PSV Eindhoven for $6 million. When he transferred to 
Internazionale of Milan, his value had tripled. 
</P>
<P>
	Inter is looking for more Ronaldos at the source. The club has  
just concluded a deal with the modest Madureira club of Rio, 
allowing the Italians to keep tabs on youngsters 11 to 13 from four 
soccer schools run by Madureira. 
</P>
<P>
	``Inter pays us $70,000 a year for the soccer school's coaches  
and uniforms and they come to look at players,'' says Madureira 
president Elias Duba. ``If they sign one when he reaches 16 or 17, 
we get 50 percent of his eventual resale price.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Duba says Internazionale is currently jostling with Italian  
first-division rivals AC Milan, Juventus and Udinese to sign 
Madureira's stars Leo and Souza, both members of Brazil's under-17 
national team. 
</P>
<P>
	The blossoming of young talent far from Brazil sometimes takes  
fans here by surprise. 
</P>
<P>
	Many Brazilians had never heard of Elber, star forward of  
Germany's Bayern Munich, until he was named to the national team 
last year. Now 27, Elber left to play abroad as a little-known 
teen-ager. 
</P>
<P>
	It's a bitter pill to swallow. Rio sports daily Lance! is  
campaigning to stem the ``talent outflow brightening Sundays in 
other countries.'' If local clubs were better run and more 
profitable, the paper said, players wouldn't have to go abroad. 
</P>
<P>
	And while Internazionale and Feyenoord have open and aboveboard  
links with local soccer schools, other clubs have more obscure 
dealings. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many European clubs have representatives in Brazil who look  
for young players of 13 and 14, but they are pirates and don't care 
about boys they contract,'' says Leo Rabello, president of Brazil's 
Association of Soccer Agents, recognized by FIFA. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some clubs are happy if just one of 20 boys they sign makes it  
(as a professional),'' Rabello says. ``But the others lose 
confidence and jeopardize their careers or end up playing in remote 
places like Tunisia.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the risk, Joao, the soccer school director, says  
youngsters from poor families should seize the chance to move to a 
wealthy foreign club. 
</P>
<P>
	``One ex-pupil of mine who is 16 and at Feyenoord is now the  
breadwinner in his family,'' says Joao. ``He has moved his family 
out of a shantytown and into Rio's smartest neighborhood and got 
his brother a job as his chauffeur,'' 
</P>
<P>
	If he had joined a Brazilian club, he says, the teenager might  
still be destitute. 
</P>
<P>
	``When young players start to train with a club in Brazil, they  
have to pay their bus fare to get there,'' Joao says. ``They don't 
get help with simple things like permission to miss school classes. 
Many tell me they have given up because it's not worth the 
effort.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
