<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Drug-maker Pfizer Stock Plummets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Pfizer Inc.'s stock skidded 10 percent Thursday  
after the drug company reported a drop in sales of Viagra and 
warned that profit growth would slow in the second quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Pfizer, which released its first-quarter results Thursday, said  
it will fall far short of the 35 percent profit growth it enjoyed 
last spring due to the explosive initial sales of the 
anti-impotence pill Viagra. Pfizer also hinted that overall 1999 
earnings would be slightly below expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	In the just-ended quarater, Pfizer earned $815 million, or 62  
cents per share, up 27 percent from $692 million, or 53 cents a 
share, in the same quarter a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Pfizer revenues jumped 29 percent to $3.93 billion from $3.04  
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Earnings met analysts' expectations, according to surveys by  
First Call. Yet, many traders had quietly hoped the company would 
beat Wall Street's already rosy forecasts. Pfizer stock fell $14.63 
to $130 on Thursday in New York Stock Exchange trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said Pfizer could have posted higher profits, but  
instead chose to spend more on research and building its sales 
staff. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a very smart strategy for the long haul, but does not  
help the short term,'' said Steven Gerber, an analyst with CIBC 
Oppenheimer. 
</P>
<P>
	Pfizer, the world's fourth-largest drug company, has been a  
pharmaceutical dynamo the past three years. It owns or sells the 
three fastest growing new drugs in pharmaceutical history: Viagra; 
the cholesterol drug Lipitor, which it markets with Warner-Lambert; 
and the arthritis pill Celebrex, which it markets with Monsanto. 
</P>
<P>
	The three drugs combined are expected to generate more than $4  
billion in 1999 sales. 
</P>
<P>
	With such high expectations, analysts said Pfizer's stock was  
vulnerable to a big selloff, especially during a week when 
investors are moving from growth stocks to cyclical stocks, those 
that tend to rise and fall with the economy, and to smaller company 
stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	Pfizer said profit growth would be in the single digits in the  
second quarter, far below the 20 percent to 30 percent Wall Street 
has come to expect. 
</P>
<P>
	Pfizer posted $193 million in worldwide Viagra sales during the  
first quarter, down 18 percent from $236 million in the fourth 
quarter. In the second quarter of 1998, Viagra had $411 million in 
sales. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Viagra sales rose slightly to $149 million in the first  
quarter of 1999, up from $131 million in the prior three months. 
</P>
<P>
	Viagra sales should improve markedly in the second quarter with  
the drug's launch in Japan and Canada, Pfizer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Weak Viagra sales in the United States were attributed to the  
leveling off of the curiosity factor related to the drug and to 
limits insurers have placed on coverage for it, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the demand for the first-ever impotence pill are  
startling. More than 9 million prescriptions have been written for 
4 million patients since its launch in April 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``Despite the Viagra problems, as far as overall sales and  
earnings growth, Pfizer is still a rising company,'' said Hemant 
Shah, analyst with HKS &AMP; Co. in Warren, N.J. 
</P>
<P>
	Pfizer's biggest-selling drug, Norvasc, a hypertension  
medication, posted a 24 percent increase in first quarter sales to 
$703 million. Sales of the antibiotic Zithromax rose 44 percent to 
$441 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues that Pfizer gets from marketing other companies' drugs,  
such as Lipitor and Celebrex, rose 168 percent to $403 million. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
