<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gooden Hurt, Shocked by Strawberry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Dwight Gooden, perhaps better than anyone,  
understands the demons of addiction that may have gotten to his 
good friend, Darryl Strawberry, again. 
</P>
<P>
	So when Gooden learned Strawberry had been arrested on charges  
of possession of cocaine and soliciting a prostitute, his pain was 
masked by the special bond he shares with his former teammate. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was shocked,'' Gooden said. ``I was hurt. I don't have all  
the results of what happened but I can feel for what he's going 
through right now. I've been there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gooden was informed of Strawberry's situation at 2 a.m. Thursday  
morning when he received a call from Ron Dock, the drug aftercare 
sponsor he shares with Strawberry. Dock had been in Tampa, Fla., 
with Strawberry, who was attempting to come back from colon cancer 
surgery this season with the New York Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't get very much sleep last night after that,'' Gooden  
said Thursday before the Cleveland Indians game with the Kansas 
City Royals was postponed by rain. ``I was just tossing and 
turning. You try and stay away from asking yourself, why? You just 
try and wonder what happened. What led to that? I really don't have 
any answers but I feel for him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gooden and Strawberry once owned New York as teammates in the  
1980s with the Mets, and later their friendship would grow stronger 
as each resurrected turbulent careers when they were reunited with 
the Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	Gooden, who said he speaks to Strawberry regularly, said he was  
unable to reach his friend Thursday afternoon to offer him support. 
He desperately wanted to talk with Strawberry to remind him he was 
there to help. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was always there for me, and I'll always be there for  
him,'' Gooden said. 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry was first there for Gooden in 1984 when the pitcher  
arrived at spring training with the Mets as a shy, introverted 
rookie. Strawberry took Gooden under his wing and taught him how to 
walk and talk like a ballplayer. 
</P>
<P>
	In his recent autobiography ``Heat'', Gooden recalled Strawberry  
telling him, ``Look at you. You got your head down all the time 
like you're embarrassed to be here. You can't even look anyone in 
the eye. I've seen you. I know how good you are. You just don't 
know it yet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The two became fast friends and were part of the group of Mets  
who loved to play hard and live fast. It wasn't enough to beat the 
Astros on a Tuesday night, those Mets went out all night partying 
before coming to the ballpark and doing it all over again the next 
day. 
</P>
<P>
	Gooden and Strawberry stayed tight for years, and Gooden  
recalled that after he was suspended for the entire 1995 season for 
drug abuse, it was Strawberry who picked him up when he was 
discharged from the Betty Ford Clinic. 
</P>
<P>
	Gooden considered Strawberry a brother then and now.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's still the same,'' Gooden said.  
</P>
<P>
	Gooden said he didn't know all the details of Strawberry's  
arrest and wanted to learn more before rushing to any kind of 
judgment. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very tough,'' he said. ``I feel it.''  
</P>
<P>
	While in Boston for the division series against the Red Sox last  
October, Gooden learned Strawberry had been diagnosed with colon 
cancer and would need surgery. The feeling of helplessness 
overwhelmed him, and he nearly broke down in tears while talking on 
the phone to Strawberry. 
</P>
<P>
	Thursday's news was equally devastating but for a different  
reason, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Last year in Boston I felt real bad and I felt helpless  
because I don't have any knowledge with that (cancer) so there was 
nothing I could really do but let him know I was there for him,'' 
Gooden said. ``This situation here I can relate so there's more 
pain. Because I've been there.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
