<DOCNO> APW19990415.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 14:57:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Duke's Avery To Enter NBA Draft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DURHAM (AP) -- Duke guard Will Avery, against the wishes of coach  
Mike Krzyzewski, will join teammate Elton Brand in deciding to 
enter the NBA draft. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not in favor of William's decision at this time,''  
Krzyzewski said in a statement released by the school Thursday. 
``We have done extensive research into the NBA for William and my 
conclusion was that entering the draft now would not be in his best 
interests.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``However, everyone is entitled to make their own decisions. I  
certainly wish him the ultimate success in his future endeavors.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Avery told Krzyzewski of his decision late Wednesday night,  
hours after Brand's news conference announcing his decision to turn 
pro. 
</P>
<P>
	Avery has an unlisted campus telephone number, and could not be  
reached for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Krzyzewski indicated during Brand's news conference that he  
expected Avery to stay at Duke. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-2 point guard, a native of Augusta, Ga., averaged 8.5  
points and 2.5 assists as a freshman backup. He improved to 14.9 
points and 5 per game as a sophomore starter. 
</P>
<P>
	He was a second-team All-Atlantic Coast Conference choice and an  
honorable mention Associated Press All-American. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990415.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 00:12:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gingrich Resumes Political Career </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Speaking in the nation's capital for the first  
time since his stunning resignation as House speaker, Newt Gingrich 
urged an end to the independent counsel law and cautioned the 
Republican presidential candidates to avoid attacks on each other. 
</P>
<P>
	Free from the responsibilities of leading a fractious House  
Republican majority, Gingrich reveled in his new freedom to once 
again offer ideas and suggestions, reverting to the visionary that 
helped the GOP in 1994 end 40 years of Democratic control of the 
House. 
</P>
<P>
	The occasion was Wednesday's ``Salute to Newt,'' a fund-raiser  
for Gingrich's new political action committee, the Friends of Newt 
Gingrich PAC. More than $500,000 was expected to be raised, with 
some of the proceeds going to the Juvenile Diabetes Foundation. 
</P>
<P>
	On the same day Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr told members  
of Congress that the law should expire, Gingrich offered a similar 
conclusion. 
</P>
<P>
	``Kill it,'' he said. ``Get rid of it. It has been a  
monstrosity. It criminalized and undermines the process of American 
government.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mentioned as a potential future presidential candidate, Gingrich  
is sitting out the 2000 race, but urged the GOP hopefuls to adopt 
Ronald Reagan's 11th commandment of not criticizing a fellow 
Republican. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let's have a great presidential nominating process with no  
negative ads,'' he said. ``Let the person with the best ideas win 
the nomination. If we don't do that, we're going to have a 
bloodbath.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gingrich abruptly announced his resignation after the  
Republicans lost five seats in the November elections. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he planned to remain active politically, and the  
assembled crowd testified to the clout that the former speaker 
still wields. The entire House Republican leadership was there, led 
by Gingrich's successor as speaker, Dennis Hastert of Illinois, as 
well many of Washington's top lobbyists, including former House 
Minority Leader Bob Michel of Illinois and former Republican 
National Chairman Haley Barbour. 
</P>
<P>
	Gingrich was greeted with three standing ovations, and the  
speeches took place against a backdrop of two huge black-and-white 
photos of the former speaker. Guests also received a calendar with 
a different color photo of Gingrich for every month. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's going to be around and be an influence in our party for  
years to come,'' said Sen. Connie Mack, R-Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	One way Gingrich will remain a political player is through his  
new PAC, which will support Republicans who share the former 
speaker's desires to cap federal, state and local taxes at 25 
percent of a person's income, use some Social Security funds for 
private investment accounts and build a national missile defense. 
</P>
<P>
	Gingrich also is setting up a consulting firm but is banned from  
lobbying his former colleagues until January. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
