<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Harlem Globetrotters May Visit Cuba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HAVANA (AP) -- The Harlem Globetrotters began talks Thursday  
aimed at returning the touring basketball performers to Cuba for 
the first time in nearly 50 years. 
</P>
<P>
	``When we started this three years ago it was pretty tough, but  
after the baseball exchange it has gotten a lot easier,'' team 
owner Mannie Jackson said Thursday. He felt the Baltimore Orioles 
had opened the way with their visit for an exhibition game last 
month. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are really hoping to play here.'' said Jackson. ``We have  
always been ambassadors of goodwill, so this would be great.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson said that Cuban sports officials seemed very warm about  
his proposal to have the team visit later this year, play the 
national team in Havana and play exhibition games in three or four 
other cities outside the capital. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan is to have the Globetrotters stay for a full week and  
also hold basketball clinics for Cuban youth. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson had meetings scheduled with Cuban sports officials  
before returning to the United States on Saturday, but said one 
more trip could be necessary before agreement is reached. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he hopes that a Cuban national team will be able to play  
the Globetrotters at Madison Square Garden in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we keep it out of the political forum and keep it in the  
human forum I think that we'll be OK.,'' said Jackson. 
</P>
<P>
	Among issues still to be worked out is how to handle any  
proceeds from the games, such as television rights. 
</P>
<P>
	The Globetrotters recently completed another U.S. tour and later  
this spring will embark on a swing overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	The team has played in 115 countries since being formed by Abe  
Saperstein in the 1940s. Jackson has owned the team since 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990415.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 15:25:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Refugee Wave Hits Macedonia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BLACE, Macedonia (AP) -- Telling authorities that thousands more  
are behind them, refugees poured across Kosovo's border with 
Macedonia on Thursday, driven out by what some called an 
intensifying Serb purge of ethnic Albanian communities. 
</P>
<P>
	Others in Macedonia's two-day influx of more than 5,500 refugees  
said they left because they heard the border was open and feared 
remaining in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Serbs were shelling Kosovo's southern mountains, where the  
refugees had fled, Kosovo Albanians said. A Serb-controlled TV crew 
in Kosovo reported smoke rising from the mountains on Thursday, and 
villages around the southern city of Urosevac that appeared empty 
of people. 
</P>
<P>
	New arrivals said they had to pay bribes to be allowed to leave  
Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``They took 200 German marks from us. We had to bribe them, or  
they wouldn't let us out,'' said Mimoza Aliu, 18. Others told 
similar stories, including 19-year-old Arbenita Asllani, who said 
Serb forces burned her home in the village of Sojevo, near 
Urosevac. 
</P>
<P>
	Aliaze Kajtaina, said she drove in from Pristina with her son on  
her own after Serb forces burned her house and killed her husband. 
</P>
<P>
	Alarmed by the new influx, Macedonia asked foreign countries to  
accept more of the refugees, saying the world wasn't doing enough 
in the crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	``All the burden can't fall on two economically weak states in  
the Balkans,'' President Kiro Gligorov said, asking for more aid 
and guarantees of his country's territorial integrity. 
</P>
<P>
	Macedonia took in more than 120,000 refugees over the past three  
weeks; Albania, more than 300,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Kosovo's conflict has sent more than a half-million refugees  
spilling across in borders in that time, many saying Serbs had 
forced them out. 
</P>
<P>
	After briefly stopping the expulsion for what it said was an  
Orthodox Easter truce, Serbia appears to be sending out steadily 
more refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are expecting more people, and it seems the number is  
increasing exponentially,'' said Paula Ghedini, spokeswoman for the 
U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	Serbs were sending trains packed with refugees to a point near  
the border, then telling them to follow railroad tracks for the 
roughly one-hour walk to the border no-man's land between Kosovo 
and Macedonia, at Blace. 
</P>
<P>
	About 1,000 people had been waiting for a day at a crossing west  
of Blace, hoping to enter Macedonia. Another 3,000-5,000 were said 
to be behind them, still in Kosovo, Ghedini said, and another 1,000 
were expected at an unofficial crossing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990415.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 02:24:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Finished Lower / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Aggressive selling of technology issues pushed  
Tokyo stock prices slightly lower today. The dollar dropped 
marginally against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell 37.60 points,  
or 0.22 percent, to close the day at 16,727.08. On Wednesday, the 
average closed up 49.52 points, or 0.87 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 118.80 yen in the late afternoon, down 0.39  
yen from late Wednesday in Tokyo but above its late New York level 
of 118.68 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	Players said the weakness in technology stocks was partly  
prompted by a 76.22 point fall in the technology-rich Nasdaq 
Composite on Wednesday to 2,507.28 -- its fourth largest point 
decline of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Technology stocks were also sold because of the recent  
strengthening of the yen, traders said. A weaker dollar reduces the 
value of export earnings when translated into yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Yoshihiko Kuroichi, manager of the research department at  
Kankaku Securities, said that technology stocks were ripe for 
profit-taking after recent gains. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the decliners was NEC, 33 cents lower at $10.60. Sharp  
fell 13 cents to $11.08, and Matsushita Electric Industrial fell 13 
cents to $19.50. 
</P>
<P>
	The Tokyo market lost steam after a strong morning, when bank  
shares rose and Sony Corp. issues soared after an announcement 
Wednesday that it will jointly develop and market digital editing 
systems for TV broadcasting with International Business Machines. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
exchange's first section was down 5.42 points, or 0.40 percent, to 
1,337.93. The TOPIX closed up 11.61 points, or 0.87 percent, the 
day before. 
</P>
<P>
	An estimated 634 million shares changed hands on the First  
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange, down from 719.5 million on 
Wednesday. Decliners beat out advancers 632 to 567 while 121 issues 
were unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar gained early on a wave of  
buying from Japanese trust banks. But selling pressure mounted 
after the Nihon Keizai business newspaper reported Wednesday that 
Japanese life insurers would reduce their investment in U.S. 
Treasury bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar traded between 118.63 yen and 119.26 yen on  
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 128.27 yen, down  
from 128.74 yen late Wednesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 211 10-year Japanese government  
bond fell to 1.585 percent from its close of 1.645 percent on 
Wednesday, driving its price up to 101.88 yen from 101.35 yen. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
