<DOCNO> APW19990415.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 18:54:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NFL Teams Want (Need) Quarterbacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Mike Ditka wants Ricky Williams so badly, he's  
willing to give up the New Orleans' Saints entire draft, maybe for 
two years, to get the Heisman Trophy winner. 
</P>
<P>
	Everyone else wants quarterbacks so badly that they're likely to  
go 1-2-3, with five and maybe six going into the first round. 
</P>
<P>
	Yes, it's the NFL draft, when coaches and general managers MUST  
have a player they can't quite seem to get. In fact, this could be 
the year when team officials don't spout the, ``We were amazed he 
was still there when we picked,'' cliche. 
</P>
<P>
	``This will be my 27th draft, and the one thing I've always  
found is there is one less player than the pick you have,'' says 
Ernie Accorsi, general manager of the New York Giants, who, in 
fact, are likely to miss out on the premier offensive lineman they 
want. 
</P>
<P>
	``So we just list enough players to make sure we'll have one we  
like when we pick.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The players people like this year are the quarterbacks: Tim  
Couch of Kentucky, Akili Smith of Oregon, Donovan McNabb of 
Syracuse, Daunte Culpepper of Central Florida and Cade McNown of 
UCLA. Couch, McNabb and Smith are likely to go 1-2-3 in some order 
to expansion Cleveland, Philadelphia and Cincinnati. 
</P>
<P>
	That seems to make this the best draft for quarterbacks since  
1983, which produced John Elway, Dan Marino and Jim Kelly in the 
first round (as well as Tony Eason, Ken O'Brien and Todd 
Blackledge). 
</P>
<P>
	But it's those last three -- and the likes of Kelly Stouffer,  
Todd Marinovich, Dan McGwire, Dave Brown, Andre Ware, David 
Klingler, Kerry Collins and a dozen more first-round 
disappointments -- that make teams wary of risking a top pick on a 
quarterback. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you go by the averages, you would hope one or two of them  
would be successful for their particular team,'' says general 
manager Rich McKay of Tampa Bay, which might take a stab at 
Culpepper or McNown if they fall as far as 15, where the Bucs pick. 
</P>
<P>
	Adds the Colts' Jim Mora, who made the right move in taking  
Peyton Manning over Ryan Leaf last year: 
</P>
<P>
	``You're not going to look five years from now and say, `Boy,  
all these guys are great.' Down the road it might be just two of 
them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That leaves players who might go in the top three to teams  
picking lower. That group is led by Williams, the Heisman 
Trophy-winning running back, who set an NCAA rushing record at 
Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	The Colts, selecting fourth, traded their star running back,  
Marshall Faulk, to St. Louis on Thursday, opening the way for them 
to grab Williams. They're lucky, they got their QB last year in 
Peyton Manning. 
</P>
<P>
	Other teams may get lucky, too, because others take  
quarterbacks. 
</P>
<P>
	``There may be four, potentially five quarterbacks that go  
before we pick, and that's good for us,'' says Tom Donahoe, 
personnel director of the Steelers, who pick 13th and are sticking 
with Kordell Stewart. 
</P>
<P>
	The players who will drop a bit include Champ Bailey, a  
cornerback from Georgia who, like Deion Sanders, also plays wide 
receiver; linebackers Chris Claiborne of Southern Cal and Jevon 
Kearse of Florida; wide receiver Torry Holt of North Carolina 
State; cornerback Chris McAlister of Arizona; running back Edgerrin 
James of Miami; and offensive tackle John Tait of Brigham Young. 
</P>
<P>
	That also could lead to a lot of scrambling.  
</P>
<P>
	Minnesota, which got the 11th pick by trading quarterback Brad  
Johnson to Washington, badly wants McAlister. The Vikings might 
have to trade up to get him. 
</P>
<P>
	Chicago would like McNabb, but probably won't get him and might  
be able to trade down a bit and still take Claiborne or Kearse. 
</P>
<P>
	New England desperately needs a running back to replace Robert  
Edwards, badly injured in a beach flag football game at the Pro 
Bowl. It has the 20th and 28th picks overall, probably not enough 
to get up for James. So the Pats could go down a bit and get a back 
like LSU's Kevin Faulk or Mississippi State's James Johnson. 
</P>
<P>
	Cleveland, back in the league as an expansion team to replace  
the franchise moved to Baltimore after the 1995 season, gets the 
first pick. Publicly, the Browns say they're considering Couch, 
Smith and Williams, but privately, most people expect them to 
choose a quarterback. 
</P>
<P>
	Then comes Philadelphia, which seems to be leaning toward  
McNabb. Cincinnati, No. 3, has four quarterbacks on the roster, but 
seems set to pick a fifth, even though Bailey would be a perfect 
fit. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you have a good quarterback, a team can ride on him for  
years,'' says team president Mike Brown, who used a the sixth 
overall pick on Klingler in 1992. ``If you look at the standings, 
almost always the teams with productive quarterbacks win; those 
whose quarterbacks are not productive don't win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Next comes Indianapolis, which seems set to take Williams now  
that they've traded Faulk. 
</P>
<P>
	They also could bite at Ditka's offer to trade away all his  
draft picks this year and next year's No. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Next comes Washington, which could end up with Bailey; St.  
Louis, which might be leaning toward Holt now that it has Faulk; 
and Chicago, which could go for Claiborne or Kearse. 
</P>
<P>
	At No. 8 is Arizona (which also has the 21st pick), followed by  
Detroit; Baltimore; Minnesota (which has 11 and 29); New Orleans; 
Pittsburgh; Kansas City; Tampa Bay; Tennessee; Seattle; Oakland; 
the New York Giants; New England (20 and 28); Dallas; Buffalo; 
Miami; Green Bay; Jacksonville; San Francisco; Atlanta; and Denver. 
</P>
<P>
	The Jets (as compensation for coach Bill Parcells), Carolina  
(for Sean Gilbert) and San Diego (as part of the deal to move up 
for Ryan Leaf,) have no No. 1s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990415.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 15:35:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dench Shines in 'Amy's View' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- In ``Shakespeare in Love,'' Judi Dench won an  
Academy Award for eight minutes of screen work. One wonders what 
Hollywood would give her for two-hours-plus on stage in ``Amy's 
View,'' the actress' London triumph that seems destined to repeat 
its West End success on Broadway. 
</P>
<P>
	Dench turns in a dazzling performance, a powerful, emotionally  
affecting portrait that doesn't overpower the play and makes its 
talky, more sober-sided moments richer and deeper. 
</P>
<P>
	``Amy's View,'' which opened Thursday at the Ethel Barrymore  
Theater, is an old-fashioned, sturdily constructed vehicle, built 
specifically around Dench's considerable talents. The play by David 
Hare, an author already represented in New York this season by 
``The Blue Room'' and the current ``Via Dolorosa,'' gives her ample 
opportunity to emote. 
</P>
<P>
	And, boy, does she! Dench rants and raves, coos and cries, all  
the while furiously smoking cigarettes as she paces designer Bob 
Crowley's English country manor setting. 
</P>
<P>
	In any other actress, these histrionics would seem excessive.  
With Dench, they don't. She favors the direct approach, 
straightforward and honest, delivering her lines in a husky, 
honey-coated voice that makes every syllable count. 
</P>
<P>
	Physically, the woman is unprepossessing. Yet Dench, sporting  
close-cropped hair and wearing matronly dresses, possesses a shy, 
crinkly smile which immediately disarms. You can't take your eyes 
off her -- which is exactly what Hare wants. 
</P>
<P>
	Set over a 16-year period from 1979 into the mid-1990s, ``Amy's  
View'' chronicles the ups and downs -- mostly the downs -- of a 
theatrical legend named Esme Allen. Esme is a stage actress of the 
old school -- grand, a bit snobby and strong-willed. She also can be 
quite funny, even when her professional and personal worlds are 
collapsing. 
</P>
<P>
	Her private life focuses on daughter Amy, a child she seems  
determined to control or at least guide through life. These plans 
are wrecked with the arrival of Dominic, Amy's boyfriend and 
incipient husband. 
</P>
<P>
	Dominic is an up-and-comer. He starts as the editor of an  
obscure film magazine, eventually working his way up the arts-media 
chain to high-powered director of action movies. Disdainful of the 
theater, he is the ultimate networker. What's more, he succeeds in 
public, even as his marriage disintegrates. 
</P>
<P>
	Esme's life falls apart, too. Financially, she is wiped out by  
bad investments made by an old friend, beautifully played with 
embarrassed charm by Ronald Pickup. His betrayal of Esme is 
matter-of-factly revealed -- and accepted by Esme -- in a scene that 
contains some of Hare's most poignant writing. 
</P>
<P>
	But then, director Richard Eyre has made sure that Hare's play  
doesn't turn into a one-woman show. In the pivotal role of Amy, a 
forceful Samantha Bond matches Dench tempest for tempest. The two 
women even resemble each other physically, although philosophically 
they are very different. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's Amy's view that everyone should try to get on,'' says  
unfaithful husband, Dominic. His wife's willingness to compromise, 
to find the good in people, dooms her to disappointment. In the 
evening's most dramatic moment, Amy admits that her mother may have 
been right about her ambitious helpmate. 
</P>
<P>
	Tate Donovan's Dominic delivers the dramatic goods, too,  
although he occasionally loses his British accent when things get 
heated. It's a difficult role -- part charmer, part cad, a man who 
goes after what he wants. Donovan walks the fine line with ease. 
</P>
<P>
	Anne Pitoniak as Esme's ancient mother-in-law makes a strong  
impression as a character who hasn't much reason to be around 
except to suggest the passage of time. Yet Pitoniak manages to 
create a real person. 
</P>
<P>
	In the end, Amy believes in the redemptive power of love and  
loving unconditionally. Love conquers all, or so she would like to 
believe. 
</P>
<P>
	Hare, on the other hand, believes in the redemptive power of  
theater. Consider the play's final moments, a spectacular bit of 
stagecraft designed by Bob Crowley, that won't be revealed here. 
</P>
<P>
	By then Esme is alone, bereft of fortune and daughter. But what  
she still has is a new play, another chance to create magic for a 
new audience. And with Judi Dench stirring the elixir, it makes for 
a terrific ending for what is a heady theatrical brew. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
