<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Franklin Exhibit Focuses on Science </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In revolutionary America, a small corps of  
earnest experimenters and observers of nature came to see 
themselves as citizens not just of a new nation but of a far more 
universal ``republic of science.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the center was Benjamin Franklin, equally at ease in the  
roles of printer, writer, postmaster, philosopher, rebel, diplomat 
and statesman. But his scientific experiments with electricity made 
him an international legend. 
</P>
<P>
	``Franklin and His Friends, Portraying the Man of Science in  
18th Century America,'' opening Friday at the National Portrait 
Gallery, stitches together the many threads of the human network 
that comprised Franklin's scientific world. 
</P>
<P>
	The exhibit, the product of more than four years of research,  
runs through Sept. 6. 
</P>
<P>
	Wherever possible, the show's curators match portraits of the  
fledgling American scientists with the brass telescopes, 
microscopes, electrostatic generators and other instruments they 
actually used. 
</P>
<P>
	In one of several portraits, Franklin is shown in 1762, seated  
in his study next to two metal bells attached by wires to an 
outside lightning rod. The bells rang, alerting their inventor, 
when a storm electrified the iron rod. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearby is a bent and rusty but highly prized iron rod, dating  
from about 1756. It was attached to a Philadelphia house according 
to Franklin's instructions. 
</P>
<P>
	Franklin's network included John Winthrop, a mathematician and  
astronomer famed for charting the course of Venus across the sun. 
Winthrop is painted with a treasured telescope. The actual 
London-made instrument is nearby. 
</P>
<P>
	An engraved Thomas Jefferson displays the Declaration of  
Independence. But he is ready to turn immediately to a machine that 
generates electricity when a crank-turned glass plate is rubbed 
against a leather pad. 
</P>
<P>
	The show includes astronomer and instrument maker David  
Rittenhouse, botanist William Bartram, museum pioneer and painter 
Charles Wilson Peale, and physician and chemist Benjamin Rush. 
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps the most flamboyant member of Franklin's group was  
Harvard-educated physician John Jeffries, whom Franklin entertained 
repeatedly in Paris in 1785 after Jeffries made the first crossing 
of the English channel by hot-air balloon. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeffries is portrayed in flight, wearing a striking leopard-skin  
cap and clutching a large barometer. 
</P>
<P>
	The original barometer, in a nearby case, is prized as ``the  
world's oldest surviving flight instrument.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990415.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 12:35:10 </DATE_TIME>
