<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Girl's Conviction in Death Reversed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- An appeals court on Thursday reversed the  
1996 conviction of an 11-year-old girl accused of beating to death 
a toddler, ruling police questioned her illegally. 
</P>
<P>
	The 3rd District Court of Appeals said that the signed  
confession given by Lacresha Murray, now 14, was illegal because 
she was ``isolated and alone'' when she gave it. 
</P>
<P>
	``At a minimum, we cannot say that appellant's statements were  
not the product of fright and despair,'' the court said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lacresha originally was charged with capital murder, making her  
the youngest person in Texas to face such a charge. After two 
trials, she eventually was convicted of injury to a child and 
sentenced to 25 years for the beating death of 2-year-old Jayla 
Belton. 
</P>
<P>
	The case was ordered returned to juvenile court. Lacresha will  
remain at a Texas Youth Commission facility unless prosecutors drop 
the charges. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am going to assume that they're going to retry her a third  
time,'' said her attorney, Keith Hampton. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors had no immediate comment.  
</P>
<P>
	Jayla died in May 1996 of massive internal injuries, including a  
ruptured liver. 
</P>
<P>
	During a two-hour interview, she denied killing Jayla at least  
40 times, but still signed a police-written statement saying she 
may have dropped and kicked the toddler. 
</P>
<P>
	In Texas, a juvenile taken into custody by police must go before  
a magistrate before being questioned. Prosecutors argued Lacresha 
wasn't officially in custody and could have left at any time. 
</P>
<P>
	Justice Lee Yeakel, writing for the appeals court, disagreed.  
</P>
<P>
	``She was not, however, told that she was free to leave the  
interview room or the children's shelter, and she was never told 
she could call her grandparents or any other friendly adult,'' 
Yeakel said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990415.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 15:25:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Verdict May Hurt Malaysian Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) -- A landmark verdict against a  
former deputy prime minister may be galvanizing opposition to 
Malaysia's long-ruling leader rather than stifling it. 
</P>
<P>
	Political science professor Chandra Muzaffar said Thursday the  
six-year jail term given to former Deputy Prime Minister Anwar 
Ibrahim will come back to haunt his former mentor now political 
nemesis, Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad. 
</P>
<P>
	``The political actors in this conspiracy wanted to render Anwar  
totally impotent,'' the professor said. ``But this stiff sentence 
will further erode Mahathir's leadership.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Syed Husin Ali, head of the Malaysian People's Party, echoed  
similar sentiments, saying the political reform movement that Anwar 
represents will only be strengthened by the verdict. 
</P>
<P>
	``His struggle for justice will go on, though, and now we are  
more determined than ever,'' Syed said. 
</P>
<P>
	Several thousand Malaysians took to the streets after Anwar was  
convicted of corruption Wednesday, staging the most violent 
demonstrations this placid Southeast Asian capital has seen in 
years. More than 200 people, mostly students, gathered in downtown 
Kuala Lumpur on Thursday to protest the verdict. Several were 
detained. 
</P>
<P>
	Anwar, 51, was sentenced to six years in prison Wednesday in a  
decision that effectively bans him from politics for a decade, 
since Malaysian law bars him from office for at least five years 
after he is freed. 
</P>
<P>
	He had repeatedly declared his innocence, saying he was the  
victim of a political conspiracy to eliminate his challenge to 
Mahathir's 18-year rule. 
</P>
<P>
	In an editorial in Thursday's edition of The New York Times,  
Anwar said he was seen as a threat because he refused to carry out 
Mahathir's ``business as usual.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I became dangerous ... I had widespread support for my work  
toward democracy and civil society. So I was accused of sex crimes, 
treason and corruption and expelled from government and party,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	It has fallen to Anwar's wife, Azizah Ismail, to carry out her  
husband's crusade to rid Malaysia of corruption and Mahathir. 
</P>
<P>
	She has become a political beacon in her own right and drew some  
8,000 supporters to a late-night meeting shortly after saying 
good-bye to her husband. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now I am more determined than ever,'' she said, ``to carry out  
my husband's struggle for justice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Augustine Paul, who found Anwar guilty on all four  
corruption charges, had served as judge and jury during the 
sensational 7-month trial. He said of his ruling, ``In this 
judgment, I am answerable to God.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But some believe Paul answered only to Mahathir, who publicly  
condemned Anwar for corruption, sodomy and adultery even before any 
charges against Anwar were filed. 
</P>
<P>
	In Washington, Vice President Al Gore said he was ``profoundly  
troubled'' by Anwar's prison term and warned that his conviction 
could affect the Malaysian economy, as countries that allow dissent 
cope better with economic crises. The United States is Malaysia's 
largest trading partner. 
</P>
<P>
	``Increasingly, investors put their money and their faith in  
democracies, and pull it out of nations where decisions are rigged, 
where contracts are not honored, where governments use the power of 
the police to quiet the criticism that could create a more just, 
more prosperous society,'' Gore said. 
</P>
<P>
	The European Union said the sentence raised ``doubts about the  
fairness of the trial.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Malaysia's 73-year-old prime minister, still recovering from a  
10-day hospital stay for a lung infection, has made no public 
comment on the conviction of the man he groomed for a decade to 
take his place until firing Anwar in September. 
</P>
<P>
	But an editorial in the government-backed New Straits Times on  
Thursday declared that Anwar was ``properly and fairly tried'' and 
deserved the severe sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	``As the adage goes, the higher you are, the harder you fall,''  
it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
