<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> HMattel Has Loss, Plans Layoffs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EL SEGUNDO, Calif. (AP) -- Mattel Inc. will lay off 3,000 workers  
and close a number of its plants as part of a restructuring that 
comes as the world's largest toymaker struggles to revive sales and 
profits. 
</P>
<P>
	Mattel, which is best known Barbie and Hot Wheels, reported  
today a net loss of $17.9 million, or 7 cents per share, for the 
quarter ending March 31, compared to a net profit of $12.7 million 
for the same period last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales for the quarter were $692 million, down 2 percent from  
$705 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The layoffs and closings are the latest attempt by Mattel chief  
executive Jill Barad to return the ailing toymaker to health. 
</P>
<P>
	The company announced a management shakeup in March, which  
included the departure of president Bruce Stein. In addition, 
Mattel has been aggressively pursuing opportunities outside 
traditional toys, like CD-ROMs and high-tech gadgets. 
</P>
<P>
	Mattel's purchase of software-giant The Learning Company is  
expected to close next month. Today, the company announced today 
that it would spend $50 million to launch an Internet venture, 
which a portion of which may eventually be offered to the public. 
</P>
<P>
	Mattel already sells some of its toys on its own Web sites, and  
plans to launch a Mattel.com site later this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The company expects the cutbacks to result in cost savings of  
$50 million this year and $400 over the following three years. 
Details about the job cuts or facility closings weren't disclosed. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite core brand strength like Barbie -- sales were up 3  
percent worldwide and U.S. shipping was up 11 percent -- Mattel has 
been forced to rethink its business strategy. 
</P>
<P>
	Important retail customers like Toys R Us drastically cut back  
Mattel orders and asked for delivery of inventory closer to the 
time that they wanted to put the toys on store shelves. 
</P>
<P>
	Barad said the company's core Fisher-Price business returned to  
health with a 9 percent worldwide increase. But its Power Wheels 
line was down, still hurt by the 1998 recall of up to 10 million of 
the battery-run ride-on toys because they posed a serious fire 
risk. 
</P>
<P>
	Character brands were also down. A year ago, Tickle Me Elmo  
contributed approximately $60 million to first quarter earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	Mattel's earnings topped Wall Street analysts' expectations. Its  
stock was up $1.25 to $27.18 3/4 in midday trading on the New York 
Stock Exchange. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
