<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rams Get Faulk From Colts for Picks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Until Thursday morning, running back was the  
St. Louis Rams' top draft-day priority. 
</P>
<P>
	Minutes before the team's scheduled pre-draft news conference,  
everything changed when the Indianapolis Colts agreed to trade 
three-time Pro Bowl running back Marshall Faulk. 
</P>
<P>
	Faulk, perhaps the best all-purpose back in the league, rushed  
for 1,319 yards, caught 86 passes and scored 10 touchdowns last 
year. He was expendable because he wanted to renegotiate his 
contract, and cost the Rams only two draft picks, a second- and 
fifth-round choice. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I'm worth more,'' Faulk said. ``But if you can get  
anything cheaper or for less the price, you do it. That's the 
American way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Faulk, 26, was the No. 2 overall pick of the 1994 draft by the  
Colts, and he had four 1,000-yard rushing seasons in his five years 
there. He had a bit of a parting shot for Colts general manager 
Bill Polian. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think there's a lot of players on the Colts that have  
a relationship with him,'' Faulk said. ``He's a business guy and he 
makes business decisions. Everyone harps on loyalty and before you 
know it, you're out of there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Colts are expected to take Ricky Williams, the Heisman  
Trophy winner, with the fourth selection, or trade up to make 
certain they get him. Many draft observers expect quarterbacks Tim 
Couch, Donovan McNabb and Akili Smith to be the first three picks. 
</P>
<P>
	``Knowing Bill Polian and Jim Mora, they have a pretty good feel  
for what's going to go on before then,'' Vermeil said. ``There's 
only a few people ahead of them, and I think they've probably got a 
good pulse on it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Colts owner Jim Irsay issued a statement that read, in part,  
``Marshall was a very productive player for the Colts, as evidenced 
by his three Pro Bowl nominations. 
</P>
<P>
	``At this point, the Colts have decided to take a different  
direction as preparations continue for the 1999 season. We wish 
Marshall continued success in his career.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This deal appears to be as lopsided for the Rams as their fire  
sale of running back Jerome Bettis to the Steelers was for the 
other side on draft day in 1996. The Steelers gave up second- and 
fourth-round picks and got a third-rounder in return for a back who 
ran for 1,431 yards his first year in Pittsburgh. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Faulk deal, St. Louis had for bait two second-round  
picks, including one acquired from New Orleans in an offseason deal 
for disappointing wide receiver Eddie Kennison. They gave up their 
own pick, the 36th overall, instead of the Kennison pick, which is 
No. 41. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the deal, the Rams appeared to be zeroing in on Miami  
running back Edgerrin James with the sixth pick of the draft. The 
running game was the weakest link on a 4-12 team with the top 
rusher, June Henley, getting only 313 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	Vermeil has said Greg Hill, who had 240 yards and averaged 6.0  
yards per carry in two early starts before seriously injuring his 
ankle, would be the starter next season. But the Rams are worried 
about his durability. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's hard for a lot of people to come back from injuries, but  
I'm not one of those people you have to worry about,'' Hill said. 
``My ankle is fine. I don't even remember which one it was.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Rams haven't had much success lately drafting running backs.  
Robert Holcombe, a second-rounder last year, was a disappointment 
with a 2.3-yard average and only 230 yards. Then there was the 
failed Lawrence Phillips experiment in 1996, with that year's No. 6 
pick now out of the NFL. 
</P>
<P>
	Faulk is the latest upgrade on offense, joining free-agent  
pickups Trent Green at quarterback and Adam Timmerman at guard. Now 
the team is leaning toward defensive help in the first round, with 
Arizona cornerback Chris McAlister at the top of the list. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's nothing like a shutdown corner,'' Vermeil said.  
</P>
<P>
	Faulk has two years to go on the original seven-year contract he  
signed with the Colts. He wants to renegotiate a deal that will pay 
him $2.2 million in base salary this year, and Vermeil said the 
Rams wouldn't be opposed to that. 
</P>
<P>
	``All the teams were made well-aware that it was going to take a  
new contract with Marshall,'' said Rocky Arceneaux, Faulk's agent. 
``I don't think they would have done it without intending on 
redoing the deal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Faulk had his best year in 1998. He led all NFL running backs in  
receptions and yards, and his 2,227 total yards from scrimmage was 
the sixth-highest total in NFL history. He was second to Terrell 
Davis in yards rushing, third in receptions. 
</P>
<P>
	Other teams -- Baltimore, the New York Giants and Oakland --  
reportedly were interested in acquiring Faulk. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
