<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Probe of Cops' Traffic Stops Sought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Angered by complaints that drivers are being  
stopped because of their skin color, lawmakers on Wednesday renewed 
the push for a Justice Department study of police practices. 
</P>
<P>
	A national police officers' organization countered that such a  
study would burden law enforcers and lengthen traffic stops. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. John Conyers, D-Mich., the lead House sponsor of a bill  
introduced Wednesday, said the available data indicate a problem 
exists. 
</P>
<P>
	``Stopping our citizens to be searched on account of their race  
is an unacceptable activity on the part of law enforcement,'' he 
said at a news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J., the prime Senate sponsor, said  
such practices are a ``national insult to our minority community.'' 
He noted that the Justice Department now is investigating the New 
Jersey State Police for such allegations. 
</P>
<P>
	A similar bill by Conyers passed the House last year but died in  
the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	The Traffic Stops Statistics Act of 1999 would require the  
attorney general to analyze existing data on the issue and then 
collect statistics from select areas. 
</P>
<P>
	The statistics include the driver's race, ethnicity and age;  
whether a search was conducted; a warning or citation issued; 
whether there was an arrest; and length of the stop. 
</P>
<P>
	A report would be due within two years of the bill's enactment.  
</P>
<P>
	Conyers, the House Judiciary Committee's senior Democrat, cited  
a finding by a Florida newspaper, The Orlando Sentinel, that 70 
percent of those pulled over on the state's stretch of Interstate 
95 were black although they represent less than 10 percent of all 
drivers. 
</P>
<P>
	A court-ordered study in Maryland also found that more than 70  
percent of drivers stopped along a stretch of the same highway in 
that state were black, but that they made up only 17.5 percent of 
the drivers, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Scully, executive director of the National Association of  
Police Organizations, which represents 4,000 police unions and 
associations, said officers often do not know beforehand the race 
or ethnic background of the individuals they stop. 
</P>
<P>
	``If passed into law, the bill would place a burden on the  
police and lengthen traffic stops,'' Scully said. He said such 
stops are one of the most vulnerable times for officers and that 
the study ``would make a dangerous situation worse.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Attorney General Janet Reno, who endorsed the previous bill,  
said she wants to deal with the issue. Last week, she called on 
police departments to begin collecting the information needed to 
assess the situation and some have begun doing so. 
</P>
<P>
	Police chiefs from some of the nation's largest cities also  
pledged last week to develop a national policy for traffic stops in 
an effort to alleviate the concerns. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
