<HEADLINE> Yankees' Brosius Likely To Go on DL </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- New York Yankees third baseman Scott Brosius has  
an acutely sprained right ankle and will not accompany the team to 
Detroit this weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Brosius, the MVP of last year's World Series sweep over San  
Diego, likely will go on the disabled list, general manager Brian 
Cashman said before Thursday night's game against Baltimore. 
</P>
<P>
	While X-rays showed there wasn't a break, an MRI Thursday  
confirmed the ankle was sprained -- an injury sustained during 
Tuesday night's game while rounding first base on a popup. 
</P>
<P>
	Yankees interim manager Don Zimmer intends to use rookie Clay  
Bellinger and Luis Sojo at third until Brosius returns. Bellinger 
made his first major league start Wednesday night and was 1-for-5 
with a double in New York's 14-7 win over the Orioles. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bellinger is a great third baseman,'' Zimmer said. ``Sojo is  
good no matter where you put him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With Andy Pettitte due to come off the disabled list and start  
Saturday at Detroit, putting Brosius on the DL would enable New 
York to activate Pettitte without another roster move. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Cashman said he might bring up a player from the minors  
on Friday so that the Yankees don't go into their weekend series a 
player short. 
</P>
<P>
	In other Yankees news, Zimmer said Hideki Irabu will remain in  
the bullpen. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's where he was yesterday when the game started. That's  
where he'll be tonight,'' Zimmer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Irabu, called a ``fat ... toad'' by owner George Steinbrenner  
during spring training, got just one out Wednesday night, allowing 
five runs as Baltimore closed to 8-7. 
</P>
<P>
	Ramiro Mendoza will continue to fill Irabu's spot in the  
rotation, starting Sunday against the Tigers. 
</P>
<P>
	Cashman wouldn't address a report that he discussed trading  
Irabu to Seattle for Jeff Fassero, but made it sounds like rumors 
of a trade are overblown. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have nothing hot going with any club,'' Cashman said. ``Not  
even lukewarm.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
