<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FCC OKs Phone Bill Reorganization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Americans' monthly telephone bills may become  
easier to understand because of action taken Thursday by federal 
regulators. 
</P>
<P>
	Phone companies generally will have to reorganize bills to  
spotlight new charges and service providers, give clear 
descriptions of all charges and explain how to contest them. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan, adopted 4-1 by the Federal Communications Commission,  
could take effect in a few months. 
</P>
<P>
	Local telephone and long-distance companies will have to abide  
by all the provisions, while cellular and other wireless companies 
must comply with just some. Violations could lead to fines or other 
penalties. 
</P>
<P>
	Many big phone companies have begun, or plan to make, changes in  
phone bills to make them easier to understand. Ameritech, 
BellSouth, AT&AMP;T, US West and MCI WorldCom believe their bills meet 
many of the FCC's requirements. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got to restore Americans' confidence in the charges that  
they are paying every month,'' said Bill Kennard, FCC chairman. 
</P>
<P>
	The lone dissenter, Harold Furchtgott-Roth, said he believed the  
agency lacked the authority to take such action. He also wondered 
how the agency would judge whether companies' descriptions are 
clear. 
</P>
<P>
	FCC officials acknowledged that it would be subjective  
determination. Also, they could not offer examples of what might 
constitute a clear description for the line-item charges that have 
been appearing on some bills, under different names, for the past 
two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Those charges, which some consumers have said are confusing,  
come from a variety of sources: a FCC overhaul of phone fees; 
itemized charges for government-ordered subsidies once included in 
rates; and paying the costs of complying with other government 
requirements. 
</P>
<P>
	Companies can recover these costs however they choose. AT&AMP;T, MCI  
WorldCom, Sprint, the nation's Bell companies and others have 
decided to do it through line items. The FCC does not force 
companies to spell out the charges in bills. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the FCC's new rules, descriptions of those line-item  
charges will have to be clear. Eventually, the labels will be 
standardized, with the wording determined later. If wireless 
companies include such line-items, they also would be subject to 
uniform labeling. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a mischievous notion,'' AT&AMP;T said in a statement,  
adding it is concerned the government ``would seek to dictate how a 
company can describe to its own customers those government fees and 
charges.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Larry Strickling, chief of the FCC's Common Carrier Bureau, said  
any company that now describes these line-item charges as 
``federally imposed'' or ``federally mandated'' will have to stop. 
</P>
<P>
	FCC officials said they were not acting to avoid being  
associated with the line-items. 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC also will require local and long-distance companies to  
use clear descriptions about all other charges and provide 
information on when nonpayment could cause phone service to be cut 
off. 
</P>
<P>
	For now, the FCC will not apply this provision to wireless  
companies. The FCC does not specify the language for the 
descriptions but encourages the industry to come up with uniform 
wording. 
</P>
<P>
	Local and long-distance companies also will have to highlight --  
the FCC does not say how -- any new provider or charge not on 
previous bills. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, the bills will have to show when a person's  
long-distance carrier was switched or the person is charged for 
calls to a hotline. Consumer advocates say this should make it 
easier for customers to spot fraudulent charges. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
