<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gov't Moves To Keep Nixon Off Stand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Lawyers for President Nixon's estate want to  
put his daughter on the witness stand to convince a federal judge 
that the government should pay millions of dollars for confiscating 
presidential papers and secret White House tapes when he resigned. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Justice Department moved on Wednesday to stop Julie  
Nixon Eisenhower from testifying in the case. It also argued to 
block the Nixon legal team's attempt to have one of its attorneys, 
R. Stan Mortenson, take the stand. 
</P>
<P>
	Testimony from these two rebuttal witnesses would force delays  
in the final stages of the trial, which is in its 69th day, said 
government attorney Neil Koslowe. The Justice Department would have 
to take new depositions, possibly recall witnesses and collect 
other information needed for cross-examinations, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are seeking to call brand-new witnesses in the guise of  
rebuttal witnesses,'' the Justice Department argued in a motion to 
exclude testimony from the two witnesses. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge John Garrett Penn has not decided whether to  
let the witnesses testify. 
</P>
<P>
	If Mrs. Eisenhower is permitted to take the stand, she is  
expected to testify that her father planned to put his papers in a 
traditional presidential library, so long as the government funded 
it and allowed him to restrict access to certain materials, 
Mortenson said. 
</P>
<P>
	That never happened. In 1974, Congress, fearing that evidence of  
criminal wrongdoing might have been destroyed or tampered with, 
seized the materials, including some 42 million papers, 3,700 hours 
of secretly recorded tapes and thousands of photographs. 
</P>
<P>
	If Nixon had known the government was not going to set up a  
presidential library, his plans would have changed, Mortenson said 
after the hearing. Mrs. Eisenhower might have sold some items to 
ensure proper funding for a private library, Mortenson said. 
</P>
<P>
	The government contends that if anything must be paid to  
compensate the Nixon estate, a fair market value for the materials 
would be no more than $2.2 million. The Nixon estate places the 
value at $30 million or more -- and with interest, compensation 
could total $210 million. 
</P>
<P>
	As a witness, Mortenson would dispute testimony of the  
government's chief appraiser, Charles Sachs, who testified that the 
presidential materials are worth about $1.5 million. That's much 
lower than the $35 million Sachs told the Nixon estate they were 
worth during a meeting in 1992, says Martin Minsker, a colleague of 
Mortenson. 
</P>
<P>
	But the government pointed out that Sachs testified he didn't  
remember the appraisal figure he gave the Nixon estate in 1992. 
``Mr. Mortenson is not in a position to impeach a witness for 
saying 'I don't remember,''' Koslowe said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
