<HEADLINE> Honda Might Expand to North America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Major Japanese automaker Honda Motor Co. plans to  
build a new manufacturing plant in the United States or Canada by 
2001, a newspaper reported Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The plant, which would employ more than 1,000 workers, would  
produce mainly sports-utility vehicles, a report in the Nihon 
Keizai business daily said, citing unnamed company sources. 
</P>
<P>
	Honda spokesman Yuzuru Matsuno denied the report, saying that  
his company had made no decision to build another North American 
plant. 
</P>
<P>
	He added, however, that Honda is planning to boost its  
production capacity in North America. 
</P>
<P>
	Honda currently has two factories in North America-- one in the  
United States and one in Canada. 
</P>
<P>
	If the reported new plant becomes operational, Honda would have  
a production capacity of 1.1 million vehicles in the U.S. and 
Canada -- almost on par with its domestic capacity of between 1.2 
million and 1.3 million vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	The plant's location is still under discussion, with the  
southeastern U.S. as the leading candidate for the site, the paper 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Honda's existing North American plants have a capacity of one  
million vehicles, which the automaker is aiming to increase to 1.01 
million in 2001, Matsuno said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
