<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Newspapers Urge Minorities Coverage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Newspapers must increase diversity among  
their staffs and on their pages if they are to turn a profit, two 
executives told the American Society of Newspaper Editors on 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Times Mirror Co. CEO Mark Willes and San Jose Mercury News  
Publisher Jay T. Harris said improved coverage of minority 
communities has enabled them to expand readership. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a moral commitment to do all we can to encourage  
respect, tolerance and diversity,'' said Willes. 
</P>
<P>
	More Hispanics are reading the Los Angeles Times and more women  
are reading the Hartford Courant because of efforts to attract 
those groups, Willis said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're doing what we're doing because it's right, but also  
because it's essential for us to grow,'' he said. ``Our papers are 
better because those stories are there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Mercury News has launched two papers, one catering to  
Hispanics and the other to Vietnamese living in Silicon Valley, 
because the paper had trouble reaching those groups, Harris said. 
</P>
<P>
	``People of this unfolding community will have some primary form  
of information. The question is whether it will be us or some other 
medium,'' Harris said. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, the Associated Press Managing Editors and the  
American Society of Newspaper Editors announced a project designed 
to make the pages of newspapers mirror the racial and ethnic mix of 
their communities. 
</P>
<P>
	The project, called ``The National Time-Out for Diversity and  
Accuracy,'' asks reporters and editors to meet during the week of 
May 17-21 to discuss ways that race and ethnicity affect choices of 
what is covered and who is assigned to cover it. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
