<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NFL Europe League To Start Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Lawrence Phillips gets another chance at pro  
football when his Barcelona Dragons open the NFL Europe league 
season this weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	``He knows he has to get through a lot in the next few months,  
but so far I have been 100 percent pleased with everything,'' said 
Dragons coach Jack Bicknell, who took Phillips in the 10th round of 
the league draft after he was cut in training camp last summer by 
the Miami Dolphins. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've never sat down and told him this is his last chance. If  
he can't figure that out, he doesn't need to hear it from me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Phillips, the No. 6 overall pick in the 1996 NFL draft, has had  
a turbulent career with various run-ins with the law since his days 
at Nebraska, including 23 days of jail time during his 19 months 
with the St. Louis Rams. 
</P>
<P>
	Bicknell described Phillips as ``everything you want in a  
football player and a teammate. He's in great shape -- 208 pounds 
and zero percent of fat'' with only a niggling hamstring injury 
slowing him. 
</P>
<P>
	Phillips, who feels he has been treated unfairly by the media,  
has declined interviews. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's been a great kid here and you can see he's been burned by  
what's happened,'' Bicknell said. 
</P>
<P>
	Also trying to resurrect his career will be Heisman Trophy  
winner Andre Ware. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think there are a lot of people like me who would like to  
see those guys do well, because it's probably their last chance,'' 
league president Oliver Luck said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ware has a profitable computer business in Houston, which he  
terms his ``B plan.'' Now it's back to work on the ``A plan'': 
making it as an NFL quarterback. 
</P>
<P>
	``It does seem a long way away, but this is where it begins,''  
said Ware, who starts for the Berlin Thunder this weekend in a 
league designed to groom young talent and give guys like Ware and 
Phillips another chance. 
</P>
<P>
	Ware says he's never been in the right place at the right time  
since winning the Heisman at Houston in 1989 and calls his four 
years as a backup with the Detroit Lions a ``continual setback with 
three different offenses in four years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He tried to right himself in the Canadian Football League, ``but  
it was a similar thing with three teams in three years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last season, Ware stepped away from football and worked as an  
active partner in a computer consulting business in Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	``The longer I was away from it (football) last year the more I  
missed it,'' he said. ``The juice started to flow about midseason 
and I knew I wanted to see about getting back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Oakland Raiders signed Ware as a free agent and expect him  
to compete with Rich Gannon, Wade Wilson and Pat Barnes. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm looking forward to starting here this weekend,'' Ware  
said. ``And I like my chances of being No. 1 when the season kicks 
off for the Raiders.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, the Frankfurt Galaxy play the Thunder in an  
all-German clash in Frankfurt, while the Amsterdam Admirals travel 
to Barcelona. On Sunday, the defending champion Scottish Claymores 
are home for the Duesseldorf Rhein Fire. 
</P>
<P>
	The top two teams after the 10-game regular season will meet in  
the World Bowl in Duesseldorf on June 27. 
</P>
<P>
	The major change this season is the closure of the one-time  
``flagship'' franchise, the London/England Monarchs, which has been 
replaced by a third German team -- the Thunder, coached by Wes 
Chandler. 
</P>
<P>
	As a developmental league, NFL Europe has been a rousing  
success, with 139 NFL Europe veterans playing last season in the 
NFL. About 150 players have been allocated this season from the 
NFL, up 97 from last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
