<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Airport Fire Safety Questioned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Firefighting rules for the nation's airports  
are inadequate because they do not require crews to rescue 
passengers and put out fires inside airplanes, the nation's largest 
firefighter union argues in a new report. 
</P>
<P>
	The rules specify only how many trucks should be operating, how  
fast they should respond to an accident and how much water and 
firefighting agent, such as foam, they must carry. 
</P>
<P>
	The International Association of Fire Fighters, writing in  
conjunction with a coalition including the Air Line Pilots 
Association and the Association of Flight Attendants, said the 
practical effect is that airports maintain a minimal staffing 
level, so low that the responding firefighters merely clear a path 
from a burning airplane, but do not fight the fire inside. 
</P>
<P>
	The unions argue that safety would be improved by hiring more  
firefighters and mandating an expanded role for them. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today many airports across the United States are completely  
unprepared to respond in the first few vital minutes after an 
airplane crashes and fires ignite, when lives hang in the 
balance,'' reads the opening sentence of the report, which was 
being released Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Both the Federal Aviation Administration, which writes airport  
safety regulations, and the Airports Council International-North 
America, which represents airports handling 90 percent of domestic 
airplane travel, disputed the report. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are ready to deal with the worst-case scenarios, whether it  
is an aircraft disaster, an airport disaster or a natural 
disaster,'' said airports council spokeswoman Bonnie Wilson. 
</P>
<P>
	FAA officials said they are deploying equipment that pierces an  
aircraft's skin and injects firefighting agents. The agency also 
provides firefighting training at regional centers around the 
country. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a very emotional subject, whenever you're dealing with  
people's lives. But overall, over the long run, based on accidents 
that have occurred and incidents, we have played a good role and 
continue to do so,'' said Bob David, manager of the FAA's airport 
safety and operations division. 
</P>
<P>
	While the most memorable airline accidents involve catastrophic,  
unsurvivable failures such as the explosion of TWA Flight 800 off 
Long Island or the plunge of ValuJet Flight 595 into the Florida 
Everglades, the majority of crashes occur near airports on takeoff 
or landing. 
</P>
<P>
	The coalition examined 60 crash reports written by the National  
Transportation Safety Board between 1970 and 1995. It found that 78 
percent of fatalities occurred after an impact. Nearly 96 percent 
of those were caused by smoke inhalation or burns. 
</P>
<P>
	The FAA addresses airport fire safety with several rules that  
outline the equipment airports must provide, the training they must 
offer and the response times they must meet. 
</P>
<P>
	The unions contend that because the rules do not specify  
staffing levels -- only the amount and type of equipment needed -- 
airports can fulfill the requirements with highly automated trucks 
that have few operators. 
</P>
<P>
	Airport and FAA officials say many airports exceed the equipment  
minimum and also allow for interior firefighting. Those who keep 
smaller crews believe flight attendants and the airplane flight 
crew can help passengers get out of a plane, so firefighters should 
concentrate on delivering them to safety. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
