<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Move Higher / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures prices were higher  
Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices extended Wednesday's strong showing, with reports of poor  
weather in the Plains states and in South America providing 
support. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures benefited from the continued reports of cold  
weather in Argentina and U.S. growing regions, analysts said. 
Forecasts show that cold weather could reach as far south as Texas, 
damaging crops. 
</P>
<P>
	Gains were limited as market participants were concerned that  
there also may be some beneficial moisture that could help the 
crops. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybean prices followed a similar pattern, rising at the open  
and then moderating, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn futures were up on reports that wet weather may delay  
planting. 
</P>
<P>
	In trading Thursday, wheat for May delivery was up 3 3/4 cents to  
$2.62 1/2 a bushel; May corn rose 2 1/4 cents to $2.19 3/4 a bushel; May 
oats rose 3 cents to $1.19 3/4 a bushel; and May soybeans were up 1/4 
cent to $4.89 1/2 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Livestock and pork futures were mostly lower on the Chicago  
Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	June live cattle fell .43 cent to 63.17 cents a pound; May  
feeder cattle fell .50 cent to 71.40 cents a pound; June lean hogs 
fell .32 cent to 53.60 cents a pound; and May pork bellies rose .65 
cent to 52.62 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
