<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mattel Has Loss, Plans Layoffs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Mattel is learning that playtime isn't always  
fun. 
</P>
<P>
	The world's biggest toymaker announced today that it will cut  
3,000 jobs, or 10 percent of its total workforce, and close some 
plants as part of an ongoing reorganization effort to revive its 
slumping sales and profits. 
</P>
<P>
	Wall Street cheered the news of the restructuring, sending  
Mattel's stock up nearly 16 percent to 4 1/8 to 30 1/16 in afternoon 
trading on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Thursday, the El Segundo, Calif.-based Mattel reported a  
smaller-than-expected loss of $17.9 million, or 7 cents per share, 
for the quarter ended March 31, compared to a net profit of $12.7 
million for the same period last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales for the quarter were $692 million, down 2 percent from  
$705 million. Mattel noted the first quarter is traditionally the 
smallest of the year, amounting to about 10 percent of its 
business. 
</P>
<P>
	The layoffs and closings, expected to result in $50 million in  
savings this year and $400 million over the next three years, are 
the latest attempts by Mattel chief executive Jill Barad to return 
the ailing toymaker to health. 
</P>
<P>
	Mattel has been forced to rethink its business after important  
retail customers like Toys R Us drastically cut back their orders 
and asked for delivery of inventory closer to the time they wanted 
to put the toys on store shelves. 
</P>
<P>
	In March, the company announced a management shakeup, which  
included the departure of president Bruce Stein and the 
reconfiguration of the executive committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Details about the layoffs and plant closures, which will be  
worldwide, weren't disclosed. Pink slips will go out next week. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be very unfair to tell you before we notified them,''  
Barad said during a conference call Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Mattel has been aggressively pursuing opportunities outside  
traditional toys, like CD-ROMs and high-tech gadgets. Mattel's 
purchase of software-giant The Learning Co. is expected to close 
next month, and it recently announced a new line of toys developed 
with chipmaker Intel. 
</P>
<P>
	A free CD-ROM will soon be included with every Barbie purchase,  
Barad said, adding she was determined to get girls on computers and 
online. 
</P>
<P>
	Mattel also announced Thursday it would spend $50 million to  
launch an Internet venture. Mattel already sells some of its toys 
on its own Web sites, and plans to launch a Mattel.com site in 
October. 
</P>
<P>
	``Restructuring is the right way to go for Mattel,'' said Tucker  
Anthony analyst Margaret Whitfield, who raised her rating on Mattel 
stock to a ``strong buy.'' ``The industry has changed to a more 
technology-oriented business at the expense of basic toys.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The Internet will be very powerful for the company,''  
Whitfield said, noting it will give Mattel greater independence 
with the ability to ship directly to customers. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the earnings decline in the first quarter were  
attributed to expenses from Mattel's purchase of the Pleasant Co., 
which makes the American Girl line of dolls. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales of Barbie, Mattel's core brand strength, were up 3 percent  
worldwide and U.S. shipping was up 11 percent. The company's 
Fisher-Price business returned to health with a 9 percent worldwide 
increase. 
</P>
<P>
	But its Power Wheels line was down, still hurt by the 1998  
recall of up to 10 million of the battery-run ride-on toys because 
they posed a serious fire risk. 
</P>
<P>
	Character brands were also down. A year ago, Tickle Me Elmo  
contributed approximately $60 million to first quarter earnings. 
Sales were nil the first quarter this year. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
