<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Homes Destroyed by Florida Fires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. (AP) -- A wind-driven fire burned between 20  
and 30 homes and was threatening dozens more in a sparsely 
populated area in southeast Florida as several blazes ravaged other 
parched areas of the state. 
</P>
<P>
	The Port St. Lucie fire was spreading in three directions and  
grew to 1,500 acres by dusk, moving towards an area that has about 
200 homes, according to the St. Lucie County Emergency Operations 
Center. 
</P>
<P>
	``All it took was one fire and with the wind blowing as hard as  
it is blowing and as dry as it is'' said spokesman Donny Elder. 
</P>
<P>
	The blaze forced about two dozen school buses to turn back to  
the schools, and 300 students were temporarily unable to get home, 
police said. Schools were closed for Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Port St. Lucie, with a population of nearly 80,000 and home to  
the New York Mets baseball training camp, is 105 miles southeast of 
Orlando on Florida's Treasure Coast and home to many retirees from 
the Northeast. Early last month, brush fires caused minor damage to 
some homes here. 
</P>
<P>
	The fire was believed to be out Wednesday night but was whipped  
up again by strong winds and gusts. Firefighters drew water from 
canals already depleted by a drought that has left Florida under a 
state of emergency. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are probably going to have a couple thousand acres burned  
all told,'' said Matt Winnell, spokesman for the state Division of 
Forestry. 
</P>
<P>
	Residents were under evacuation orders in Osceola and Polk  
counties in central Florida, and Collier County in the southwest. 
Residents of Polk County were allowed to return home once the fire 
was contained. 
</P>
<P>
	In northern Collier County, up to 60 residents took shelter in a  
county building outside Naples, while firefighters reported 
substantial progress against a huge blaze that had burned about 
1,650 acres by Thursday evening, county emergency management 
officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	A wildfire near Lakeland in central Florida canceled an air show  
and sent some spectators scurrying to safety. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is perfect weather for erratic fire behavior,'' said Lori  
Stone, a forestry spokeswoman. ``The wind is pushing it right 
along.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fire officials have cautioned that conditions are ripe for fires  
similar to the ones that happened last year, when 100,000 residents 
fled their homes as nearly 500,000 acres were scorched. 
</P>
<P>
	Those fires, which started Memorial Day weekend and lasted into  
mid-July, destroyed 350 residences or businesses and caused $400 
million in damage. Over 50,000 acres already have burned this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
