<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McGraw-Hill Profits Rise 21 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The McGraw-Hill Cos. reported a 21 percent  
increase in first-quarter earnings Thursday due largely to a strong 
showing in its Standard &AMP; Poor's credit rating subsidiary. 
</P>
<P>
	The company, which also publishes Business Week and other  
magazines, earned $24.4 million in the first three months of the 
year compared to $20.1 million in the same period a year ago. 
Per-share earnings rose to 12 cents from 10 cents, just exceeding 
Wall Street expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues rose 1.9 percent to $716.5 million from $703.4 million.  
</P>
<P>
	Despite a slight decline in U.S. bond issues, for which Standard  
&AMP; Poor's provides ratings, the credit assessment unit posted solid 
gains amid increased demand for credit ratings in Europe and other 
financial transactions in the U.S. market. 
</P>
<P>
	Standard &AMP; Poor's also benefited from increased trading in  
financial products based on its widely-used S&AMP;P 500 index of major 
U.S. companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Business Week magazine had solid results, reporting higher  
revenues and profits due to an 11 percent increase in advertising 
pages. But the company's other publications covering the 
construction business and trade didn't fare as well, leading to a 
12 percent decline in operating profits at its information and 
media group. 
</P>
<P>
	McGraw-Hill's educational and professional publishing unit  
continued to run a loss due in part to another poor showing at the 
Continuing Education Center, which the company has decided to phase 
out. A seasonally slow quarter and investments in ramping up 
education publishing also weighed down the division's results. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of McGraw-Hill fell $1.25 to $55.50 in trading on the New  
York Stock Exchange. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
