<DOCNO> APW19990415.0297 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 15:35:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GM, Ford Post Higher Earnings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Record U.S. demand for the most profitable  
vehicles -- pickups and sport utilities -- combined with ongoing 
cost-cutting to drive up earnings at General Motors Corp. and Ford 
Motor Co. in the first quarter, even as their losses continued 
overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	Profit reports Thursday from the world's largest automakers  
exceeded analysts' expectations, but shares of GM slumped 3.6 
percent while Ford barely managed to gain ground on Wall Street. 
</P>
<P>
	``Overall, they were excellent results because of the powerful  
market in the United States, with very strong volume for both 
companies,'' said analyst David Healy of Burnham Securities Inc. 
``But every place outside of North America was weak.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No. 1 GM earned $2.1 billion, or $3.04 a share, setting a  
company record for any quarter and exceeding by 31 percent its 
year-ago performance of $1.6 billion, or $2.27 a share. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford had a 20 percent increase in operating earnings at $1.81  
billion, or $1.46 a share, vs. $1.51 billion, or $1.22 a share, a 
year earlier. Ford's results compare continuing operations, 
excluding a one-time gain of $165 million from the sale this year 
of its share in the AutoEuropa joint venture in Portugal and last 
year's $15.9 billion gain from the spinoff of its Associates First 
Capital finance business. 
</P>
<P>
	Light trucks -- a category that includes pickups, SUVs and  
minivans -- continued to boost profits. Through the first quarter, 
truck sales amounted to a record 49 percent of the U.S. market, up 
from 48 percent last year. 
</P>
<P>
	GM finance chief J. Michael Losh credited the strong North  
American market, a big improvement in the mortgage operations of 
the GMAC finance subsidiary, and a turnaround in Europe as the 
major factors in GM's record gain. 
</P>
<P>
	The automaker narrowly surpassed its previous quarterly profit  
record of $2.09 billion set in 1997's second quarter. A big 
contributor was cost-cutting: Losh said GM saved about $1 billion 
worldwide in the first quarter, on track with its goal of reducing 
costs by $4 billion this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford, however, out-earned GM in their biggest market. The  
Dearborn, Mich.-based automaker posted a $1.59 billion profit in 
North America, up 57 percent from a year ago. Ford said its 
high-profit truck sales were up 20 percent in the quarter, while 
car sales were up 10 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	GM earned $1.4 billion from its North American operations, up 67  
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``We know we have more to do to improve our cost-competitiveness  
in North America,'' Losh said. 
</P>
<P>
	GM also was hurt because it couldn't make enough of its  
hot-selling and highly profitable Chevrolet Silverado to 
immediately meet demand for the full-size pickup, which was 
redesigned for 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	Though GM's U.S. vehicle sales were up 6 percent in the quarter,  
its market share declined to 28.8 percent from 30.2 percent in the 
first quarter of 1998 -- an indication of the robust demand for new 
cars and trucks industrywide. GM is pushing to get its share back 
up to over 30 percent for the year. 
</P>
<P>
	``With an additional 14 new product launches in 1999, we expect  
to build momentum in the market,'' president G. Richard Wagoner Jr. 
said. ``We have also announced plans to further increase our 
production capacity for full-size trucks to meet the strong and 
growing demand.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ford enjoyed its 12th straight quarter in which operating  
earnings improved. Analyst John Casesa of Schroder &AMP; Co. said the 
company benefitted from an excellent product mix in North America, 
with a wide array of popular light trucks and increased retail 
sales over less-profitable fleet sales. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they could run the whole company like they run North  
America, you wouldn't be able to stop these guys,'' Casesa said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford's automotive operations earned $1.49 billion, up 20 percent  
from a year ago, with surging sales in North America making up for 
a break-even quarter in Europe and losses in South America, where 
Ford does not expect a profit this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said Ford's losses in South America were particularly  
troubling, widening to $165 million from $45 million a year ago. 
Casesa termed the showing ``disastrous.'' 
</P>
<P>
	GM had a loss of $25 million in Latin America compared with a  
$53 million profit a year earlier. But some analysts had expected 
even wider losses. 
</P>
<P>
	European operations contributed $174 million to GM's bottom  
line, up 76 percent from a year ago. Ford broke even in Europe 
after excluding the one-time gain from the sale of its AutoEuropa 
interests. A year ago, it earned $230 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford completed its purchase of Volvo AB's car business for $6.45  
billion on March 31 and will include Volvo results beginning in the 
second quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	German-American automaker DaimlerChrysler AG plans to report its  
first-quarter earnings April 28. 
</P>
<P>
	In trading Thursday on the New York Stock Exchange, GM dropped  
by $3.18 3/4 to close at $86.56 1/4 a share, while Ford was up 6 1/4 cents 
to $62.81 1/4. 
</P>
<P>
	David Bradley, an analyst with J.P. Morgan Securities Inc., said  
GM's drop appeared to have been partly due to disappointment among 
traders who had speculated in advance of the release of the figures 
that the automaker's results were going to be even stronger. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
