<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Up 2525; Nasdaq Down 20.19 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices were mixed again today with blue  
chips rallying while technology stocks continued their slide. 
</P>
<P>
	At 3 p.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
up 25.25 at 10436.91 after changing directions several times. On 
Wednesday, it had its third straight closing high, rising 16 points 
to 10,411.66. 
</P>
<P>
	Broad-market indexes fell as investors continued to unload  
technology shares. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 9.84 at 
1,318.60, and the Nasdaq composite index was off 20.19 at 2,487.09. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors began the day by continuing Wednesday's strategy of  
selling technology and consumer shares and buying economically 
sensitive issues such as manufacturing and basic materials. As the 
session wore on, they keyed into the fact that bond yields were 
rising on heavy new supply in the bond market and a report that 
manufacturing in the Philadelphia area strengthened considerably 
this month. 
</P>
<P>
	Although that does indicate manufacturers are seeing their  
business improve, it also caused concerns that the growing economy 
could reignite inflation, said Jack Shaughnessy, market strategist 
at Advest Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	The stock market ``has been driven (higher) in the last three  
years by rapidly expanding money supply and falling interest 
rates,'' Shaughnessy noted. Now, ``the market is becoming 
apprehensive that the Federal Reserve could raise interest rates 
because of concerns about inflation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the bond market was paring its losses by late afternoon. The  
yield on the 30-year Treasury bond was 5.52 percent, up only 
slightly from from 5.51 percent late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the shares of industrial companies, which had  
performed well since Tuesday afternoon, were still higher. The Dow 
components were led higher by Boeing, up 5 at 43; DuPont, up 4 1/8 at 
69 3/8; and International Paper, up 3 1/4 at 55 1/2. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumer stocks were still struggling, with Johnson &AMP; Johnson  
down 1 9/16 at 93 1/8. 
</P>
<P>
	The fresh blow to technology stocks today was a warning from  
Storage Technology, a maker of computer storage equipment, that it 
wouldn't meet analysts' first-quarter earnings expectations. 
Storage Tech shares were down 7 3/16 at 18 7/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by nearly 9 to 7 on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume was heavy at 1.05 billion 
shares, up substantially from Wednesday's pace. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
