<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ad Firm Sells Space on Balloons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GAINESVILLE, Ga. (AP) -- After giving directions to his business,  
Don Hall adds confidently: ``You can't miss it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No kidding.  
</P>
<P>
	A 30-foot parrot marks the site of Advertising Innovations, a  
fast-rising business that rents inflatable advertisers, from King 
Kong and Godzilla to cartoon characters such as Popeye, and 
brightly colored balloons. 
</P>
<P>
	In this era of increasingly complex special effects and  
multimillion-dollar advertising campaigns, the concept behind 
Advertising Innovations is simple. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's eye-catching,'' says Tim Hall, company president. ``If  
you see that parrot, you'll take a look. 
</P>
<P>
	``People commuting get used to seeing the same thing every day,  
and then one day you look up and see a giant balloon and you think, 
'I never realized there was a tire store there.' '' 
</P>
<P>
	Tim Hall, 30, was a professional water skier five years ago when  
he decided he needed another occupation for the long term. He had 
worked with a company that used a balloon for advertising, and 
talked with his father about starting a business. 
</P>
<P>
	Don, retired after three decades at AT&AMP;T, was intrigued, and got  
together with Sandy Jones, a longtime business associate, to help 
Tim start the company. 
</P>
<P>
	From a single, used balloon bought for $400, the company has  
swelled to include more than 100 inflatables and a 
remote-controlled blimp often rented for sporting events or 
concerts in places such as the Georgia Dome, where it can be used 
to drop T-shirts or fliers. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides the costs of the inflatables, which sell new for $4,000  
and up, the Halls do suffer some losses from vandalism -- among the 
balloon-killers has been a crossbow-firing vandal -- and theft. 
There also are pranksters, some who climb inside the balloons to 
party, while others have moved inflatables to school campuses. 
</P>
<P>
	While Advertising Innovations, a closely held company, doesn't  
disclose its finances, the Halls profess they're doing very well. 
</P>
<P>
	Bill Weldon, who runs Events Spectacular in Walnut Creek,  
Calif., and is president of the Inflatable Advertisers trade 
association, said the industry is growing at a time when a strong 
U.S. economy means many new businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	``The definition of a grand opening has come to mean having a  
big balloon on your roof,'' Weldon said. 
</P>
<P>
	Businesses small and large find the inflatables an efficient,  
effective way to complement other advertising campaigns, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It takes advantage of the local market -- in most cases, people  
do their shopping within five or 10 miles of their home,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike radio or television advertising, which blankets an  
audience that might never come near a business, balloon advertising 
reaches the most likely customers, Weldon said. 
</P>
<P>
	Carl Black's giant automobile dealership in Kennesaw often  
sports an Advertising Innovations inflatable on weekends, from a 
``lady King Kong'' in a pink bikini to seasonal characters such as 
a snowman or Santa Claus. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Rotruck, a general sales manager, said the dealership uses  
only about 5 percent of its ad budget on the inflatables, which it 
rents for $500 to $750 per weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's head-turning,'' he said. ``People kind of recognize us  
that way; it's not unusual for kids to try to guess what we're 
going to do next.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
