<DOCNO> APW19990415.0314 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 02:24:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Accused JFK Forger Goes on Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The rumors about John F. Kennedy and Marilyn  
Monroe, the mob and J. Edgar Hoover seemed real when a Connecticut 
man first produced letters between his late father and the slain 
president. 
</P>
<P>
	But Lawrence X. Cusack III now sits in a federal courtroom in  
Manhattan, accused of swindling investors out of $7 million by 
forging Kennedy's name on phony letters about scandalous subjects. 
</P>
<P>
	The documents nearly became the basis for a chapter in Seymour  
Hersh's book, ``The Dark Side of Camelot,'' after the Pulitzer 
Prize-winning author saw documents alleging that Kennedy set up a 
trust for Miss Monroe's mother to buy her daughter's silence about 
the alleged affair. 
</P>
<P>
	Hersh deleted the chapter before publication after their  
authenticity was challenged. 
</P>
<P>
	As Cusack's mail fraud trial opened Wednesday, Assistant U.S.  
Attorney Paul A. Engelmayer explained how Cusack, 48, came up with 
the documents after befriending a Stamford, Conn., autograph 
specialist. 
</P>
<P>
	Engelmayer said the collectibles dealer, John Reznikoff, told  
Cusack that documents confirming a presidential affair with Miss 
Monroe would sell for hundreds of thousands of dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	Soon, Cusack told Reznikoff he had found correspondence between  
the president and his late father, a lawyer, confirming Kennedy's 
payment of hush money to Miss Monroe to cover up an extramarital 
affair. 
</P>
<P>
	Other letters described Kennedy's battles to prevent FBI  
director Hoover from blackmailing him and even Kennedy's paralyzing 
addiction to pain killers, Engelmayer said. 
</P>
<P>
	With Reznikoff's help, Cusack sold documents and began making  
millions and enjoying the riches, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Luxury stores, luxury cars, luxury clothes,'' he said. ``It  
was a great life and it was built entirely upon the documents. But, 
as the evidence will show, it was also a life built upon fraud.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Expanding publicity brought with it increased scrutiny, and the  
1997 revelation that Cusack created the documents himself, 
Engelmayer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cusack's father, Lawrence Cusack, had been a lawyer for the  
Roman Catholic Archdiocese of New York and Miss Monroe's estate 
after her death, but only in a routine manner, the prosecutor said. 
</P>
<P>
	``To make himself rich, Cusack exploited his father's accidental  
brush with celebrity,'' Engelmayer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cusack claimed to have found 700 documents relating to the  
Kennedy family, Miss Monroe and Chicago mob boss Sam Giancana in 
his father's files. 
</P>
<P>
	Cusack's lawyer, Robert Katzberg, told the jury that it was  
irrelevant to the mail and wire fraud charges whether the documents 
were fake. He said the case hinged on whether the jury concluded 
that his client knew the documents were fake when he sold them. 
</P>
<P>
	Katzberg said several experts on signatures and Kennedy  
memorabilia had examined the materials and found them to be real. 
</P>
<P>
	``By the end of this case, you will be left with more questions  
about the Kennedy papers than answers,'' Katzberg said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
