<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO Strikes After Convoy Accident  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- A day after its bombs hit a convoy  
of refugees in Kosovo, NATO pressed ahead with its air campaign 
today, hitting military installations, TV transmitters and bridges 
throughout Yugoslavia. NATO expressed regret over the ``tragic 
accident,'' saying its planes had been targeting Serb forces when 
they struck a column of ethnic Albanians fleeing the province. A 
Yugoslavia judge claimed 69 bodies had been identified. Alliance 
jets late today pounded military targets around Montenegro in the 
strongest attack on the smaller Yugoslav republic in two weeks. 
Yugoslav media also reported attacks in Belgrade and Novi Sad, 
Serbia's second largest city. 

</P>
<P>
	US: Yugoslavia Has Chemical Agents  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- U.S. officials said today that Yugoslavia has  
stockpiled chemical agents that are ready for use as weapons. 
President Clinton promised a ``swift and overwhelming'' response to 
any chemical attack. Yugoslavia, however, has made no threats to 
use deadly chemical weapons and Pentagon officials said they have 
no intelligence indicating that Belgrade has any such plans. NATO 
strike planners have specifically avoided ordering raids on three 
known chemical agent storage facilities in Yugoslavia to avoid 
sending a deadly plume into the atmosphere, according to one senior 
Pentagon official. 

</P>
<P>
	American Pilots Union Fined $45M  
</P>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- A federal judge today fined the American Airlines  
pilots union more than $45 million -- nearly all of its net worth -- 
for an illegal sickout that led to the cancellation of more than 
6,700 flights. U.S. District Court Judge Joe Kendall had previously 
held the union in contempt after they refused his back to work 
order. American claimed the 10-day sickout in February cost the 
airline $57 million. 

</P>
<P>
	Impeachment Cost At Least $1.2M  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House paid its top impeachment  
investigators as much as $20,000 a month, part of the $1.2 
million-plus price tag for the five-month congressional proceedings 
that ended with President Clinton's acquittal, expense records 
show. Adjusted to annual salary, both Republican investigator David 
Schippers and Democratic counsel Abbe Lowell were being paid at a 
rate of more than $200,000 per year. In contrast, staff lawyers for 
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr earn between $66,563 and $118,400 
annually. 

</P>
<P>
	3 Die in Mormon Library Shooting  
</P>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- A disheveled man walked into the Mormon  
church's genealogical library during an international convention 
today and methodically began shooting people with a small-caliber 
handgun. The gunman had killed a church security officer and a 
library patron and wounded five others, including a police officer. 
He was shot by police and died later in an ambulance. Police knew 
of no motive. 

</P>
<P>
	Algerians Vote in Chaotic Election  
</P>
<P>
	ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) -- Algerians voted today in a presidential  
race marred by the last-minute withdrawal of all candidates but the 
most controversial one -- the man backed by the country's powerful 
military. Abdelaziz Bouteflika, left alone in the race when his six 
competitors pulled out yesterday to protest alleged fraud, would 
become Algeria's first civilian leader since 1965. 

</P>
<P>
	Evidence of New Solar System Found  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- For the first time, there is clear evidence  
that a solar system other than our own exists. Three huge planets 
are spinning around the star Upsilon Andromedae 44 light years from 
Earth in our Milky Way galaxy, San Francisco State University 
researchers said today. Their presence indicates that many of the 
Milky Way's 200 billion stars are likely to have planetary systems. 

</P>
<P>
	Tax-Mania Sweeps Post Offices  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Today's tax filing deadline brought music, back  
rubs and long lines of procrastinators to the nation's post 
offices. Some post offices were open as late as midnight, with 
parties until closing time. But for those who didn't want to deal 
with stamps and envelopes, electronic filing was increasingly 
popular. IRS spokesman Don Roberts said 17 percent more people paid 
their taxes either online or by telephone this year. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends at New High: 10,462.72  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow industrials gained 51.06 to 10,462.72 to  
close at a fourth-straight record high. On the NYSE, advancers led 
decliners 1,781-1,296. The Nasdaq rose 14.76 to 2,522.04. 

</P>
<P>
	Salmon, Angels Top Athletics 12-1  
</P>
<P>
	OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Tim Salmon homered twice, including a  
grand slam, and drove in a career-high six runs to lead the Anaheim 
Angels to a 12-1 victory over the Oakland Athletics today. Omar 
Olivares (2-0) allowed four hits in seven innings as the Angels 
avoided being swept in the three-game series. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SAMANTHA CRITCHELL  

</P>
