<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO Strikes After Convoy Accident  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO jets pounded military targets  
around Montenegro and struck at military and industrial sites in 
Belgrade and other cities late Thursday and early Friday. The 
attacks came a day after the alliance's bombs mistakenly hit a 
convoy of refugees in Kosovo. Vojislav Seselj, a Serbian deputy 
prime minister, accused NATO of killing civilians on purpose. He 
said NATO knew it could ``accomplish nothing by striking military 
targets'' and was therefore ``taking revenge by bombing 
civilians.'' Meanwhile thousands of ethnic Albanians crossed over 
into Macedonia and Albania, fleeing what they described as a 
methodical Serb push to empty towns and villages in Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	Conflict May Cost Over $1B Monthly  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congressional budget analysts said Thursday  
that the U.S. share of NATO's air campaign against Yugoslavia could 
cost more than $1 billion a month to sustain. The first three weeks 
of the air strikes have already cost the U.S. about $600 million, 
according to a Congressional Budget Office report. The estimates do 
not include humanitarian aid or certain procurement costs, such as 
replacing the F117 ``stealth'' fighter that was lost. That aircraft 
is no longer being manufactured. And sending in ground troops -- an 
option the administration says is not currently considering -- could 
cost another $200 million a month. 

</P>
<P>
	26 Killed in Colombia Mudslide  
</P>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Mudslides killed at least 26 people in  
western Colombia on Thursday, many of them rescuers swept away 
while digging for victims, authorities said. At least a dozen more 
people were missing and feared dead, said Monica Yamhure, the 
federal director for disaster response. After weeks of torrential 
rains, the mudslides plowed under several blocks of the town of 
Argelia, 150 miles west of Bogota. The first slide occurred before 
dawn, the second after rescue workers had arrived. 

</P>
<P>
	4,500 Protest NYC Police Brutality  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- An estimated 4,500 protesters walked across the  
Brooklyn Bridge today in the largest demonstration yet against 
allegations of police abuse targeted at minorities. Marchers 
included former New York City mayor David Dinkins and entertainers 
Harry Belafonte, Ossie Davis and Dick Gregory. Meanwhile in 
Washington, Attorney General Janet Reno called for action to 
restore the trust of minority neighborhoods. 

</P>
<P>
	GOP Renews Tax Relief Promises  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- For Republicans in Congress, Thursday's income  
tax deadline brought a chance to renew their promises for tax 
relief. In what has become an annual April 15 exercise, the GOP-led 
House failed to approve a constitutional amendment that would 
require that most tax increases gain a two-thirds vote in Congress. 
Still, the three hours of floor debate, along with an anti-tax 
rally, enabled Republicans to remind voters that tax relief tops 
their agenda. 

</P>
<P>
	American Pilots Union Fined $45M  
</P>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- A federal judge fined the American Airlines'  
pilots union more than $45 million -- nearly all of its assets -- for 
an illegal sickout that led to the cancellation of more than 6,700 
flights earlier this year. U.S. District Court Judge Joe Kendall 
had previously held the Allied Pilots Association in contempt after 
it initially refused his back-to-work order. American Airlines 
claimed the 10-day sickout cost it $50 million. 

</P>
<P>
	Japan Stocks Open Higher  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese share prices opened higher on Friday. The  
Nikkei rose 27.23 points to 16,754.31 in early trading. In New York 
on Thursday, the Dow industrials gained 51.06 to 10,462.72 to close 
at a fourth-straight record high. 

</P>
<P>
	Ottawa Fans Salute The Great One  
</P>
<P>
	KANATA, Ontario (AP) -- Wayne Gretzky said tonight it would take  
``a miracle'' to change his mind about retiring. ``I told Gordie 
Howe his records were safe unless a miracle happens in the morning 
and I'll probably make it official,'' Gretzky said following the 
New York Rangers' 2-2 tie with the Ottawa Senators. If the game was 
Gretzky's final game in Canada, 18,499 Ottawa fans made sure it was 
memorable. With 4:43 left in the third period and the scored tied 
2-all, the fans began to chant ``One more year.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Clemens Fails To Tie AL Record  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Roger Clemens failed to tie the American League  
record for consecutive wins, getting a no-decision in the New York 
Yankees' game against Baltimore tonight. Clemens fell behind 4-0, 
then wasted leads of 5-4 and 6-5 before leaving with Baltimore 
ahead 7-6 in the top of the fourth. Chuck Knoblauch got Clemens off 
the hook in the bottom of the inning with a sacrifice fly that tied 
the game at 7. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON  

</P>
