<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NFL Draft Booming With Berman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Seventeen hours of name after name, most of them never heard  
before and never to be heard again. Why, then, do so many people 
watch the NFL draft on ESPN? 
</P>
<P>
	Chris Berman is one reason. The Fred Flintstone-lookalike  
sportscaster has found a way to give viewers expert analysis and 
witty entertainment. 
</P>
<P>
	As usual, Berman will be the host of ESPN's 17 hours of draft  
coverage beginning Saturday at noon EDT. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even though the guy hasn't played, he knows as much or more  
than guys who have played or coached. He's a jack of all trades,'' 
said former Bills quarterback Jim Kelly, who makes his NFL draft 
debut Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Things may have changed since ESPN first televised the event 20  
years ago, but its most famous face and voice has not -- and that's 
partly why he's become a sports icon. 
</P>
<P>
	``He hasn't changed at all,'' said George Grande, who anchored  
ESPN's first seven NFL drafts. ``Chris, along with most of us who 
started with ESPN, is just like the fans out there. He's one of 
their own and I think everyone portrayed it like he was one of them 
sitting up there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1979, after the NFL owners unanimously rejected the idea of  
allowing ESPN to televise the draft, the fledgling cable network 
eventually persuaded the league to go ahead with a cut-down 
version. 
</P>
<P>
	The result: An audience too small to be measured.  
</P>
<P>
	In 1984, the event grew to an 0.6 rating and was watched in  
178,000 homes. Last year, it had a 3.1 rating and was seen in more 
than 2.3 million households. 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, Berman will be the traffic cop once again, making  
certain that everything goes smoothly from the 27 teams the network 
hooks up with cameras or reporters. He'll also find ample 
opportunities to poke fun at draft guru Mel Kiper Jr., and make his 
own predictions. 
</P>
<P>
	``I dread it in some ways because it's the hardest thing I do in  
the course of the year,'' Berman said. ``I'm not talking about the 
10 hours on Saturday, I'm talking about getting up to speed. It's 
like cramming for an exam, or announcing a game that goes into 10 
overtimes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Berman is more surprised by his personal rise to success than  
that of the draft telecast. Even though the network began airing 
the event at 8 a.m. EDT for the first few years, he wasn't 
concerned. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm really not shocked at all that it's grown like it has  
because this was a happening waiting to happen,'' he said. ``Pro 
football is just that big. ... For me, it's just sports. I didn't 
do a liver transplant or something important. I'm just delivering 
sports and trying to enhance the enjoyment of it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Berman can't really imagine being anywhere else except at the  
NFL draft this time of year. But the man who few in the business 
utter a bad word about says he does have a game plan for when he 
leaves the business. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to own the concession and drive the beverage cart at  
Pebble Beach,'' he said. ``I could see myself doing that in 10 
years -- But I'd have to get free tee times.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *NOT IN MY CLASS:* Kelly was one of the quarterbacks in the  
famed 1983 draft that also included John Elway and Dan Marino. But 
it's not fair to compare this year's rich QB crop to that group -- 
yet. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's hard to judge these guys right now, but the Class of '99  
has better athletes,'' Kelly said. ``Most of us were pocket 
passers. In terms of pure talent, there is no comparison. There 
will never be a class like that again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kelly has been studying tapes of each of this year's quarterback  
candidates and has his own rating system based on footwork, reading 
coverages, passing accuracy and arm strength. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I had to rate the quarterbacks overall, Donovan McNabb  
would be No. 1,'' he said. ``Then I like Cade McNown, Tim Couch and 
Akili Smith. I don't think anyone will go wrong picking Couch, but 
he doesn't have a very strong arm.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *TUBE BITS:* CNBC begins the inaugural American Le Mans Series  
Sunday from Road Atlanta at 3 p.m. EDT. ... ESPN will televise up 
to 64 NHL playoff games beginning with a Wednesday doubleheader on 
ESPN2. ... Fox Sports Net will air a high school national title 
football game in December of 2000, based on season-long rankings 
compiled along with Student Sports, Inc. ... HBO's ``Real Sports'' 
examines the $4 billion trade in counterfeit golf clubs in the 
United States, Tuesday at 10 p.m. ... Lawrence Taylor is No. 40 on 
ESPN's ``SportsCentury'' list. ... CBS has signed a deal with 
Raycom to show nine ACC college basketball games next season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
