<DOCNO> APW19990415.0325 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 07:45:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> WNBA, Union Settle Labor Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The WNBA and its players accomplished what the  
NBA and its players couldn't do, avoid a lockout. 
</P>
<P>
	The WNBA and the newly formed players union assured a smooth  
start to their season by agreeing to a four-year collective 
bargaining agreement Wednesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been a long process, but well worth it,'' said Pam  
Wheeler, the chief negotiator for the WNBA Players' Association. 
``It's a milestone for women's sports. We wanted to ensure whatever 
foundation we lay can catapult women's professional basketball for 
the future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both sides compromised on the most contentious issues -- salaries  
and health benefits, incoming players from the defunct ABL, and 
guaranteed contracts. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was very much our desire not to disrupt what we had  
created,'' WNBA commissioner Val Ackerman said. ``What we produced 
together reflects a spirit of compromise so we can continue to 
build on the incredible foundation and fan base we've developed 
together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The preliminary agreement, expected to be ratified by the 122  
players on Monday, included increases in the minimum salary from 
$15,000 to $30,000 for veterans and $25,000 for rookies. Those 
figures rise to $40,000 and $30,000, respectively, by 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	The benefits package includes year-round health and dental  
benefits, pension, maternity benefits and life insurance. The 
contract is expected to be formalized by April 22. 
</P>
<P>
	``Getting year-round health insurance was huge and made up for  
not getting a bigger starting salary,'' said Washington, a lawyer 
and guard on the New York Liberty. ``These are minimums, and 
players can negotiate their salaries.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Player salaries had been determined by where they landed in the  
draft. Now players can negotiate increases based on merit. In 
addition, their contracts, which were not guaranteed, will be 
secure at the midpoint of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	The 10 current WNBA teams will be limited to three players from  
the ABL, while the expansion teams in Orlando and Minnesota will be 
allowed five ex-ABL players. 
</P>
<P>
	The restriction will be in effect for only one year.  
</P>
<P>
	Washington said ABL limit was a ``loyalty issue,'' meant to  
reward WNBA players who passed up the channce at substantial ABL 
salaries to sign with the league. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have no animosity toward the ABL players,'' she said. ``A  
number of them are Olympians or All-Americans. They will help make 
the WNBA a more competitive and stronger league.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The league plans to add four new teams in 2000 with no limits on  
ABL players. 
</P>
<P>
	Washington said the turning point in negotiations came on Sunday  
when the league decided to bend on two issues. 
</P>
<P>
	``The league came up on the salary -- that was huge -- and was  
willing to compromise on the ABL issue. Once we hammered out those 
two issues ... it had a snowball effect, and we compromised on the 
other issues,'' said Washington.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although they did not receive a percentage of the league's  
basketball related income, players will receive a percentage of 
royalties from merchandise that use their name and likeness. The 
percentage is 40 percent the first year, with increases to 50 
percent in years three and four of the contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Washington thanked Billy Hunter, the executive director of the  
NBA players union, Patrick Ewing, Mitch Richmond and Juwan Howard 
for their support during the bargaining process. 
</P>
<P>
	``They provided valuable assistance,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	Sue Wicks of the New York Liberty said the minimum salary will  
continue to be an issue at the bargaining table. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a small step forward and we have a lot of years to take  
steps forward,'' Wicks said in a telephone interview from 
Strasbourg, France, where top American players earn six-figures for 
playing on a pro team. ``I'm sure in five years it will be a great 
place to play and it will be very lucrative for the WNBA.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The pre-draft camp opens Friday in Chicago, a day later than  
originally scheduled. The 10-week season begins June 10. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
