<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Airlines Gets More Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANILA, Philippines (AP) -- The government's corporate watchdog  
rejected Philippine Airlines' revised rehabilitation plan on 
Thursday, saying it was ``fraught with generalities'' and its 
earnings forecasts were unclear. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Securities and Exchange Commission gave the ailing  
airline until May 4 to improve the plan, extending Thursday's 
deadline for SEC approval. 
</P>
<P>
	In a highly critical assessment, the SEC said the plan was  
``substantially lacking'' in detail on key issues. 
</P>
<P>
	It said the new deadline was final, and warned that the airline  
will close if it cannot find investors to provide $200 million in 
exchange for new stock in the airline company -- a key element of 
the plan. 
</P>
<P>
	SEC Chairman Perfecto Yasay said PAL failed to identify any new  
investors by the Thursday deadline. 
</P>
<P>
	PAL, which owes more than $2.2 billion to around 9,000  
creditors, said it was surprised by the SEC's decision and remains 
convinced it will find someone to provide the money. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're in very serious discussions with potential investors,''  
said Peter Foster, the airline's chief adviser. ``We believe we're 
on track.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said he could not disclose the names because of  
confidentiality agreements. 
</P>
<P>
	PAL has set its own deadline of June 4 to come up with the fresh  
equity, which would give the new investors a 90 percent stake in 
the airline. 
</P>
<P>
	PAL submitted a revised rehabilitation plan to the SEC last  
month. The plan has already been conditionally approved by the 
airline's major creditors -- a consortium of European financial 
institutions and the U.S. Export-Import Bank -- owed two-thirds of 
the total debt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
