<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 18:43:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing Beats Earnings Estimates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Boeing Co. earnings rebounded to $469 million  
during the first quarter as the company's commercial aircraft 
division showed healthy returns for the first time in more than a 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	The results announced Thursday were well above financial  
analysts' estimates and boosted Boeing's stock price by nearly 10 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing had per-share earnings of 50 cents during the quarter,  
compared with a profit of just $50 million, or 5 cents a share, a 
year earlier, when the company was struggling with massive 
production problems and aircraft delays and took a $219 million 
loss on its new-generation 737 jetliner program. 
</P>
<P>
	The results surpassed the 43 cents predicted in a survey of  
analysts by First Call Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	First-quarter revenue rose 11 percent to $14.39 billion from  
$12.95 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing lost $178 million in 1997 and had depressed earnings of  
$1.1 billion last year. Boeing chairman and CEO Phil Condit, who 
caught much of the fire for Boeing's poor performance, said it was 
gratifying to see his company doing better. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've had two quarters now that show improving results,'' said  
Phil Condit, Boeing's chairman and chief executive officer. 
``Everything I see says we are turning.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Analyst Peter Jacobs with Ragen MacKenzie Inc. in Seattle said,  
``considering how bad the problems have been, this quarter 
certainly demonstrates that at least the worst of the problems are 
behind them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The results sent Boeing stock up $3.69 to $41.69 a share on the  
New York Stock Exchange and helped the Dow Jones industrial average 
reach its fourth-straight closing high, 10,462.72. 
</P>
<P>
	Condit said all three operating units -- commercial airplanes,  
military aircraft and missiles, and space and communications -- 
contributed to a solid first quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	The commercial airplane segment had operating earnings of $382  
million, up from just $23 million a year earlier, when Boeing was 
struggling with production line snarls, parts shortages and delays 
in bringing out the new 737s. Revenues from commercial jets were 
$9.8 billion, up $1.7 billion from first-quarter 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing delivered 148 commercial jets during the quarter, 40 more  
than the same period a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Deborah Hopkins, Boeing's chief financial officer, said that  
while commercial aircraft managed an operating margin of 3.9 
percent in the first quarter, that figure is expected to fall to 
between 2 percent and 3 percent for the rest of 1999 and 2000 
because of the models of aircraft being delivered and the deals 
struck with airlines. 
</P>
<P>
	``It happened that our first quarter had a very rich mix of  
products as well as deals that had less concessions than in the 
second, third, and fourth quarters'' of 1999, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Delta Air Lines announced Thursday it would indefinitely defer  
deliveries of four new Boeing 777 jets because of labor problems, 
taking instead smaller 767-300s. Although 767s sell for around $30 
million less than 777s, Condit said the change would not 
significantly affect Boeing's bottom line. 
</P>
<P>
	The military aircraft and missile segment had operating revenues  
of $3 billion in the first quarter, about the same as last year, 
while space and communications had $1.5 billion, $300 million lower 
than a year earlier, due in part to fewer deliveries of Delta II 
rocket boosters. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing plans to deliver 620 jetliners in 1999, and projects  
overall profits for the year at $1.6 billion to $1.8 billion on 
revenues of $58 billion. For 2000, it forecasts 480 jetliner 
deliveries and revenues of about $49 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Condit said he believes the worst of the Asian financial crisis  
is over and that deliveries could be ``flat to potentially slightly 
higher'' in 2001. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
