</P>
<P>
	Mattel Has Loss, Plans Layoffs  
</P>
<P>
	EL SEGUNDO, Calif. (AP) -- Mattel Inc. will lay off 3,000 workers  
and close a number of its plants as part of a restructuring that 
comes as the world's largest toymaker struggles to revive sales and 
profits. Mattel, which is best known Barbie and Hot Wheels, 
reported today a net loss of $17.9 million, or 7 cents per share, 
for the quarter ending March 31. Sales for the quarter were $692 
million, down 2 percent from $705 million. Mattel stock was up 4 
1/16 at 30. 

</P>
<P>
	First Union Profit Down 11 Pct.  
</P>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- First Union Corp. reported an 11 percent  
drop in first-quarter profits today as the nation's sixth-largest 
bank absorbed the cost of buying CoreStates Financial Corp. First 
Union posted net income of $706 million, or 73 cents a share, for 
the first three months of the year, down from $790 million, or 81 
cents a share for the first-quarter last year. 

</P>
<P>
	BankBoston Profits Down 6 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- BankBoston Corp. reported a 6 percent decline in  
profits for the first quarter on higher expenses, fewer short-term 
loans and mutual fund fees in Brazil. The bank on Thursday posted 
net income of $223 million, or 75 cents a share, just 2 cents above 
Wall Street's estimate. BankBoston earned $207 million, or 79 cents 
a share in the first quarter last year. Revenues were $1.23 
billion, up 19 percent from $1.03 billion in the year-ago period. 

</P>
<P>
	Unisys Profit Almost Doubles  
</P>
<P>
	BLUE BELL, Pa. (AP) -- Unisys Corp. nearly doubled its  
first-quarter profit and easily beat Wall Street predictions, 
helped by strong demand for the company's computer services and big 
business machines. Unisys reported on Thursday that it earned 
$111.2 million, or 32 cents a share in the three months ended March 
31. That was up from a profit of $62.7 million, or 14 cents a 
share, in the year-ago quarter. Revenue grew 10 percent to $1.81 
billion from $1.65 billion. 

</P>
<P>
	Deutsche Telekom To Sell More Stock  
</P>
<P>
	BONN, Germany (AP) -- German telecommunications company Deutsche  
Telekom said today it plans to make another share offering by the 
end of June, its second under a privatization begun in late 1996. 
The announcement was coupled with its report that its earnings were 
unchanged in the first quarter -- 1.04 billion marks, or $575 
million, the same as a year ago. The money from the stock sale is 
designed to make Telekom more competitive. 

</P>
<P>
	FCC Makes Phone Bills Clearer  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal regulators approved a plan today  
designed to make all those charges on your monthly phone bill 
easier to understand. The Federal Communications Commission's plan, 
which is backed by the Clinton administration, generally would have 
phone companies reorganize bills to flag new charges and service 
providers, give clear descriptions of all charges and information 
about how to contest them. The plan, adopted in a 4-1 vote, could 
take effect in a few months. Local telephone and long-distance 
companies would have to abide by all of the FCC's provisions, but 
cellular and other wireless companies would have to comply with 
just some. Violations could trigger fines or other penalties. 

</P>
<P>
	Economic Numbers  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Economic numbers:  
</P>
<P>
	Jobless claims: up 14,000 to 316,000  
</P>
<P>
	Tomorrow: Housing starts  
</P>
<P>
	Tomorrow: Industrial production  


</P>
