<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore: Tobacco Targeting the Young </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AKRON, Ohio (AP) -- Tobacco companies are still trying to get  
young people hooked on cigarettes, Vice President Al Gore charged 
at an anti-smoking forum. 
</P>
<P>
	A study commissioned by the Department of Health and Human  
Services said the most heavily advertised cigarette brands -- 
Marlboro, Newport and Camel -- are the most popular among teen-agers 
who smoked last year. 
</P>
<P>
	A separate study for the Campaign for Tobacco-Free Kids said  
children are two and a half times more likely than adults to have 
seen tobacco advertising in the past two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Annual spending on tobacco ads is about $5 billion -- 100 times  
what is spent on anti-smoking messages, Gore said Wednesday at a 
middle school in northeast Ohio. As long as that's the case, ``this 
problem is going to continue to get worse,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republican National Committee accused Gore of hypocrisy.  
</P>
<P>
	``Gore gobbled up at least $16,440 from the tobacco companies'  
PACS just from 1979 until 1990,'' said committee Chairman Jim 
Nicholson. 
</P>
<P>
	Mike Pfeil, a spokesman for Marlboro-maker Philip-Morris, said  
the company has never marketed its products to children. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal study found that 88 percent of 12th-grade smokers  
used the three heavily advertised brands in 1998. Tobacco-Free Kids 
said 75 percent of children and 31 percent of adults indicated they 
had seen tobacco advertising in the previous two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore highlighted the studies in the gymnasium of Roswell Kent  
Middle School. About 100 students wore red and white Campaign for 
Tobacco-Free T-shirts. 
</P>
<P>
	Thirteen-year-old Heather Slusher agreed that Gore's  
anti-smoking message would have a positive effect. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it was just like a teacher, they wouldn't listen to him,''  
she said. ``But it's the vice president.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990415.0333 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 14:46:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Marquee Fight Pits Jones &AMP; Johnson </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Roy Jones Jr. says he cannot resist a challenge.  
</P>
<P>
	Well, the WBC-WBA light heavyweight champion could get one when  
he fights IBF champion Reggie Johnson in a 175-pound title 
unification bout June 5 in the Mississippi Coast Coliseum in 
Biloxi. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the biggest fight of Roy's career, and it's the  
biggest fight of my career,'' the left-handed Johnson (39-5-1, 24 
knockouts) said Thursday. Jones has a 39-1 record, with 33 
knockouts. 
</P>
<P>
	Attending the news conference were some students of PS72 in  
upper Manhattan, and one youngster had a question for Jones. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mr. Jones, in what round do you think you will knock Mr.  
Johnson down?'' the boy asked. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know if it I'll knock him down or not, but from round  
one to round 12, I'll be doing a job on him,'' Jones said. 
</P>
<P>
	The match will be the fourth in a string of HBO-televised fights  
that run will run through July. 
</P>
<P>
	Prince Naseem Hamed of Britain retained the WBO featherweight  
title by stopping Paul Ingle of Britain in the 11th round April 12. 
</P>
<P>
	The next fight will be Oscar De La Hoya's WBC welterweight title  
defense against Oba Carr on May 22 in Las Vegas. It will be 
followed by Felix Trinidad's defense of the IBF welterweight title 
May 29 in San Juan, Puerto Rico, the Jones-Johnson match, a 
heavyweight fight between Michael Grant and Lou Savarese on June 19 
at Madison Square Garden in New York and another bout featuring 
Hamed, on July 17, against an opponent to be chosen. 
</P>
<P>
	Seth Abraham, president of Time Warner Sports, also said that a  
pay-per-view rematch between heavyweight champions Evander 
Holyfield and Lennox Lewis -- who fought to a disputed draw March 13 
-- would be held Nov. 6 or Nov. 13. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're one meeting away,'' Abraham said when asked if the fight  
was made. 
</P>
<P>
	There hasn't been an undisputed light heavyweight champion since  
Michael Spinks relinquished the title in 1985 to successfully 
campaign for the IBF heavyweight championship against Larry Holmes. 
</P>
<P>
	The 30-year-old Jones, a former IBF middleweight and super  
middleweight champion, won the WBC light heavyweight title in 1996, 
lost on a disqualification to Montell Griffin in 1997 and regained 
the title with a first-round knockout of Griffin later that year. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones added the WBA title by outpointing Lou Del Valle last July  
18. 
</P>
<P>
	The 32-year-old Johnson won the WBA light heavyweight title in  
1992 and lost it in 1993. After failing twice to regain it, he 
became IBF champion by knocking out William Guthrie in the fifth 
round Feb. 6, 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990415.0334 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 14:46:02 </DATE_TIME>
