<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 15:48:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kosovo could cost US $1 billion a month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The U.S. share of NATO's air campaign against  
Yugoslavia cost roughly $600 million in the first three weeks and 
could run over $1 billion a month to sustain, congressional budget 
analysts said as the Clinton administration worked to complete a 
multibillion-dollar emergency request. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican leaders told the administration to make the package  
more than the $4 billion that the Pentagon has suggested to pay for 
the war and for humanitarian relief through September. 
Congressional officials close to the process said they expected the 
administration request to be at least $5 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a stretching thin of our overall capacity,'' House  
Appropriations Committee Chairman Rep. C.W. Bill Young, R-Fla., 
told Secretary of State Madeleine Albright at a hearing Thursday. 
``We have to do more than just replace the bullets and the 
missiles.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Whatever the final cost, it appears likely that Congress will  
agree to take it out of the new-found budget surplus rather than 
tap into other hard-pressed accounts 
</P>
<P>
	The Congressional Budget Office said its report that the air war  
had cost $600 million so far and would cost $1 billion for each 
additional month it is sustained did not include humanitarian aid, 
or certain procurement costs, such as replacing the F117 
``stealth'' fighter that was lost. That aircraft is no longer being 
manufactured. 
</P>
<P>
	CBO Director Dan Crippen said that sending in ground troops -- an  
option the administration says it is not currently considering -- 
could cost another $200 million a month, assuming a force of one 
heavy division with support, or about 27,000 troops. 
</P>
<P>
	Young, Senate Appropriations Committee Chairman Ted Stevens,  
R-Alaska, and other congressional leaders met later Thursday with 
White House budget director Jack Lew to discuss the 
administration's request, but no final figures were announced. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're very close,'' Lew told reporters after the session.  
</P>
<P>
	Stevens said he had hoped to be able to take the administration  
request with him to study this weekend when he and other 
congressional leaders fly to the Balkans to speak to U.S. troops 
and to NATO headquarters in Brussels. But he suggested that now 
seemed unlikely. The congressional delegation leaves Friday 
morning. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked what the final price tag on the administration request  
would be, Stevens said, ``it depends on whether they take our 
advice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And, clearly, the GOP advice was for more, not less.  
</P>
<P>
	Republicans suggested they might try to amend the measure to  
provide for longer-term needs for the Defense Department. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., even suggested that  
the Senate might attach to the measure the across-the-board 4.8 
percent military pay increase that was approved but not funded by 
the Senate in February. The pay and benefit increase would cost $7 
billion over the next five years, more than a smaller pay increase 
planned by the administration. 
</P>
<P>
	House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., urged the administration  
to make a ``realistic appraisal of what this is going to cost.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Young and other Republicans told Albright they were afraid that  
in moving aircraft and even an aircraft carrier away from the 
Korean peninsula, the administration was making U.S. troops there 
uneasy, as was moving aircraft to the Balkans region from the 
Persian Gulf area. 
</P>
<P>
	Albright said the administration would do nothing to jeopardize  
troops in South Korea or anywhere else. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, 19 House members complained in a letter to the  
administration that the Pentagon was doing little to replenish 
cruise missiles used in the war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990415.0337 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-15 15:35:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Polaroid Losses Nearly Double </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) -- Polaroid Corp. reported its  
first-quarter loss nearly doubled to $30.8 million as its sales 
declined in several overseas markets. 
</P>
<P>
	The maker of self-developing cameras and film said Thursday its  
loss translated to 70 cents per share and compared with a loss of 
$17.4 million, or 39 cents per share, in the same quarter a year 
ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales declined to $379 million from $391 million in the first  
quarter of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The company, which said the first quarter is traditionally its  
weakest period for revenues and profits, said its operating loss 
narrowed to $6.9 million from $13 million due to cost-cutting. 
</P>
<P>
	Polaroid has lost money in five of the last six years amid  
declining sales. The company attributed the latest decrease in 
sales principally to a drop in orders from Europe and lower sales 
in Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	But Polaroid said sales were strong in Japan, and it reported  
gains in North and South America. U.S. sales rose to $227 million 
from $212 million a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``As we focus on revitalizing core business profitability, we're  
gratified to see strong leading indicators for growth from our new 
products,'' said Gary T. DiCamillo, the company's chairman and 
chief executive officer. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's stock was off 18 3/4 cents at $20.93 3/4 on the New York  
Stock Exchange today. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
