<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ill. Delays Web Marijuana Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) -- Concerns about free speech have  
persuaded a state senator to delay action on a bill that restricts 
using the Internet to transmit information about marijuana. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislation makes it a misdemeanor to use the Internet to  
discuss marijuana or other controlled substances ``knowing that the 
information will be used in furtherance of illegal activity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But an anti-crime group and a pro-marijuana group both  
criticized the bill as an intrusion on free speech. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate sponsor, Republican Duane Noland of Blue Mound, said  
the measure is meant to apply only to people with criminal motives. 
But he acknowledged concerns about ``the vagueness of some 
issues.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I need to do a little work on my bill -- which might be a  
polite way to say I'm not certain about the future of it,'' Noland 
said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Illinois House has approved the measure 114-0, and it awaits  
action in the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	The private anti-crime group Illinois State Crime Commission  
fears the bill could be used to interfere with legitimate efforts 
to provide information about drug problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't like gray areas when it comes to the First Amendment  
because I don't want to be the first test case,'' said Jerry 
Elsner, the commission's executive director. 
</P>
<P>
	What if an ill person were considering smoking marijuana to  
relieve pain, he asked -- would a group break the law by providing 
information about the drug's potential medical benefits? 
</P>
<P>
	Or what if a drug-awareness group listed the latest trends in  
drug use as a service to parents and police? Would the group be 
prosecuted if a teen-ager got the idea to experiment? 
</P>
<P>
	The National Organization for the Reform of Marijuana Laws, or  
NORML, also criticized the idea. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no need for this bill,'' said Paul Armentano, the  
group's director of publications. ``It seems blatantly 
unconstitutional. It seems impossible to enforce.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is HB792.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
