<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Huntsman Now the Chemical King </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Huntsman Corp. became the largest private  
chemical company in the world Thursday with its $2.8 billion 
purchase of four chemical businesses from Imperial Chemical 
Industries of London. 
</P>
<P>
	The family-owned company, which Jon Huntsman founded in Salt  
Lake 1982, nearly doubles its revenue with the acquisition from the 
struggling British company. 
</P>
<P>
	Huntsman expects revenue to grow from $4 billion to $7.5 billion  
per year. The deal gives the Huntsman 7,000 more employees, 
bringing the total to 16,000, and a presence in 34 countries. 
</P>
<P>
	Huntsman will buy ICI's polyurethanes, titanium dioxide,  
aromatics and petrochemical businesses, and has exclusive rights to 
the future purchase of ICI's $800 million acrylics business. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal satisfies one of the Huntsman's long-held goals: to  
build as big a petrochemical empire as possible so he can give it 
away to charity. Listed third among Huntsman's corporate spending 
priorities is: ``Give relief to human suffering.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Huntsman, 61, is a philanthropist who gave $100 million to  
create a cancer institute at the University of Utah and $40 million 
to his alma mater, Wharton Business School, last year. He has 
survived lip and prostate cancer this decade and lost both parents 
to cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Huntsman, a native of Idaho who is perhaps best-known for having  
developed stryrofoam hamburger holders in the 1970s, has built his 
company by buying plastics and petrochemical companies that are 
struggling during down cycles. 
</P>
<P>
	That's also the case with ICI, which had revenues of $15 billion  
in 1998 but has struggled lately in the face of a slipping 
chemicals market. The company had $6.8 billion in debt, but the 
deal with Huntsman knocks that down to $4.5 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Faced with trouble, ICI made plans to restructure and move into  
special chemicals -- which stalled last year, when three major deals 
fell through because agreements could not be reached with the 
Federal Trade Commission. ICI had tried to sell its titanium 
dioxide business to DuPont and NL Industries for $1 billion, and 
its Crosfield unit to W.R. Grace &AMP; Co. for $455 million. 
</P>
<P>
	But in the past three weeks, ICI has managed to sell its  
German-based equipment specialty company to PPG Industries of 
Pittsburgh and its Chase &AMP; Hunt supply enterprise to a management 
buyout team backed by Close Investment Management Ltd. 
</P>
<P>
	ICI's U.S.-listed shares rose $1.12 per share to $42.18 on the  
New York Stock Exchange Thursday afternoon after rising 6 percent 
the day before on the rumor of the impending sale. 
</P>
<P>
	``The businesses which we are selling have leading market  
positions, good management and a strong record of achievement,'' 
said ICI Chief Executive Charles Miller Smith. ``We couldn't be 
more confident about this transaction and strongly believe the 
customers and employees will prosper under Huntsman ownership.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It will also be Huntsman's first foray into polyurethane, which  
is used for building insulation, furniture cushioning, carpet 
backing and bedding, and titanium dioxide, a white pigment used to 
make paint, paper and plastics. ICI's titanium dioxide business has 
about a 14 percent share of the world market. 
</P>
<P>
	Huntsman will own 70 percent of a new company, Huntsman ICI  
Holdings, being set up to complete the acquisitions. ICI will own 
30 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement is subject to approval by the Federal Trade  
Commission, but no problems are foreseen and it is expected to be 
completed this summer, said Huntsman spokesman Don Olsen. 
</P>
<P>
	The sale also gives Huntsman ICI's position in global joint  
ventures in Japan, South Africa and Louisiana. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Huntsman is headquartered in Salt Lake, it has no  
production facilities here. Six of Huntsman's sons and three 
sons-in-law all work for the company. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
